<HEADLINE>Ton-up Carson</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WHITE AND GOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764931</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WILLIE Carson reached 100 winners for the twenty-third season in the
last 25 when he partnered Muktabas to victory yesterday at Nottingham.
Fittingly, the winner carried the colours of his retaining owner,
Hamdan al Maktoum, when scoring by threequarters-of-a-length in the
'Childrens Day' Conditions Stakes.
The 52-year-old was cheered into the winner's enclosure and was
presented with a bottle of champagne to mark his achievement.
Carson failed to hit a century in 1984 when he missed part of the
season after a heavy fall in Milan and he registered only 87 successes
last year.
But the Scot, at present fourth in the jockeys' table, has reached
three figures consistently otherwise since he first achieved the feat in
1971.
He has no immediate plans for retirement, particularly with Alhaarth
currentlyclear favourite to clinch him a fifth Derby triumph next June.
</TEXT>
