<HEADLINE>Champions of the sunshine island are determined to make it hot for the men from Ibrox. Cypriots quietly confident of causing an upset</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976764932</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
With Famagusta
CLOUDS of dust billow up around your feet as you cross the bare,
parched patch of land outside the Antonis Papadopoulous Stadium. It
would be completely featureless were it not for the wrecked cars which
have been abandoned there.
It is to be hoped the European dreams of Rangers are not to be added
to the pile of broken things come tomorrow night.
Already the Ibrox side's supporters are gathering -- approximately
1000 are to make the trip to Cyprus where their number is expected to
swell to 2500 when joined by fans serving in the British Army stationed
here and also Scottish tourists -- and just for a moment it seemed as
though Paul Gascoigne had arrived in Larnaca ahead of his team-mates for
the conclusion of Rangers' European Cup preliminary-round tie against
the Cypriot champions, Anorthosis Famagusta.
Perhaps Gascoigne was so anxious about the return leg that he had come
to familiarise himself with the humble ground, but on closer inspection
the figure turned out to be one of those ridiculous look-alikes with the
cropped, bleached hair. This one was wearing a T-shirt, across which was
emblazoned the declaration: ''I'm back'' above a photograph of the one
and only Gazza.
The groundsmen looked bewildered by the creature in their midst who
was casually strolling across the pitch, which will do Gascoigne and the
rest of Walter Smith's team no favours. The surface is baked and solid
and is far from smooth, which means there will be an element of chance
when long passes are played.
It is a tight pitch with basic concrete structures and scaffolding and
rickety wooden grandstands. They will house 13,000 supporters tomorrow
night when, thankfully, the temperature will have dropped from 38[DEG]
to 25.
Anorthosis played a Croatian team in a UEFA Cup tie here two years ago
when the game kicked off at 2pm and with the sun still high. The
Cypriots scored six times against opponents who could barely stand at
the end, but the heat should not be too much of a factor this time,
which is just as well because Rangers might need to concentrate hard
when they arrive at the ground.
''When the game starts and everyone is in the ground this can be a
very noisy, passionate place,'' said club spokesman Lakis Avraamides.
''These fans are committed and they believe they are coming to see
Anorthosis win the biggest match they have played in.''
The stadium, built seven years ago mostly by volunteer, refugee
labour, sits in the Kokkines area of Larnaca, which was set aside for
those who fled the Turkish soldiers in 1974, and before and during the
game it will be patrolled by the Cypriot police and also the military
police from the British Army bases.
''We do not, however, expect trouble,'' said Avraamides, who was
caught up in frantic telephone calls to the electricity authorities. The
power supply had been cut off for some reason and preparatory work in
the stadium had ground to a halt.
''Don't worry. It will be different tomorrow and it will be alive when
the game starts,'' he added.
Unimpressed, Gascoigne's double was gone before Georgi Vassilev
brought his players out for a late afternoon training session -- just as
well since Ilian Kiriakove might have tackled the wrong Gazza, although
the Bulgarian said: ''I am not sure if the coach wants me to do follow
Gascoigne again. He may want me to be more creative, I don't know yet.''
Dimitris Assiotis, who missed the game at Ibrox because of injury, is
fit and has taken full part in the build-up work, and he might win back
his place from Panikos Poynas, who supported Kiriakov in taking care of
Gascoigne. Vassilev will later reveal which of these defenders will
start. Yesterday he was concentrating on his attack.
''I was pleased with the way we played at Ibrox, but I would have
liked Sinima Gogic and Nikolai Todorov to have made more of the chances
we created,'' he said. ''But we know we can make chances against Rangers
and I'm sure we will have scoring opportunities again.''
Gogic, who is one of the highest-paid players in Cypriot football,
although his #4000 a month is paltry compared to what Rangers' players
earn, is regarded as the star of the team, and the supporters are
convinced he will not let them down.
''This is such a big game for all of us and we know we have a chance
to do something that a Cypriot club could never have contemplated only a
few years ago,'' Gogic said. ''To beat Rangers and play in the
Champions' League would be a huge triumph.''
The 32-year-old knows he should have scored on a couple of occasions
at Ibrox, but he shrugged and added: ''There are always other chances
for strikers. Wednesday perhaps.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
