<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Durie can be a shot in the arm for Rangers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976764933</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
With Rangers
THE worst weekend fears of Rangers manager Walter Smith were realised
yesterday morning when Brian Laudrup failed a fitness test at Ibrox and
was left behind when the team departed for Cyprus.
Now the Scottish champions must face Anorthosis Famagusta without the
man who was their most influential player last season, a player who
could have been looked on as a potential match winner in Cyprus.
''We wanted to see how Brian was this morning before travelling,''
said Smith. ''There has been very little improvement to his injury and
there's no point in having him with us.
''It's much better for him to stay at home, avoid a five-hour flight,
and receive treatment to the ankle at home.''
It was a blow Rangers had feared since Laudrup was injured in training
for Denmark before his country's European Championship clash in Armenia
last week.
And it was the kind of injury problem which forces Gordon Durie into a
situation where he may have to go through the pain barrier to help the
Ibrox club in their European Champions' League bid.
It is not a prospect that Durie welcomes, and not one he would always
accept. But to help his club overcome Famagusta, Durie will do so if the
club medical staff believe it necessary.
He said so yesterday as Rangers jetted to the torrid sunshine of
Cyprus.
Durie pointed out: ''This game is so important for all of us that I
will take an injection if the manager and the doctor say I should do so.
It isn't something I would always want to do. But this game is so vital
for everyone connected with the club.
''We know that we let ourselves and the supporters down last season
when we were expected to defeat AEK. We don't want a repeat of that
now.''
Durie's goal gave Rangers their 1-0 victory at Ibrox in the first leg.
It remains the goal which can carry the Scottish champions into the
next, lucrative stage of the tournament.
Rangers desperately want to be in the Champions' League next month and
Durie insists: ''People have been acting as if we had lost the first
match. But we didn't. We won 1-0 and it was always more important that
we did not lose a goal to them at Ibrox.
''There is a lot of pressure on clubs in the preliminary games. I
believe it is easier to play in the Champions' League itself. Getting
there is the hardest thing.''
Rangers, of course, go into this game with several injury worries --
hence the probable need for playing Durie even if an injection is
required.
The player says: ''I am running okay, and I have been working in the
gym, so general fitness is not a problem. I just have this pain in my
left foot from a knock I had in the first leg. But I'll be ready for
this one.''
That decision will be made closer to the match along with similar
decisions over Alan McLaren and Stuart McCall.
Manager Smith is likely to give them as much time as possible to be
ready.
Laudrup is a major loss as Durie agrees. ''All of us hoped that Brian
would be ready because he is a player who could have won the matches for
us,'' said Durie.
''However, we still have quality players available to come in. The
gaffer has been buying class players to provide cover in situations like
this. In the game itself I think they will come at us in the first 20
minutes. If we survive that opening burst, then we can frustrate them
and we will find gaps for ourselves.
''I don't think any of us doubt that we have the players who can score
away from home in Europe. We have done that in the past. This is a bit
of a tightrope for them because if we score, they must know their
chances are over.''
It is that away goal which haunts the Cypriot champions.
The man who marked Paul Gascoigne at Ibrox, Bulgarian World Cup player
Ilian Kiriakov, admits as much. ''Just one goal, only for the Scots
would end our dreams,'' says the 28-year-old. ''We would then need to
score three times and that would be very, very difficult. Probably
impossible.''
Kiriakov, however, is ready to battle with Gascoigne in the midfield
once more, in a role with which he is unfamiliar.
He shrugs: ''It was a job the coach asked me to do. Normally I play
full back but he wanted Gascoigne man marked, and told me to do it. I
think I won the battle in Glasgow and I want to repeat that this time.
''Gascoigne is one of the biggest names in Europe but I believe I can
mark him as effectively this time as I did before.
''Our only problem is if we concede a goal. Rangers know that too.
That is why Smith's strategy for the game will call for an organised,
disciplined defence, but with players who will look for the breakaways
that are always available to any team playing away from home in a
European competition.
''The strikers who are here will recognise that need. They will also
recognise that the increased competition at the club means they must be
ready to do something special, particularly here.''
Grins Durie: ''We all know that the competition up front is very
difficult. Mark and Ally are still there, still scoring. I want to be
involved and now the gaffer has brought Oleg Salenko. We cannot afford
to let our standards slip, otherwise we will be out. But that is only
good for the club.''
How good it is we may find out in Larnaca tomorrow night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
