<HEADLINE>Plans could soon be in play</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764934</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PLANS for the formation of an association to represent the interests
of Scotland's 70 national league rugby sides are at an advanced stage,
and a meeting of all interested clubs will be staged in Perth next week.
The new association, to be called the Scottish Rugby Clubs'
Association, will perform virtually the same functions as the
three-year-old Premier League Clubs' Association which represents 25 of
the 32 clubs in the Tennents Premiership -- the seven Border League
clubs still declining to become involved.
The fact that many clubs feel the need for an organisation which is
devoted to their interests reflects feelings expressed at the Scottish
Rugby Union annual general meeting in June that the SRU was becoming
remote from the clubs.
At that meeting, retiring president Ken Smith declared that there was
no need for additional organisations to represent the clubs, and that
the SRU's district apparatus was the forum through which concerns within
the clubs could be expressed.
That view was underlined yesterday by SRU chief executive Bill Hogg,
who said: ''We don't see that there is any requirement for additional
associations but neither do we see a problem with it if that is what the
clubs want. The premier league clubs already have their association and,
by that token, there is no reason why the national league sides
shouldn't have one as well.''
All national league sides now have received a letter from Linlithgow
RFC president Ian Gibson inviting them to attend an exploratory meeting
at Perthshire RFC club on August 30.
Among the other clubs involved in the formation of the new
organisation are Cartha Queen's Park, Leith, Forrester FP,
Hillhead-Jordanhill, Annan, Allan Glen's, and Livingston.
The new Scottish Rugby Clubs' Association is envisaged as a national
organisation with threeregional components -- Lothian and Borders, North
and Midlands, and West.
''There is a general feeling that the new league structure will create
a club elite and the other clubs, who often provide the players for
them, want to be listened to as well,'' said Gibson.
''The meeting has been called for next week and if nobody turns up
then the concept won't happen but, if it does, then I don't see it as
being a rival to the SRU. We would be very much a self-help group.
</TEXT>
