<HEADLINE>Flight into unknown for Raith</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764937</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RAITH Rovers were today recovering from a catalogue of disasters which
has disrupted preparations for tonight's UEFA Cup tie with Gotu
Itrottarfelag.
First, the club was forced to change airlines -- and endure an 11-hour
delay -- for their flight to the Faroes, as the original company did not
have a pilot who was qualified to land on the island.
Then bad weather around the Faroes delayed the departure even further.
The situation was further exacerbated by the fact that the club also
faced a hefty fine from UEFA, as competition rules demand that they are
in the host country 24 hours before kick-off.
The first problem cropped up at lunchtime on Friday, when Titan
Airlines faxed the club to say that they had been denied landing
permission at Vagar Airport because their pilot didn't hold a special
licence qualifying him to touchdown at the cliff-top airfield.
The Coca-Cola Cup holders, who kick off against GI in the second leg
of their preliminary round tie at 6.30 this evening, quickly fixed up a
flight with another airline -- but it wasn't due to leave Edinburgh
until eight o'clock last night.
Worse followed when the airline called Stark's Park at lunchtime
yesterday to report that, because of heavy fog around the Faroes, the
plane wouldn't leave until 11.55 -- and wasn't expected to touch down at
Vagar until 2.30.
But there was some good news for Rovers when a spokesman for UEFA
revealed that they would not be punished for their late arrival. He
said: ''This matter has been discussed by the committee and it has been
decided not to fine Raith Rovers.
''This is because the club contacted us very quickly to let us know
about the difficulties they were having. We recognise the Faroes is a
very difficult and awkward place to get to.
''We also know that there will be no further problems and are happy
with the new travel arrangements.
''It is fair to say their prompt action in reporting the matter has
helped them escape any financial punishment.''
Raith manager Jimmy Nicholl said: ''When I discovered we wouldn't
arrive until the day of the game I thought we would be thrown out.
''My first move was to phone Andy Roxburgh at UEFA and he spoke to
match secretary Rene Eberle, who said not to worry because they had had
problems with the Faroes before.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
