<HEADLINE>Aitken's warning to fit-again Booth</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BROADLEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976764938</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SUCH is the determination of Roy Aitken to restore the fortunes of
Aberdeen that he could threaten the place of Scott Booth who had scored
twice in his return from injury after an eight-month absence.
Booth, who sustained that injury while scoring in the draw against
Russia which sustained hopes of a place in the European Championship
finals, had, not unnaturally, hoped his feat might attract the attention
of Craig Brown.
Instead, his Pittodrie manager warned: ''Strikers are there to score
goals. That's what I expect of them. I'm delighted Booth and Billy Dodds
got among the goals in our first game. But I'll have Duncan Shearer
available after Saturday and he will be breathing down their necks. It
is healthy to have such competition in attack and this is what I want in
every department.
''Booth is a proven goalscorer who has the capabilities to do well in
the international arena.
''If he gets it right with Aberdeen then obviously he will bring
himself to Craig Brown's notice and get into contention with Scotland.
But he's got to produce his best form consistently.''
Aitken is committed to ensuring there will be no repeat of last season
when the Pittodrie club required a play-off to save their premier place.
He has promised that players must maintain their standards or they will
be axed from his plans.
However, he was full of praise for the the competitive debut of
teenage defender Craig Ireland and promised: ''There are first-team
places waiting for any youngster who convinces me he is worthy of a
call-up. Ireland is a hungry, willing lad with a lot still to learn. But
he has the desire to do well and that is what I'm looking for.''
Injured defenders Gary Smith and Colin Woodthorpe re-started training
yesterday and should be ready for Falkirk on Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
