<HEADLINE>Mission improbable in bid to retrieve Scottish pride but... Ambitions still lurking within Fir Park men</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976764940</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
'We can't play any worse than we did that night. In fact, I think we
will do an awful lot better this time.' DOUGIE ARNOTT
MOTHERWELL'S Tristar trek to Finland as they try boldly to do what no
Scots team has done before was surprisingly upbeat despite the 3-1
deficit they face from the first leg of their UEFA Cup preliminary round
tie.
No team from Scotland has ever recovered from defeat at home in the
first leg of a European tie and it is long odds against the Fir Park
side being pioneers in this department.
However, at least the squad who flew to Helsinki then made the 75-mile
road journey to their base in Kouvola were in positive, albeit
realistic, mood. The feeling that an aggregate victory is too much to
expect is tacitly conceited but the belief that some Scottish pride can
be retrieved is unanimously held.
After that, the most used phrase is: ''Who knows?''
Unfortunately, the answer probably is ''everybody'' but such cynicism
is not likely to encourage the kind of ambition that lurks in Motherwell
breasts.
Manager Alex McLeish's view that MyPA-47 will have to play badly to
allow his own team any serious chance of going into the first round is
as honest an appraisal as you could expect in the circumstances. His
players would like to think that they could become unique by achieving
what seems well nigh impossible but a win of any sort is perhaps the
only target worth contemplating.
Even that may be very difficult against a team that looked, at the
least, competent at Fir Park.
Certainly, the presence of Dougie Arnott, who was under suspension for
the first leg, will lend a different dimension to the Scottish team's
attack. His darting, annoying energy could test the composure of the
Finnish defence.
Arnott suffered in the stand, along with the rest of us a fortnight
ago and can scarcely wait to put his boots on. He, too, was brutally
honest.
''One thing is for sure,'' he said. ''We can't play any worse than we
did that night. In fact, I think we will do an awful lot better this
time.
''For some reason we played a long ball game all night and that is
just not us. We will be doing it differently tomorrow.
''Our big hope is that they will take it easy, thinking the job is
done, and if we get an early goal, who knows?
''Realistically, we lost the tie at Fir Park but we will have a real
go here and take it from there.''
McLeish would go along with that view. But what he wants as much as
anything is to see his team as they can be.
He was upset that they allowed the ever present impatience of Scottish
fans to get to them in the first leg.
''I know how the fans felt and if I had been one of them I would have
been snarling, too,'' he said. ''But players have to handle that and
stick to the game plan, I want to see us passing the ball as we can. If
we do that I believe, as I have from the start, that we can win here.
But the Finns are an above-average side and are full of confidence.''
That was borne out by their manager, Harri Kampman, and defender Sami
Hyypia, both of whom said the usual diplomatic bits but clearly are
utterly convinced their team will go through.
''We have no injury problems and are in good form, after winning 3-0
on Saturday,'' said the manager.
For Hyypia the chance to stake his claim for a place in the Finnish
team against Scotland next month is his incentive to do well tonight.
The under-21 defender, who also has six full caps to his name,
believes that if he subdues such as Tommy Coyne again he would do his
prospects a lot of good, especially as the places in the Finnish side
are open following the nation's 6-0 defeat by Russia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
