<HEADLINE>Manager likely to be in hot water</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976764941</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUNDEE United manager Billy Kirkwood yesterday refused to comment on
the weekend incident at Cowdenbeath which is likely to land him in
trouble with the Scottish Football Association.
Kirkwood was involved in a row with rival manager Tom Steven at the
end of United's 4-0 Coca-Cola Cup win.
Later, Steven gave his version of the incident, revealing that it had
been sparked by a challenge by United's Billy McKinlay on one of his
players.
Kirkwood would not discuss the incident, although it is understood he
is angry at having become involved.
The SFA still have to receive their report from match referee Tom
Brown and the supervisor who was present but it seems certain that both
Kirkwood and Steven will be called to explain their actions.
Meanwhile, although Dundee manager Jim Duffy was delighted with Neil
McCann's four-goal show in the victory over East Stirlingshire, he
wasn't happy to read reports saying that the under-21 internationalist
still was a Celtic target.
Duffy said: ''These reports have been going on for more than a year.
The fact is that Celtic made a general inquiry and that is all that has
happened as far as we are concerned.
''But we have had formal bids for the player from other clubs.
''For instance, everyone knows we have turned down two offers from
Luton Town.
''Based on that, it would be more appropriate to describe him as a
Luton target.
''This could get more ridiculous. Would people still describe him as a
Celtic target if he happened to sign for Liverpool?''
One man staying at Dens, at least for the time being, is midfield
player Morten Wieghorst, who has renewed a one-month contract with the
club.
Defender Dusan Vrto could accept a fresh one-month deal when he meets
Duffy this morning.
Dundee will play their third-round Coca-Cola Cup tie against
Kilmarnock next Wednesday night at Dens Park.
United will meet Motherwell at Tannadice 24 hours earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000013</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000013</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Munro tells his men to keep cool</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976764942</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FEELINGS could run high tonight as Lanarkshire rivals Airdrie and
Hamilton clash in their opening tie in the Scottish League Challenge
Cup.
Hamilton are still upset by a transfer tribunal decision last week
that awarded them only #135,000 for striker Peter Duffield, who moved
under freedom of contract.
But manager Iain Munro will emphasise to his players that this should
not concern them and that their job is to win on the pitch.
Airdrie are intent on retaining the trophy they won last year when the
tournament was known as the B and Q Cup.
Assistant manager John McVeigh said yesterday: ''We do not intend to
give up our hold on the trophy lightly. We know the benefits of a good
run in this competition, for, last season, we got a spin-off in our
league form.''
Sean Sweeney, a recent buy from Clydebank, will make his debut and
Kenny Black returns after suspension.
Stirling Albion manager Kevin Drinkell knows what it feels like to be
a winner of this tournament as a player and he wants to repeat that
feeling.
Drinkell, as he looked forward to the tie against Queen's Park, said:
''I won a medal when I was a player at Falkirk and would like to repeat
that now as a manager.
The former Ranger could make a couple of changes from the side which
beat Hamilton on Saturday and points out: ''We have a busy programme and
it is important to keep everyone involved.''
Charlie Nicholas will make his home debut for Clyde as they face first
division St Johnstone.
Recent signing Charlie McLean, Steve Florence, and keeper Gordon Dunn
will be included by Arbroath as they visit Clydebank, who will freshen
the side after their penalty kick shoot-out defeat against Motherwell on
Saturday with striker Craig Flannigan in line for a return after injury.
East Stirling manager Billy Little will make a late team selection to
the side who lost six goals to Dundee on Saturday when they face St
Mirren, who again will be without Norrie McWhirter.
</TEXT>
