<HEADLINE>Celtic change date of cup tie</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764943</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH COCA-COLA CUP
CELTIC have switched their Coca-Cola Cup third-round tie against Raith
Rovers at Parkhead to Thursday, August 31.
The match, a repeat of last season's final, is being moved because
there are no games the following Saturday due to Scotland's crucial
European Championship clash with Finland at Hampden on September 6.
A spokesman for the Parkhead club explained that the Scottish League
had given them a choice of playing either on the Tuesday or Thursday.
They opted for the latter date to give players more time to prepare
for the match, which will kick off at 7.45.
Rangers, meanwhile, will play their tie against Stirling Albion the
previous day at Ibrox with a 7.45 kick-off, as will the Falkirk v
Aberdeen encounter. Other ties that night are scheduled for 7.30.
The matches between Dundee United and Motherwell, and Airdrie and
Hibernian both will take place on Tuesday, August 29, at 7.30.
* THE Andrei Kanchelskis transfer saga could finally end this week,
with Everton confident they will eventually get their #5m man.
The Russian international winger has been forced to train alone after
the collapse of his move from Manchester United following the demand for
a #1.1m cut of the fee from his Ukrainian former club, Shaktyor Donetsk.
Kanchelskis is not allowed to train with his would-be Goodison
team-mates while he has refused to return to Old Trafford.
But Everton director Cliff Finch said that behind-the-scenes moves
aimed at salvaging the deal were still proceeding.
''I cannot do any more than I am doing to get that player in a blue
shirt,'' said Finch.
''United have acquiesced in so much as allowing Andrei to train, but
not with us, so he is working on his own at the moment.''
Everton have already asked the Football Association to arbitrate in
the dispute, and FA spokesman Mike Parry said that United had responded.
''We wrote to United last week to inform them that the arbitration
process was underway and we have now had their response,'' he said.
''They acknowledged our letter and said that we would be hearing from
them very shortly.''
Parry added: ''United have already agreed that they will not negotiate
with any other club over the sale of Kanchelskis until the situation
with Everton is resolved.''
