<HEADLINE>Holder Haining off to a comfortable start</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MIKE HAGGERTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764945</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROWING:
UNPERTURBED by a delay to his opening race caused by a technical
problem on the boat of his Cypriot opponent, Peter Haining, Scotland's
world lightweight sculling champion, started the second defence of his
title here in Tampere, Finland, with a comfortable victory, booking a
place in Thursday's semi-finals, despite a sustained challenge from
Thomas Kacovsky of the Czech Republic.
Joining him in the semi-finals is Ireland's Niall O'Toole, last year's
silver medalist, who looks like being Haining's main threat.
This race marked Haining's competitive return to the single this year.
It was the first time he had raced over the championship distance of two
kilometres since his world title win in Indianapolis last year, and was
just the confidence booster he needed. The semi-final will be the first
real test for him here.
Altogether, four of the 13 British boats racing yesterday qualified
for semi-finals, while the lightweight eight, with Scottish
internationalists Jim McNiven and Ben Helm aboard, went straight to
their final, thanks to an impressive victory over Germany and Argentina.
The day started with an exhibition performance by the reigning Olympic
and world champion coxless pair of Steve Redgrave and Matthew Pinsent
who raced at something like full power till the halfway mark, only to
cut back from then on to paddle home in control of their race. Now more
than before they look simply unbeatable here.
All other Scottish internationalists racing yesterday must depend on
tomorrow's repechages. They include Carl MacLannan (second in men's
coxed fours), Gillian Lindsay and Kate Templeton (last in women's
fours), and Kareen Marwick (along with Phillippa Cross (last in women's
pairs).
Also dependent on repechages are Britain's women's eight, with former
Edinburgh University captain Dot Blackie aboard. The three remaining
British boats -- men's eight, lightweight four and lightweight double
scull -- start today.
</TEXT>
