<HEADLINE>Tyson may be rushed into Seldon clash</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764946</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOXING
PRESSURE could be mounting on promoter Don King to thrust Mike Tyson
in with WBA champion Bruce Seldon sooner rather than later. After
Saturday's 89-second fiasco against Irish-American Peter McNeeley at the
MGM Grand, blasted by TV stations across America, the paying public will
want vastly better value for money when Tyson climbs through the ropes
for phase two of his comeback campaign on November 4.
Buster Mathis Jr has signed to fight Tyson on that date, says his
promoter Cedric Kushner, but Tyson's co-manager John Horne has insisted
Mathis was only a ''consideration''. Mathis will probably be seen as
more cannon fodder for the former undisputed world heavyweight champion,
and MGM moguls will hardly want to host another McNeeley-type farce.
MGM will be competing with the Caesars Palace attraction of the
Riddick Bowe-Evander Holyfield third fight, which is due to take place
on the same night just a mile away down The Strip -- unless boxing
business commonsense prevails and one of the heavyweight attractions is
switched.
Seldon could now fit conveniently into the Tyson picture for November
4, or on the next scheduled slot of March 16, and pay-per-view
financiers Showtime will want something several leagues better to beam
nationwide for a #30 fee. Promoted by King and unscathed after his
clinical 10-round demolition of native American Indian Joe Hipp on the
Tyson card, Seldon would be ready -- and definitely willing -- to set
himself up for life by going in against Iron Mike. Seldon boxed Hipp as
if he was holding something back in reserve.
Meanwhile, McNeeley's manager Vinny Vecchione awaits his hearing
before the Nevada State Athletic Commission for the hotly-controversial
ring intrusion which rescued and disqualified McNeeley. The commission
have withheld Vecchione's #119,000 share of McNeeley's purse pending the
inquiry -- cash which Vecchione planned to use to buy his mother's house
from his three brothers.
</TEXT>
