<HEADLINE>A sorry tale of missed chances</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764947</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOCKEY
SCOTLAND contrived only a 1-1 draw against France in the Nissan
European Nations Men's Hockey Cup in Dublin yesterday in the penultimate
round of group matches.
In the first half Scotland played their best hockey of the tournament
and by the break could have established a winning lead.
David Leiper converted their first corner in 10 minutes and this
appeared to boost their confidence even although Ledovic Tissier forced
the equaliser when he hit the target from France's first setpiece.
In between, Richard Freeland squandered a great opportunity by not
releasing the ball to Gordon Shepherd when the pair were in a two-to-one
situation with the French goalkeeper. Then Shepherd failed to put the
final touch to a well-worked routine and Michael Starling hit a post
from a penalty after Freeland had been fouled while shooting for goal.
Scotland's play deteriorated in the second half. In the end France
outscored Scotland 10-9 on shots at goal but Scotland had the advantage
on the corner count 8-6.
This point keeps Scotland in fifth place, a group ahead of France. If
they can retain this position after today's contest with Spain they
would have the easier opening classification match in the play-off for
places nine to 12 at the weekend. Results:
Group A -- Scotland 1, France 1; Holland 3, Wales 0; Spain 2, Belgium
2. Group B -- Germany 7, Switzerland 0.
</TEXT>
