<TEXT>
SAILING:
DAVID Harte, the former Irish coach, maintained a slender lead on the
second day of the second leg of the Teacher's Round Britain Challenge as
light breezes and strong tides continued to make progress intermittent
en route from Cardiff to Rothesay.
Harte, skipper of Dream of Erin, had a lead of just one mile yesterday
as the wind faded once more and the fleet compressed, many taking to
anchor in a strong tide.
''We've been stopped in more than 40 metres of water and have had to
tie everything together but the kitchen sink to cope with the depth of
water,'' said England's David Alan-Williams, who skippers Jackson's
Landing Spirit of Hartlepool, lying second.
Scotland's Jon Fitzgerald and Chris Nichol were sailing conservatively
in third place in Glendronach, secure in the knowlege that so far they
have been one of the quicker boats in the 10-strong five-nations fleet
when the wind blows.
An end to the 10 days of doldrums is believed to be in sight.
