<HEADLINE>Gallacher delays Olazabal decision</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764949</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOLF: RYDER CUP
BERNARD Gallacher will wait until the last moment before deciding
whether he wants Jose Maria Olazabal in his Ryder Cup team next month.
Olazabal has been troubled all season by a foot injury and indicated
from America last week that he might ask to be left out of the match.
That was before he finished joint sixth in the Sprint International in
Colorado yesterday and Gallacher, Europe's captain, wants to see the
outcome of this week's Volvo German Open, the last qualifying event,
before making up his mind. Olazabal, Nick Faldo, and Ian Woosnam are
outside the top 10 who automatically gain selection.
Of the three only Woosnam, No.13 in the table, plays in Stuttgart --
Olazabal and Faldo are at the World Series in Ohio -- but even if the
players above him all miss the halfway cut the Welshman would still have
to finish in the top five.
Gallacher said: ''Jose Maria might not be able to play every match in
the cup, but I do have to consider his relationship with Seve
Ballesteros. They have been wonderfully successful together. It will
come down to whether Jose Maria and I think that he will be hindering
the team if he was there.''
Gallacher knows only five of his side -- Colin Montgomerie, Bernhard
Langer, Sam Torrance, Costantino Rocca, and Ballesteros. For the
remaining five automatic spots there are 19 in contention.
David Gilford and Howard Clark, runner-up in the Czech Open yesterday
after bogeying two of the last three holes, look almost home and dry at
sixth and seventh in the table.
But Mark James, Per-Ulrik Johansson, and Philip Walton -- eight, nine
and 10 -- are separated by less than #2500 and Spaniard Miguel Angel
Jimenez is right on their heels.
Nick Faldo is guaranteed a wild card. If it comes down to Woosnam or
Olazabal for the other, Europe will be seen as having shot themselves in
the foot by changing from three to two wild cards.
</TEXT>
