<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Murray stays on her feet for an easy win. Forgotten man Hanlon back in the limelight</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976764951</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOM Hanlon, so impoverished by paying medical bills that he had to
borrow money to represent Great Britain last night, made a dramatic
winning return against the USA -- in a match sponsored, ironically, by
BUPA.
The forgotten man of UK athletics, racing on the track for the first
time since the European Championship final 53 weeks ago in Helsinki,
Edinburgh's Hanlon won the 3000 metres steeplechase in 8min 24.37sec,
helping Britain win the men's match at Gateshead by 203 points to 182.
Though 10 yards off the pace with two laps remaining, Hanlon clawed
his way back relentlessly, then surged into the final water jump, going
on to win by 12 metres.
Behind him were two Britons -- Keith Cullen and Spencer Duval -- and
an American. All had competed earlier this month at the World
Championships in Sweden.
Hanlon applauded the crowd on his lap of honour, showing real delight
at his successful return. ''But it wasn't that good,'' he confided.
''After all, these guys are tired. I am pretty rusty, and my head is not
up to scratch.
''I've had my problems physically -- my back, and an Achilles tendon.
I have spent a fortune on medical fees. It is #23 every time I go to the
osteopath to get myself sorted out, and I would go twice a week if I
could afford it. But I can't. I'm skint.''
Hanlon's right calf muscle is clearly much more wasted than the left,
but he is convinced his physical problems are over. ''Financially
though, I'm pretty hard up. I borrowed money to come here. The British
Athletics Federation is prepared to pay just #100 in physiotherapy
bills. That's gone in no time, and the form-filling and medical
referrals before getting the money takes ages.
''Your condition is chronic before you are treated. There is supposed
to be a system, but it is pointless if you can't get help, especially
treatment needed to prevent injuries. You can only get the money once it
is too late.''
Peter Fleming, the Scottish marathon internationalist who quit
Scotland for the USA yesterday, cited similar reasons for his departure.
Hanlon, however, makes no such threats. This was his third
international win for Britain -- one against the supposedly invincible
Kenyans, and the other two against the USA, both at Meadowbank.
The 28-year-old Scottish record-holder is just praying for an
injury-free winter, consistent training, and the chance to attune his
mind for a serious Olympic bid next year.
Yvonne Murray stayed on her feet for an encouraging win in the 3000m,
though in a modest 8-59.80. ''No scars this time,'' she smiled, perhaps
for the first time since her 10,000m fall in Gothenburg. The
Commonwealth champion broke clear with more than 600m to go and won by
nearly five seconds.
The field included three-times world cross-country champion, Lynn
Jennings, who was second. But the USA team overall, though containing 35
of their world squad, had not one of their nine individual gold
medal-winners.
It was seven-and-half hours after the meeting began that America's
only individual world medal winner appeared -- Jearl Myles -- to run a
relay leg. Even then the depleted US women won their match easily,
210[1/2]-156[1/2].
Murray, having done all that was asked of her on her return, admitted:
''I needed to get back with that win, and throw off my fall. You can't
dwell on it. I could have acepted a bad performance -- but I didn't even
give a performance.''
She will decide today whether to run the Brussels grand prix on
Friday. ''I'll see how my legs are -- but I will definitely run the
3000m in London next Sunday,'' she added.
David Strang almost made it a hat trick of Scottish wins. The
Govan-born European indoor 1500m champion took the lead at the bell in
the 800m, but had victory snatched from his grasp on the line. Rich
Kenah, his US training partner, lunged past close to home, winning in
1:46.52. Strang, who races again at Crystal Palace next weekend, was
second in 1:46.68.
Melanie Neef, having switched from her preferred 400m at the team
management's request, to the 200m, was frustrated by the calmest night
the normally wind-assailed Tyneside track fans can remember.
Neef, warming up for a 400m run in Copenhagen tomorrow, then the
Berlin grand prix next week, clocked 23.42, finishing fourth, seven
hundredths outside her best. Then she watched the 400m won in a time
which, had she matched it, would have broken the Scottish record.
Edinburgh's Lorna Jackson reached 52.86m, for fifth in the women's
javelin, and Blackpool-based 22-year-old Anglo, Vikki Lawrence, though
sixth in the 800m, clocked 2:04.77, fastest by a Scot this year.
The inspirational impact of world triple jump record-breaker Jon
Edwards was in evidence even before the local hero showed his face in
his home stadium, to tumultuous applause. But a tired Edwards managed
only one legal jump, 17.49 metres -- good enough to win, well short of
his world best of 18.29 -- though it would have been a personal best for
him before this season.
Others took a leaf from his book, however. US-born Ashia Hansen twice
broke the UK and Commonwealth record in the women's triple jump, first
with 14.57m, and then reaching 14.66m in the final round.
It was the third time this week, and the ninth this season indoors and
out, that she had improved the women's record. ''I feed off Jonathan's
jumping,'' she said.
Steve Backley took the javelin with 83.00m and Jamie Baulch set a
Welsh record with 45.15 in the 400m, but John Regis needed the
disqualification of US rival Anthuan Maybank to take the 200m in 20.63.
Colin Jackson made a winning hurdles return, in 13.18, then revealed
he would be having two operations under the same anaesthetic at the end
of the season -- on a cartilage and tonsils simultaneously.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Education first for dynamic duo</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUGLAS LOWE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976764952</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RARELY, if ever, have two young amateur golfers, Gordon Sherry and
Janice Moodie, had such an impact on Scotland's national psyche.
If they weren't household names before the summer, they are now
following 21-year-old Sherry's barnstorming campaigns in the Scottish
Open at Carnoustie, where he was fourth, and the Open at St Andrews --
which included outscoring former champions Greg Norman and Tom Watson
over the 36 holes he was in their company -- and 22-year-old Moodie's
feat in finishing top Scot, seventh overall, in the women's Scottish
Open at Dalmahoy.
The meeting, at Moodie's home club of Windyhill, was at the behest of
the Bank of Scotland, who, as part of their tercentenary activities, had
granted sports awards to both under an elite scheme run by the Scottish
Sports Aid Foundation. They are described as ''potential high-fliers,''
but patently they already are stars of today, and if they are becoming
role models for Scotland's extreme golfing youth, then parents have
little to worry about.
Moodie is studying psychology and business at San Jose State
University in California, where she won a golf scholarship, and is
waiting until she graduates in 1997 before having a tilt at the American
LPGA Tour.
Improvisation, however, is required and her lifestyle is almost one of
''have books will travel.'' This week she returns to university for all
of a week, to register for classes and collect the required reading
material, before jetting off again to Australia to represent Great
Britain and Ireland in the Commonwealth tournament at Royal Sydney Golf
Club, a pattern which will be repeated regularly during the collegiate
golfng season.
Sherry has almost completed his BSc degree at Stirling University,
where he also is on a golf scholarship. The Kilmarnock Barassie player
has 13 of the 15 units he needs and expects to have the remainder by the
time he turns professional after playing in the US Masters next April,
having been invited there as Amateur champion. Finding the hours to
combine studying and golf has been hard, but he is in no doubt the
effort, which will have to be made for a few more months, has been
worthwhile.
Following his campaign in the Canadian Amateur championship at
Toronto, where he reached the semi-finals last week, he will play in the
North of Scotland Open at Royal Dornoch this weekend in preparation for
the Walker Cup at Porthcawl, Wales, on September 9 and 10. This will be
followed by the home internationals at Royal Portrush, the European Club
Cup in Portugal, a trip to South Africa in spring, and a spell at
Valderrama prior to Augusta. One of his first pro tournaments may be
Jack Nicklaus's Memorial Tournament at Muirfield Village, Ohio, in May.
For two golfers who have evolved separately, their careers have
similarities. Sherry has great faith in coach Bob Torrance, with whom he
has worked since 1991, while Moodie has stuck with Cawder's Ken Stevely,
her mentor since she was 15. Both believe in the principle of one coach
only. Now they have made their breakthrough among the world's top
players at the same time, achievements which both believe have given
them higher confidence levels.
There are still differences, not just the obvious one. Sherry is 6ft
8ins and 18st while Moodie is 5ft 9ins and just under 10st. In the
''what might have been'' stakes, Sherry would have won around #40,000
for the Scottish Open and Open had he been a pro, while Moodie's cheque
would have been only #2500.
Yet the expenses are still the same. Sherry came to the global total
of #10,000 for 1994 and more this year, while Moodie reckoned she was
not far short. So such awards -- #2000 to Sherry and #2500 to Moodie --
from the Bank of Scotland, who have pledged #70,000 to elite and
grassroots schemes over a three-year period to various sports is an
important contribution.
Sherry, whose handicap is plus 3, and Moodie, who plays off plus 5,
were meeting each other for only the second time, having bumped into
each other briefly three years ago. With both playing almost exclusively
in scratch events, their plus handicaps are effectively badges of
honour.
</TEXT>
