<TEXT>
PARBUSTERS
IT might well come as a relief to all those sharpshooters that there
is no outright bandit-of-the-season now that the dust has settled from
the 16 qualifying weeks of Parbusters and the finalists are declared for
the seventh annual final at Haggs Castle on October 4, writes Douglas
Lowe.
The lowest net score was only minus 13, compiled by five players,
three men and two women. Only? Well, previously they have been as low as
minus 18 and this season has been the tamest so far, though the
qualifying cut-offs have been remarkably consistent over the seven
years.
Scratch scores, however, are going down. Minus 4 in the past has been
good enough for the men as has plus one for the women. Not now though.
Ballots were required on minus 5 for men and level for women, and
similarly on minus 11 for men's handicap. Strictly, there also should
have been a ballot on minus 11 in women's handicap, but as there were 11
players on that score or better, it seemed harsh for one to be denied.
However, an alternate will be invited from among the minus 10s only if
there are two call-offs. Alternates will be contacted in the other
