<DOCID>GH950822-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>When finding a home needs a greater measure of care</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WENDY JACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976764955</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE can come a point in the lives of elderly people, struggling to
cope with the mental and physical stresses of running a home too large
for current needs, when it all becomes too much.
For growing numbers the answer has been found in the purchase of a
sheltered or retirement home, specifically built to cater for the needs
of the older generation.
The two descriptions, sheltered and retirement, are somewhat confusing
since they are basically one and the same thing -- namely flats or
bungalows -- which are offered for sale with a number of services.
In these days, when many people retire early, ''retirement''
accommodation is increasingly directed towards this younger and more
able group.
However, for those who require the reassurance and safety net of a
resident or non-resident warden, or an emergency call system, sheltered
accommodation with features such as grab handles in bathrooms, perhaps
electric sockets placed more conveniently higher on the wall, and
possibly communal facilities such as a lounge, guest flat or laundry,
can be ideal.
Age Concern Scotland's factsheet two covers the subject in great
detail and is well worth getting, by sending a SAE to them at 113 Rose
Street, Edinburgh EH2 3DT.
As Age Concern points out, prospective purchasers need to ask
themselves many questions including:
* will the housing you are considering meet your needs now and in the
future?
* what sort of further care options might be available if necessary in
the time ahead -- or would you have to leave the development?
And on costs:
* can you afford (a), the capital cost; and (b) the ongoing (and
consistently rising) service charges which will be levied?
What sort of control will you have over your initial investment, and
the annual costs in the future? What are the obligations involved in
living in a communal setting? What options are at your disposal should
you feel that the management isn't meeting all its obligations? And can
an unsatisfactory management be removed?
The National House Builders Council (Scotland) is the guardian of the
quality of private housebuilding north of the Border. It has produced a
draft Code of Practice which covers new private sheltered and retirement
housing in Scotland. The NHBC keeps a membership register of those
builders who follow the set standard of construction, and therefore have
a Buildmark warranty.
The code also lays down guidelines for the management of private
sheltered and retirement housing. It had been hoped that builders
wishing to continue to use the NHBC Buildmark for sheltered or
retirement developments would have to comply with this section too, but
sadly it appears likely that the sellers of the property may be able to
pick and choose the parts of the ode that they wish to adopt.
It is advisable when considering buying a new home in this area of the
market place, that you send for a copy of the draft code of practice
from NHBC (Scotland) at 5 Manor Place, Edinburgh EH3 7DH.
Compare it with what is contained in the purchaser's information pack
which you will get from the organisation selling the flats or houses.
This, along with Age Concern (Scotland) factsheet, will offer valuable
guidelines along which your thinking should run.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Company improves quality of life</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976764956</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LONELINESS and isolation in old age can be hard to overcome. At home,
alone, without the companionship of others and with little to enliven
the week, life can be sad and empty.
And for those who are fortunate enough to have family or friends to
care for them on a full-time basis, the carers themselves have a great
need also, to get the occasional break, secure in the knowledge that
their charge is being looked after.
Since 1948, Glasgow Old People's Welfare Association has done a
sterling job, running a large number of clubs throughout the city,
mainly in church halls, schools or community centres. Today these number
around 130, and along with other projects run by the association, mean
that the Old People's Welfare Association is in touch with between
10,000 and 12,000 elderly people in a year.
''In addition to our clubs which normally meet on a weekly basis, we
have two purpose-built day centres, one on the south side of Glasgow and
one recently opened in Yoker,'' says Jock Stevenson, the association's
director.
''These bring in people who have carers at home, and therefore
relieves him or her, in addition to giving all sorts of activities for
the elderly to take part in during the day. Lunch is also available at
the day centres.''
One worthwhile project initiated by the association is neighbourhood
visiting. It recruits volunteers via paid coordinators, to visit elderly
people within a small geographic area to see they are alright, and give
advice. Coordinators have community flats, which serve as drop-in
centres for pensioners in the area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Alex Munro shops saved by Dewhurst MBO</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976764957</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE management buy-out of the JH Dewhurst butchers' shop chain from
receivership, announced yesterday, has saved 13 Alex Munro outlets on
this side of the Border.
Property group Asda Property Holdings has linked up with the
management team, which is led by joint Dewhurst managing directors Roger
Reeson and Eugene Lines.
Asda Property has purchased the freehold premises occupied by
Dewhurst, the largest chain of its type in Britain, and will lease them
back to the new MBO company, Dewhurst Butchers.
No financial details of the buy-out, or the purchase and lease-back of
the freeholds, were revealed.
Asda Property's involvement secured the future of about 80 of the
200-plus outlets which will be operated by the MBO firm under the
Dewhurst, Baxters, Matthews, Cobb of Knightsbridge and Alex Munro names.
In Scotland Dewhurst trades exclusively as Alex Munro. The number of
Munro outlets has declined in recent years, in line with the chain
nationally. The 13 remaining employ about 50 people.
Mr Reeson said Munro was a significant part of the deal and believed
it might ultimately be possible to increase the number of shops north of
the Border.
He added: ''We are proud to retain a very strong hold in Scotland with
Alex Munro, and we look forward to driving the business forward.''
Mr Lines expressed the company's view that there was an exciting
future for specialist High Street retailers.
The deal, announced by receiver Ernst &amp; Young, will safeguard about
1000 jobs throughout the UK. However, about 150 jobs will go as a final
wave of 35 shops not included in the transaction are closed.
Dewhurst and its parent company Union International, owned by the
Vestey family, went into receivership on March 22.
Union subsidiary British Beef, which has abattoirs and meat-processing
plants at Preston, Wakefield and Peterborough, was sold on March 31 to
Irish company Kepak (UK) for an undisclosed sum.
Terry Robinson was brought in from Lonrho in 1992 to revive the
family-dominated business headed by Edmund Vestey. By 1993, the number
of Dewhurst outlets had been cut from 1100 to 400.
Dewhurst owned 360 shops, employing about 1800 people, when it went
into receivership with debts of about #35m.
The buy-out transaction was led, structured and negotiated by Foreign
&amp; Colonial Ventures. NatWest Markets (acquisition finance) provided the
bank funding and the management team was advised by Coopers &amp; Lybrand's
corporate finance arm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Abel Eastern set to rise from the ashes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764958</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABEL Eastern, the Scottish supplier of Asian nan bread to supermarkets
throughout the UK, is rising from the ashes of a factory fire as a new
company backed by venture capitalist 3i.
3i is providing the lion's share of a #10m financing package to launch
Abel Eastern International, but Mike Pacitti, the negotiator involved,
declined to say how much.
This new company will take over the business of Abel Eastern Foods,
which went into liquidation after a fire at its Livingston factory on
June 30. Managed by husband-and-wife team Shazia and Wazir Gallam, it
aims to start production at a brand new site in Cumbernauld at the end
of September.
The Gallams founded Abel Eastern Foods in Livingston in 1988 and built
it into a thriving business employing 280 people.
The firm sold #15m worth of nan bread and other Asian food produce a
year to supermarket chains such as Marks &amp; Spencer, Tesco and Sainsbury.
But its factory was destroyed by a fire on June 30 only hours after
insurance cover had run out, sending it into receivership. The Gallams
are suing an insurance broker, who they claim was responsible for this
oversight.
Meanwhile, they have lost no time in starting up a successor company
with a #10m package of equity, loans, grants and leasing finance.
Scottish Enterprise and accountancy firm Rutherford Manson Dowds are
helping launch Abel Eastern International, as well as 3i.
The Gallams hope many of their former employees in Livingston will
work at the new Cumbernauld plant, which is only 25 miles away.
''It's a blow that we couldn't start again in Livingston, but
Cumbernauld was the only place which offered the right facilities,''
said Mrs Gallam, who is managing director of the new firm. Her husband
Wazir is sales director.
Abel Eastern International will move in to a brand new factory shell
supplied by Scottish Enterprise at the Orchardton Woods development in
Cumbernauld. This offers plenty of space for future expansion.
Initially, the new firm will recruit about 100 employees who will
start producing nan bread as soon as the necessary machinery is
delivered in September.
Abel Eastern International plans to double this workforce by March and
achieve an annual turnover of #18m within three years. It has received
assurances from many former clients of Abel Eastern Foods that they will
buy nan bread from the new company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>HarperCollins still hopeful of concluding print sale</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976764959</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MANAGEMENT at the HarperCollins book printing operation is understood
to be still hopeful of concluding a sale of the closure threatened plant
by the end of next month.
A circular distributed to staff has confirmed that negotiations are
continuing with two potential investors.
Morale among the 470 employees at the loss-making plant at
Bishopbriggs, near Glasgow, is said to be at an ''all-time low'' given
the uncertainty that has surrounded the operation since The Herald
revealed last November that a search was underway to find a buyer.
The London-based merchant bank Robert Fleming has been working with
senior management to secure a buyer and has contacted about 40 potential
purchasers who might take over the plant as a going concern.
Of the 40, 28 requested a summarised information memorandum on the
business, and 11 of those asked for detailed information.
However, staff have seen the expiry of several sale deadlines come and
go with no firm news of a buyer.
In his latest brief statement to staff, Eddie Bell, HarperCollins'
executive chairman, apologised for the uncertainty during what he
recognised had been a ''prolonged'' and ''difficult'' period.
While he could give no guarantee that any deal would be concluded, he
said negotiations were continuing with two potential investors with a
view to saving as many of the jobs in manufacturing as possible.
He was hopeful the matter could be concluded ''one way or the other''
by the end of next month.
HarperCollins said yesterday that Mr Bell was on holiday and no-one
else was available to comment in his absence.
A management source dismissed reports that the loss of more than 400
jobs at the plant was now inevitable and said the company was ''fairly
optimistic'' a sale could still be achieved.
He said: ''One never sets a deadline when you are in this position.
These matters progress very slowly. The time of events is not in the
hands of the vendor but is dictated by the purchaser. I am sure that
something will be sorted out as suggested in the letter.''
The source declined to reveal the identity of the two potential buyers
although he said it was ''extremely unlikely'' they would include a
management-buy-out team. He also ruled out interest from the Far East.
Gareth Ward, editor of Printing World, the UK's leading printing
magazine, said the identity of the potential buyers remained a mystery
among industry sources, although the giant German publishing giant
Bertelsmann had been touted.
This assertion constrasts somewhat with a fax received by the Herald
in June from Dr Horst Benzing of Bertelsmann, which stated that it had
''no interest'' in purchasing ''either parts of HarperCollins or the
company in total''.
Mr Ward added: ''As I understand it little interest has been shown by
UK-based publishing firms.'' On a slightly more optimistic note, he
added: ''The fact that the manufacturing plant is still operating,
despite several apparent sale deadlines passing, perhaps indicates that
a buyer of some description is lined up in the next few weeks.''
It is understood that any deal could involve up to 100 permanent
redundancies at the plant, which is said to be losing #4m a year.
The deal would also involve the remaining employees being made
redundant and re-employed under fresh terms and conditions set by a new
employer, a move the Graphical, Paper and Media Union may oppose.
David Munro, Scottish branch secretary of the GPMU, said he had
requested a meeting at the ''earliest opportunity'' with Mr Bell to
discuss the contents of the staff circular.
He said the union was quite happy that the company was still trading
and that it had done nothing to break any agreements.
However, he suggested that it was not satisfactory that staff were
merely being given a stay of execution each time a deadline passed and
added: ''This will have to come to a head some way.''
Last November Mr Bell warned of the possibility of closure at the
Westerhill plant if a buyer was not found.
He said a sale would not affect 700 other workers employed at
Bishopbriggs in distribution, finance and administration, although some
employees have privately expressed fears that any sale of the
manufacturing operation could put the entire Westerhill complex at risk.
A sale would bring to an end Collins's 175-year link with book
manufacturing in Glasgow. The company was bought for #400m by Rupert
Murdoch in January 1989 after a bitter takeover battle.
Although it is associated with several best-selling authors,
management has conceded it has failed to attract enough business for the
manufacturing side, which can produce about 60 million volumes a year,
because other publishers regard it as a competitor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mice looks to buy as income rises 8%</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764960</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MICE chairman Mike Curley may soon be able to offer shareholders an
unusual perk -- free admission to the Nubian Museum in Aswan where the
exhibition design company has a three-year #7m contract to present
Egyptian artefacts at their most compelling.
The work is about one-third completed and accounted for a fair
proportion of half-time turnover, which rose 8% to #5.83m. It employs
160 people, which is more than the rest of the group put together.
The full Museum Interiors, Conferences and Exhibitions contract is due
for completion in two years. Then the results will be appraised by
developing countries such as those in Central and South American as well
as in the Far East, which have history and culture to sell via the
tourist industry.
Shorter term, Mice's prospects look good. It also has a #1m contract
to design a display lasting for just four days for the Sony Play Centre,
as well as the Foreign Office input into the World Trade Fair in Lisbon
and the subsequent one in Berlin.
Mice is, therefore, looking for German acquisitions and it seems
almost certain one will be achieved over the next couple of months.
There is net cash of nearly #1m in hand at the Bank of Scotland and a
total of #3m available for deals.
For the immediate future, it has also designed the Scottish and
Frankfurt Motor Shows.
Against the trend, its in-store display activities have performed
well. New customers include Wedgwood in the foreign tourist oriented
retailers.
At the half-way stage, there was a swing round from losses of #99,000
into #85,000 profit, and the City now expects an increase in the
full-year total from #450,000 to at least #750,000. There is a maiden
interim dividend of 0.032p, with a 0.096p total forecast for a 3% yield
with the shares at 4p.
Those looking for a penny stock with potential -- it was floated at 3p
last December -- may like to take a punt. Unfortunately, they will have
to find their own way up the Nile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mare reigns supreme at Dumfries show</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764961</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SEVEN-YEAR-OLD mare won the supreme championship at the 24th annual
Dumfries and Galloway Horse Show held at Wheatcroft Farm, Castle
Douglas.
John Smith from Speddoch, Isle of Whithorn, was showing for the first
time at South-west Scotland's biggest horse show. His Camford Yvonne,
which was sired by Millisle Footprint, was Clydesdale champion before
being judged the best horse on the showfield.
She was female champion at Wigtown earlier this month, and Mr Smith
said he was delighted with the result. ''I was pleased when she was
picked out as Clydesdale champion, but it was tremendous to win the
champion-of-champions award, especially on my first time at the show,''
he said.
It was a successful day for Helen Mair from Holywood, Dumfries, and
seven-year-old Just Kylie who won the JL Taylor Cup for small hunters
and then took the President and Vice-President's Trophy for the hunter
championship.
The Copeland family from The Piggery, Motehill, Glenluce, had a highly
successful day with three winners. Ruth-Mary Copeland, aged eight, and
Luce Bay Gentleman James won the John Hunt Memorial Trophy for the first
ridden pony, and she also collected the Brown Trophy for the leading
rein pony on Springs Minuet. Her sister, Angela, won the Corrielaw
Trophy for any age in-hand Arab with four-year-old Craigwell Starlight
Express, who has clocked up nine championship wins.
Anne Howard of Castle Douglas was showing her four-year-old registered
Dales Wath Freestep Teddy for the first time, and together they won the
Barncrosh Cup for the best registered pony in the mountain and moorland
classes.
Well-known Palomino exhibitor Tommy Thorburn from Eastriggs took the
championship once again and also won the McMaster Trophy for in-hand
ponies with his yearling Woodhall Trena.
Trophy winners were:
Honeyman Trophy for ridden hunters -- Pat Baird, West Linkins, Gelson
and Ben Tudor; JL Taylor Trophy for small hunters and President and
Vice-President's Cup for hunters -- Helen Mair, Holywood, Dumfries and
Just Kylie; Kirkland Trophy -- Mary Moore, Dinwoodie Green Farm,
Johnstone Bridge and Poetic Promise; Trophy for best rider 12 and under
-- Louise Maxwell, South Carleton, Borgue.
James Picken Trophy for ridden ponies -- Susan Hunt, Maryfield,
Terregles and Pendley Dancer; John Hunt Memorial Trophy for first ridden
pony -- Ruth-Mary Copeland, Motehill, Glenluce and Luce Bay Gentleman
James; Brown Trophy for leading rein -- Ruth-Mary Copeland and Springs
Minuet.
Lady Stair Trophy for best riding pony -- Margaret Hunt and Hamptonne
Mimosa; Gordon Trophy for best PBAR -- Tommy Thorburn, Woodhall,
Eastriggs and Woodhall Trena.
McMaster Trophy for best foal -- Marion Robson, Hollandbush, Racks
Road, Dumfries and Lochar Cat Ballou; Honeyman Trophy for Palomino --
Tommy Thorburn and Woodhall Cindy; Corrielaw Trophy for Arab any age --
Angela Copeland with Craigwell Starlight Express.
Barncrosh Cup for best registered pony -- Anne Howard and Wath
Freestep Teddy; Knockgray Cup for best Highland Pony -- G McMurray,
Bellstown, Eaglesfield; Trophy for best Clydesdale -- John Smith,
Speddoch Farm, Isle of Whithorn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Government set for sheep quota claims</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764962</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government is preparing to meet substantial claims from sheep
farmers who, in the light of an English High Court ruling, have been
wrongly refused sheep quota from the national reserve.
Quota allocation is the key to claiming sheep annual premium payments,
which are currently worth #21 per breeding ewe.
The English High Court ruling means the criterion laid down by the
Government -- that ''developers'' had to show documentary evidence of a
plan for increasing their flock -- have been declared unlawful.
With the easing of this criterion more producers will qualify for
quota and may claim they have suffered loss as a result of being
rejected when they made their initial application in 1993. The total
amount of quota remains unaltered, however, so the Scottish Office
Agriculture Department and the Ministry of Agriculture south of the
Border face difficult decisons on how to re-dress the balance.
The 1993 allocation has to be revised so those who can now claim they
should have received an allocation from the national reserve will
receive either quota or compensation.
Indications are that the Scottish Office is unlikely to recall all
categories of quota allocation and redistribute them according to the
new rules. While spreading the pain over a wide area, this would require
EC legislation.
A preferred option could be to confine the revised allocation to what
is known as category three -- which covers people who had declared an
intention of increasing the size of their flock, those who took over
land from which quota had been removed by a departing tenant, and new
entrants who were seeking a quota allocation for the first time in 1993.
Some 300 sheep farmers currently receive their quota, totalling about
30,000 units, under arrangements for ''developers''. A further 400 were
rejected in 1993.
Although the current problems arise from the rulings of an English
Court, the Government has made clear that it will operate on a UK basis.
The National Farmers' Union of Scotland has indicated, however, that it
may seek recourse to the Scottish courts if it feels the rights of quota
holders here are being usurped in the implementation of the English
ruling.
In a briefing note to NFUS members, chief executive Tom Brady said:
''We have told the Government that it is their responsibility to get
whatever quota may be needed to sort out the mess they have made. If it
means going to Brussels for more quota, or obtaining authority to open
an outgoers scheme, that is what they should do.''
Civil servants and NFUS officials have been involved in detailed
discussions on the quota problem and Scottish Office Agriculture
Minister the Earl of Lindsay has said he hopes to find a solution
acceptable to both sides.
Meanwhile, existing national reserve quota holders have been told to
submit their 1996 claims for sheep annual premium as usual. These will
be paid subject to the normal requirements. ''They need not consider
purchasing or leasing additional quota as a precaution,'' Lord Lindsay
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Asda takes control of Burwood</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764963</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SUPERMARKET group Asda has concluded its agreement to buy out its
joint venture partner British Aerospace from their Burwood House retail
property company.
It will pay #88m cash and take over Burwood's #265m debt, giving a
total funding requirement of #353m.
Both parties welcomed the deal, which gives Asda control of 34 of its
own stores -- and four shopping centres -- and helps British Aerospace
exit from an ill-fated flirtation with property development that started
six years ago.
The acquisition would be broadly neutral for earnings in the current
financial year.
Rent paid from Asda stores located on properties owned by Burwood was
enough to pay for all the interest charges on Burwood's total debt.
BAe finance director Richard Lapthorne said the sale was the last
significant step in BAe's strategy to focus property interests in
Arlington Securities.
Burwood achieved a consolidated profit before tax of #430,000 for
1994.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
