<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NIESR predicts #5000m income tax cut in Budget</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764968</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN its economic forecasts in the August quarterly review, the
independent National Institute of Economic and Social Research assumes
that income tax cuts costing some #5000m in revenue will be announced in
the coming Budget.
It also suggests, in contrast to the May review when it advocated a
rise in base rates to 8% by the end of this year, that interest rates
will be held at their present level throughout this year and next.
This change of assumption reflects both the indications of slower
output growth and also a change in emphasis in the statement of policy
objectives by the Government, although not by the Bank of England.
The NIESR itself believes that if taxes were to be cut in the Budget
it would be appropriate to raise interest rates at about the same time.
This, it says, would improve the odds on a reduction in inflation while
reassuring financial markets that the Government is not simply guided by
considerations of political popularity.
The tax measures could be designed to help the construction sector in
particular, since a further rise in interest rates might otherwise hit
too hard.
The other obvious option is to do nothing since the state of the
economy remains quite satisfactory after a very good year in 1994, an
option the NIESR favours, although it accepts that between now and
November new information will no doubt become available which could
point to a different conclusion.
Its forecasts, as stated, are based on tax cuts and no increase in
interest rates. This involves a risk to the strict interpretation of
inflation objectives. Given the very public differences of view between
the Governor of the Bank of England and the Chancellor that risk is a
serious one to contemplate.
''It is nevertheless a risk which we think that the Chancellor, for
essentially political reasons, may well decide to take,'' says the
review.
The NIESR is now forecasting that inflation will rise later this year,
but that it will then slow down again and will be around 2.5% at the end
of next year with interest rates unchanged from current levels.
The latest Treasury forecast is inflation of 2.5% at the end of 1996,
though it does not say whether it believes interest rates need to be
raised to achieve this.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
