<DOCNO>GH950822-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Now string along with the Boys. Boys of the Lough, Queen's Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ADAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764973</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As the Festival's swings into week two The Herald's team of critics
guide you through the highs and lows of the Fringe
CATHAL McConnell is holding inimitable court: ''If you haven't heard
these tunes before, you'll be hearing them for the first time.'' And
all's well with the world, particularly the Boys, who have traded
deadening piano accompaniments for Chris Newman's light, driving guitar
patterns and are once again gaining momentum.
Canny, almost classical traditionalism remains an essential part of
their style. Nobody does it better. But Aly Bain, fiddling with a mix of
silk and sandpaper on a raking duet with Newman, proved that they can
cause goose bumps when they so choose.
Guests Flora MacNeill and Maggie MacInnes had a similar effect with
their beautiful, naturally sung Gaelic songs. And for all his blethers,
McConnell, too, can still put a song across with admirably simple
dignity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Moody's issues harsh rating for Japan's banks</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RIKA OTSUKA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764974</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Tokyo, Monday -- International credit rating agency Moody's issued a
harsh assessment of the health of Japan's banking industry today, rating
the financial strength of many of the country's banks as no better than
adequate.
Moody's Investors Service for the first time assigned ''financial
strength'' ratings to 50 leading Japanese banks, which were hit hard by
the collapse of Japan's ''bubble'' economy of inflated land and asset
prices in the early 1990s.
Most of the banks were rated between the lowest possible grade 'E',
meaning very weak intrinsic financial strength, and 'D', or adequate
strength. Only one bank, Shizuoka Bank, was rated 'B' or in strong
financial health.
''The 'E' ratings on the banks were due to a lack of profits and their
bad loans, based on a comparison with the financial system worldwide,''
said Masaru Kakutani, a director at Moody's office in Tokyo.
Japanese authorities estimate bad loans in Japan's financial system
total some 40 trillion yen ($412bn), and private analysts say the real
figure could be much larger.
The ratings were considerably worse than Moody's assessments of the
banks' bonds, issued previously. Unlike the bond ratings, the financial
strength measure does not include the possibility of aid to the banks
from Japan's financial authorities.
Most internationally operating banks have their own set of standards
and ways to assess other banks, which have already been applied, the
analysts said.
But the Moody's assessment could have a negative impact in the long
term by making it harder for the weak banks to trade derivative
financial instruments with foreign banks or by creating liquidity
problems at banks' overseas branches, economists said.
A Bank of Japan (BoJ) official said that the central bank would keep
careful watch on the liquidity of Japanese banks' overseas branches --
although he stressed that he was not referring directly to Moody's.
The official said that the central bank was prepared to provide help
if necessary to ensure that the overseas branches did not face financial
problems from worsening credit standings.
Several analysts in Tokyo said the Moody's ratings could push Japanese
authorities to take stronger action to solve the problems of bad debt
plaguing the financial system.
This year, authorities have intervened to limit the impact on the
overall financial system of the failures of three Tokyo credit unions,
including one last month.
However, political controversy and bureaucratic wrangling have so far
prevented the government from promising large injections of public money
to resolve the bad loan problem.
''When you're confronted with these kind of ratings, I hope this will
become a kind of springboard for the Japanese to act,'' said Richard
Koo, senior economist at Nomura Research Institute. -- Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Black Bride, Theatre Workshop</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764975</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FROM a children's nursery rhyme to intimations of holocaust, Andrew
Kelm takes us on a deconstruction of Sing A Song of Sixpence which
spirals into ever more bizarre imagery. Directly addressing the audience
in the manner of a stand-up, with occasional magician-like flourishes,
he muses over the implications of the symbolism of the rhyme, marvelling
at the horror of the maid who has her nose pecked off, conjuring up
mutilation and blood-splattered laundry.
His rigorous questioning takes in biblical and historical references
and a spot of Freudian analysis, all delivered with witty aplomb. He not
only strips the rhyme bare, he strips himself, standing bollock naked as
he muses over the queen inside him. But despite his wry command of the
well-written material, it's a dispassionate piece which leaves you cold.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Heart And Sole, Gilded Balloon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764976</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIFE'S not easy when you're a repressed St Andrew's primary
schoolteacher whose chosen love-partner, David, is a fish with an large
angular head and three finger-like walking rays in front of his pectoral
fin. Aye, fall for a gurnard and friends'll spurn you.
But David is no ordinary piscine playmate. And Lynn Ferguson's deft
and witty new drama is no ordinary girl-meets-fish affair.
It's a touching, funny, and perceptive play which allows Lynn to
display the full range of her acting abilities, from gutsy to prim, from
combative to defeated. And when Lynn does the play's central sad bit, it
would bring a tear to the glassy-eye of a dead halibut.
Go for Heart And Sole hook, line and sinker.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Andres Serrano, Portfolio Gallery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764977</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE tabloids have done Portfolio a service by stirring up a
shock-horror outrage over Serrano's glossy cibachrome photographs taken
in a morgue. The Pavlovian reaction is thus for ''experts'' to rush to
Serrano's defence. I have no intention of doing this.
Why? First, one must be convinced of what one is defending. I too
found these images difficult to look at, but that is not an proof that
they are great photos. Anyway, I am squeamish. And secondly, my response
to ordinary police photos would be just the same.
In fact I believe Serrano's less controversial Budapest pictures, the
young Sailor, the old life Model, are perhaps more interesting. They
capture the pose, glance, nuances of a personality. They also speak
volumes of a society at a particular time in its political development.
A corpse is a corpse.
Making work of rotting bodies is bound to shock. But it needs to do
more than that to be art.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jenny Eclair, Pleasance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764978</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIZZINGLY filthy, Jenny Eclair remains the slapper-superstar and scold
supreme of the Fringe. Her rationale for being drunk a lot of the time
and dyed-blonde all of the time is as impeccable as it is unprintable.
At her foul and truthful words of sexual wisdom, women guffaw in
liberated solidarity while men gasp in sharply-imagined pain and
embarrassment.
She makes Lenny Bruce look like Bernard Manning, and Bernard Manning
look like Mother Teresa. With mixed feelings of admiration and terror,
we must salute her.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mirjam, Church Hill Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764979</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MIRJAM has survived Auschwitz. So why has she slashed her wrists . . .
?
Memories, that's why. Memories that come milling on to the stage in a
rapid, stark collage of terror, death, brutality, and unexpected
sisterhood -- as she says herself ''the worst cruelty and the greatest
beauty''.
The women who people her memories are different ages, different
nationalities, different creeds. Only Mirjam (strongly played by Lynne
Livingstone) is a German Jew. Their one bond is the death camp.
Gradually the hostility of self-preservation gives way to a supportive
comradeship, the circumstances and the shifts of attitude finely
conveyed through the choreography that is central to the piece.
Elizabeth Marshall, Karen Coleman, and Katie McDonald give able
support, their characters reminding us of the courage shown during --
and after -- the Holocaust by those whose memories form the harrowing
basis of Mirjam.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Home Front, Fingers Piano Bar</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH BRUCE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764980</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BBC Radio Scotland's Dave Batchelor based this production on his
much-admired Radio 4 series about British life during wartime. It richly
deserves another outing, if only to let lunchtime audience see two fine
professional actors at work, using only their voices and facial
expressions.
Crawford Logan and Gowan Calder are both superb, creating a cast of
characters with accent and impersonations -- and both can sing well too.
With pianist Ralph Laing accompanying, it is Batchelor who provides the
bulk of the vocalese on songs familiar and obscure. He also takes credit
for what is an exquisite compilation, alternately hilarious and moving,
albeit still basically a radio show.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Car crash victim named</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764981</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN killed in a car crash on the Mayfield-Dalkeith road late on
Saturday was named yesterday as Mr Alan Cairney, 32, of Newton Street,
Easthouses, Midlothian. Stuart Buchan, 15, of Easthouses, and Craig
Cumming, 13, of Dalkeith, who were passengers in Mr Cairney's car when
it was involved in a collision with another car, were detained in
Edinburgh Royal Infirmary.
The other driver, Mr Raymond Parker, of Bogwood Road, and Michelle
Allan, five, both from Mayfield, were also hurt. All the injured were in
a satisfactory condition yesterday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Monologue Of A Madwoman, Gilded Balloon II</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DANIELLE NAGLER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764982</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MADWOMAN? Or more correctly of several, mad and arguably brilliant
too. Song, story and reading combine in this tribute by Linn Van Hek to
those that have inspired her across the years.
Role models offered range from Virginia Woolf and Viv Eliot (wife of T
S and alleged coiner of the title The Wasteland) to Van Hek's
grandmother, an outback woman who discovered lesbianism at the age of
40.
Van Hek seems to be a versatile and talented performer, but the show
has difficulty escaping from the lecture mode. There is however some
pretty good music, especially Joe Dolce's harmonica version of The
Lunacy Blues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sawn-Off Shakespeare, Adam House</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764983</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TORSION Theatre Company have choppped up the Bard and elongated bits
of themselves. Thus, we have a hilarious Romeo and Juliet where the
nurse dashes around, in wonderful Joyce Grenfell mode waving around arms
that come down to the floor, a Mercutio who cheerily strides about on
stilts, and a priest with a ballooning belly which he uses to fend off
the sodden nurse's unwanted attentions.
Romeo and Juliet are white-faced, red-nosed nerds, sick with puppy
love in the midst of all the chaos. It's gloriously energetic, hilarious
nonsense.
Their half-hour Hamlet, in stylish frock coats, was more sombre, with
elegant dance sequences condensing much of the action. Followed by a
dynamic, nightmarish 15-minute rendition of Macbeth this is one
thrilling, anarchic programme.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trade gap widens</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE, CITY EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764984</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S visible trade gap with the non-EU countries widened from
#759m to #856m in July, the highest since December, confounding market
projections which had centred on a shrinking in the deficit to around
#630m.
Adverse factors included a continuing low level of oil export volumes
in recent months due to North Sea maintenance work which has also
boosted imports.
Stripping out oil and erratic items, defined as ships, aircraft,
precious stones and silver, leaves the deficit little changed at #650m
compared with #645m in June.
However, the Central Statistical Office said that the latest estimate
of the trend suggests than the non-EU visible balance is widening. In
the three months to July, the deficit was #2300m compared with #1100m
because of the reduced exports of oil and an increase in the total value
of imports.
The trading picture up to May -- for which the last global figures are
available -- showed that trading with the EU countries has been
reasonably encouraging with exports growing. But there are now definite
signs of a slowdown elsewhere and particularly in the US which is
hitting UK exporters.
Virtually all the non-EU areas showed a widening of the size of the
trade gap last month with North America increasing from #239m to #276m.
Taking the three months to July, the value of exports to North America
has fallen by 11.8% while imports have grown by 7.5%.
For July alone, the value of total imports to non-EU areas was
unchanged from June at #5115m while imports were a record #5971m, an
increase of 1.5% on June. In the three months to July exports fell by
2.5% while imports rose by 4.5%. Estimates of the trend in value show
imports rising and exports virtually flat.
Excluding oil and erratics the volume of both exports and imports rose
by 3.5% in July compared with June. But taking the three months to July,
exports fell by 0.5% while volumes were up 5%. And estimates of trends
show export volume flat and import volume rising.
The July outcome made little impression in share and currency markets
although analysts expressed their disappointment, suggesting that the
deterioration in net exports could dampen third-quarter GDP.
The UK's economic recovery has of course been export led. If the EU
countries were to follow North America, it would have worrying
implications for the economy. The global visible trade figures for June
are due on September 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Eurotunnel shares tumble</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764985</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Eurotunnel plunged 28p a new all-time low of 138p as concern
mounted that there would have to be yet another re-financing within the
next few months as the company is failing to meet its revenue forecasts.
However, the Midland Bank, which is heavily exposed to the
cross-Channel tunnel company, did not make any extra provisions in its
half-time figures during the recent banking results season.
As usual, most of the action took place in Paris as French small
shareholders control the majority of the equity. There, the minority
shareholders' association suggested last week that Eurotunnel would lose
the equivalent of #1000m, compared with the company's own forecast
earlier this year of about #610m.
There is increasing pressure for state action to help it, although
that would raise a political storm from the ferry operators, who so far
have managed to withstand the competition with relative ease helped by
much better than expected bookings, particularly for one-day trips to
Calais.
Eurotunnel repeated yesterday that it would issue a revised 1995
profits forecast along with its interim results in October. However,
that is a considerable time ahead in stock market terms and there will
be pressure to bring forward the announcement.
Next month, it is due to meet its banks for talks about the terms for
financing the second tranche of its #693m senior debt, while debt
analysts argue that it needs #3000m of fresh equity to replace debt
before it can see light on the horizon.
It will be difficult to persuade shareholders to subscribe to a new
rights issue given that the last was in May 1994 at 265p or almost twice
the current share price.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Horse, The Palladium</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CARMEN ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764986</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN I first saw Horse play I was still in school and Glasgow still
admitted to having a club called the Mayfair. The then-suited Horse had
a five-piece band behind her. She rocked until she collapsed, she sang
until she was hoarse.
On Friday, however, I saw a Horse in a completely different field.
There she stood, visibly older, more confident, dressed casually with an
acoustic guitar hung over her shoulder and only long-term friend Angela
McAlinden for accompaniment.
Her unmistakable voice rang through the old church like that of a
sweet bird. Songs new and old, fans new and old. And although she
commented on her nervousness, it was obvious she is much happier in a
smaller, more personal environment, swapping innuendo and chatting with
the audience who have all followed her long enough to believe they are
her friends.
A standing ovation said it all. Who could help but be won over?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ScottishPower dismisses defence document for #1000m bid. Manweb plans cashback</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976764987</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MANWEB has confirmed earlier hints that it is planning a financial
package for shareholders, including a cashback, as part of its campaign
to see off ScottishPower's #1000m bid.
Its formal defence document says substantial value will be released to
shareholders through the package which will include cash and its 5%
holding in the National Grid, the #4000m business due to be privatised
this autumn.
ScottishPower dismissed the document, with chief executive Ian
Robinson declaring: ''Manweb has failed to address the key issues raised
by our offer.''
Manweb has also confirmed that it will release a profits and dividend
forecast for the year to next March and will reveal further cost-cutting
moves. However, there is no mention of several years of special
dividends, which formed part of Northern Electric's defence against
Trafalgar House.
Manweb is keeping the powder dry on its financial package until later
in the battle, the latest time it can reveal it being mid-September. It
is hoping that by then the bid will have been put on ice through a
reference to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
However, at the rate ScottishPower is buying up shares on the market
-- it now has 14.4% -- it will soon be in a commanding position.
The defence document is the usual mix, rejecting ScottishPower's
criticisms and drawing attention to Manweb's successes, while attacking
the bidder's own record. But it fails to make a convincing hit on the
Scottish group.
In comparison to Hanson's agreed offer for Eastern, which valued the
target at 13 times adjusted earnings, ScottishPower's offer of 10.5
times Manweb's earnings ''looks mean'', according to Manweb chief
executive John Roberts.
The document accuses ScottishPower of mounting its bid to offset the
failure of its diversification strategy, with its retail and non-core
activities providing only 2% of operating profits and showing a return
on capital of only 7.7%.
''ScottishPower has diversified into market sectors which are highly
competitive and where the potential returns to shareholders are
questionable,'' Manweb states.
The group refutes criticism of its industrial and commercial supply
business, pointing out that it made profits of #41.7m in the last two
years from this within its own region, while ScottishPower lost #11.9m.
Also rejected is the bidder's assertion that Manweb's costs are high.
They are said to be in line with those of other electricity
distributors, while the distribution costs of the Scottish power
companies cannot be directly compared because they are allocated
differently.
Manweb claims to have managed costs in its distribution and supply
businesses more successfuly than its opponent, whose costs in these
areas ''have increased by 15.7% in real terms since 1990-91''. This was
rejected by ScottishPower as ''spurious'' last night.
Manweb also maintains it has lowered its domestic tariffs by 8% in
real terms between 1991-92 and 1994-95 against ScottishPower's 5%. But
the latter dismissed these figures as incorrect.
The cashback to shareholders will be financed through raising
borrowings and Manweb's document draws attention to its level of gearing
of ''only'' 21% even after its #92m share buy-back.
In Northern's defence its gearing was projected to rise to 175% as a
result of its shareholder package. This was widely considered excessive
and it is unlikely Manweb would want to go above 150%. Even at this
level shareholders could be paid more than 650p per share. If gearing
was limited to 100%, it would still come to 400p.
The payout would be largely offset by a corresponding reduction in the
share price, unless the dividend was raised sharply. Dividend cover
currently tops three times. If it came down to two the dividend could be
increased 1[1/2] times to 46p. In this case the rump of the company
would after a, say, 400p payout probably be valued at some 700p, giving
a total of around 1100p against the 973p offered by ScottishPower.
This gives an idea of the options available to Manweb and shows that a
sweetener will undoubtedly be required for ScottishPower to succeed. But
then it probably budgeted for that before embarking on the bid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ceolbeg, Queen's Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ADAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764988</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON first consideration the new-look Ceolbeg doesn't seem so different
from the old model. Instrumentally, the band still has a tendency
towards making bonnie sounds with no great purpose, a kind of MacMuzak,
and is at its best by far on pipe-tunes such as the bold, stirring and
nicely named Mother Farquhar or the nimble Sleepy Tune with its loping
drum pattern.
With the introduction of Rod Paterson, however, Coelbeg now has a
commanding vocal presence, albeit under-utilised at the moment. A
long-time Burns' devotee, Paterson's Deil's Awa' Wi' The Exciseman,
smacking more of the Mississippi than the Afton, his terse, reggaefied
Ah Widnae Gie A Button For Her and the aptly titled The Presence
certainly boded well for the new partnership.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fred MacAulay, Gilded Balloon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764989</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FRED is happily monogamous but confesses to wishing he was sometimes
Minoguamous. With either Kylie or Dannii, he wouldn't mind. If the two
Ocker sex-shockers had seen Fred being knife-sharp on Have I Got News
For You, they'd be after him, that's for sure. Aye, Fred's got news for
you: he's a scream.
Fred's likeable without ever simply seeking an audience's approval.
He's authoritative yet approachable. He wields his charm like a rapier,
shocking as surely as he delights and vice versa. Mark my hat: if the
boy MacAulay don't get Perrier'd this year, some wet blanket's got neau
sense of humour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Aspects of the Royal Academy, British Council</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764990</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIRST come first served. Sheeran Locke is quick off the mark when it
comes to Festival venues. She has two shows running, one at the College
of Surgeons, another at the British Council in Bruntsfield Crescent.
Both have exemplary catalogues.
Bernard Dunstan's Aspects of the Royal Academy -- a didactic display
on lithography -- explains the process in a series of preparatory
sketches, proofs and photographs.
Dunstan's four lithos, made over 10 months in 1994 at the Curwen
Chilford Studios with master printer Stanley Jones. They feature typical
views of the Royal Academy: a private view, musicians in the courtyard,
the Friend's room and last, the life room of the RA Schools where
students draw the model.
The show is linked to the RA Schools' appeal which gets a quarter of
proceeds to help restore their litho room. I suggest a similar project
for Glasgow School of Art for next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Inmates sought</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976764991</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SEOUL: Inmates intent on escape were blamed for setting fire to a
dormitory at a South Korean rehabilitation centre, killing or seriously
