<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Prime Minister's Son, Gilded Balloon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764992</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister being Margaret Thatcher. The son being Mark -- a
natural figure of fun not only being the most treasured offspring of a
ruthlessly ambitious parent, but also being not very good.
That's where actor Richard Hallam, starring in James Poulter's one-man
play, scores most laughs. The over-privileged toff falling flat on his
face, failing his accountancy exams (three times), getting lost in the
desert, is a character-type we all love to hate.
But there's a more sinister side to the life of Mark Thatcher,
multi-million pound arms dealer, that this easy-going satire treats too
lightly. We can chuckle over his shortcomings -- and Hallam gives us
much opportunity to do so -- but should we be so blase about the power
he wields?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Footsie shines after gloomy 18 months</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E DUNDAS, CHIEF FINANCIAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<FLAG>COMMENT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764993</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AT last the FTSE-100 share index has attained a fresh closing record
after more than 18 months during which the stock market has been under a
cloud.
The previous closing peak was 3520.3 on February 2 last year. The
following day it lost ground after recording an all-time peak of 3539.2.
Yesterday's jump of 25.9 points to 3535.7, agonisingly short of a
proper breakthrough, came at the end of a summer rally which has added
over 200 points to the index.
Just as the rise in US rates, which began in February last year and
was replicated in the UK seven months later, caused share prices to
collapse last year (the Footsie fell below 2900 in June last year), so
this year's more benign interest rate environment has boosted share
prices on both sides of the Atlantic.
US interest rates were cut in July. UK rates have been on hold since
February and may be close to their peak. Gilts have joined in a
worldwide bond rally, and equities have risen on the back of this.
Takeover activity has provided the icing on the cake. Institutions are
becoming cash rich as a result. Ratings in the UK are not demanding,
certainly compared with the US, where the Dow-Jones index has built up
an 1100-point lead on the FTSE-100. The average yield on UK shares is
just below 4% against about 2.5% on Wall Street.
So far this year the Footsie has advanced by 15%, well short of the
Dow's 21%. On the face of it London has been left behind by New York.
However, the economy is slowing and margins are under pressure in some
areas.
It has been a long haul back to record-breaking territory. Even
allowing for fund managers' holidays, volumes have been low this month.
The market may have further to rise, but this is not a raging bull
market. In fact it is rather tame. So investors should not expect too
much more too quickly. If they get it takeovers will be a crucial
factor.
Points victory
THE downward revision to the second-quarter's gross domestic product
figures has given the Chancellor of the Exchequer, Kenneth Clarke,
victory on points in his long-running dispute with the Governor of the
Bank of England, Eddie George, over interest rates.
The two men have been at odds since May, but the argument has been
moving in Clarke's favour, especially in the last week. Inflation was
lower than expected in July, the pound has been given a leg up by a
rally in the dollar, and now there is evidence that the economy has
slowed down to a sustainable rate.
Second-quarter growth has been revised down from 0.6% to 0.5% against
0.7% in the first quarter. Its onshore component was restated at 0.6%
(0.7%), the same as the first quarter. Growth peaked in the second
quarter of last year when total GDP rose by 1.4% and onshore GDP by
1.3%.
The Central Statistical Office, which compiles the figures, said most
of the downward revision to the second-quarter figures was due to weaker
air transport and lower North Sea output. The latter fell by 3%, and
construction by 1.1%. However, manufacturing grew by 0.5%, electricity,
gas and water by 1%, agriculture by 2.5%, and services by 0.7%.
The key question is whether the slowdown in activity will prove
durable or there will be a bounceback in activity. Strong figures for
consumer spending, accompanying the GDP data, suggest the latter.
Consumers' expenditure grew by 0.8% in the quarter with the National
Lottery contributing about 0.2% of this. In the first quarter consumer
spending fell by 0.1%, but this now looks to have been an aberration.
Capital spending, which grew by 1.3% (disappointing at this stage in
the economic cycle), also reversed a first-quarter drop of 0.2%.
The rebound in consumption (and investment) suggests that activity
will pick up again, but the timing of this could be delayed by a stocks
overhang.
Stocks increased by #1600m in the quarter, the biggest rise since 1988
and equal to 0.6% of GDP. But stocks figures are notoriously unreliable
since they include residual errors and omissions and are subject to
massive revision.
Yesterday's CSO figures show a big deterioration in net trade, which
reduced GDP by 1% in the second quarter after increasing it by 1.4% in
the first. James Capel's Adam Cole questions this. In particular he
suspects that import volume may have been overstated and with it
stockbuilding.
Precipitate Fed
THERE is not much money going on the US Federal Reserve Board
delivering another cut in rates when its open market committee meets
today.
It last met on July 6 when the Fed funds rate was cut by a
quarter-point to 5.75%. The American banks followed with reductions in
their prime lending rates from 9% to 8.75%. But the US authorities left
the discount rate on hold at 5.25%.
At the time it was feared that the US economy would return negative
growth in the second quarter and Fed chairman Alan Greenspan did not
want to be accused of sparking off a recession. In the event the economy
turned in sharply lower growth of 0.5% in the second quarter, but since
then it has perked up again with the monthly indicators pointing to a
pick up in activity after a brief pause.
So there is no economic case for the Fed to ease rates again,
certainly not at this stage. The dollar is at last staging a useful
rally against the Japanese yen and the German mark. A rate reduction
would cut it short. Indeed many independent observers have criticised
the Fed's earlier move as precipitate.
The Bundesbank council meets on Thursday. The pundits are betting on
no change in the key discount and Lombard rates. But an easing of
inflationary pressures could enable the German authorities to justify
lower rates in the autumn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
