<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Thrilling individuality of utter freshness</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764997</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIZ AGGISS has an instinct for being unconventional. Some people have
to work hard to break rules, others rebel because they fret about going
unnoticed. Aggiss simply goes her own way, makes work that feels right
to her -- and leaves audiences thrilled by her audacity, her wit, and
her utter freshness.
It was this untrammelled individuality that led one London reviewer to
dub her 'The Vivienne Westwood of avant-garde dance'. The comparison
was, she says, ''The most wonderful thing ever said about me. Because it
places us, and the work, in a really nice niche. Gives audiences a right
good clue about us!''
Her latest venture is a solo event. ''It's just me,'' says Aggis
merrily. ''A radio mike. No music. Lots of text, lots of dance. And it's
quite visual too. What's more, it works! We've toured it around
different places and -- so far, anyway -- it's worked. It's kind of like
stand-up comedy, only it's dance. There's no equivalent word for it, so
I've started calling it stand-up dance.''
Absurditties, as the show is called, is about performing. It's about
the sudden, shifting relationship that exists between the on-stage
performer and the audience. It's an unpredictable affair, a one-sided
one even, with the performer exposed and vulnerable while the audience
chooses whether to become engaged or not.
Her collaborator in all this is musician/composer Billy Cowie. It's
his text that runs through her performance, a text full of puns and
wordplay where comedy intermingles with tragedy. ''It's that thing,''
says Aggiss, ''where the audience is moved between laughter and tears.
And often it's the music that manipulates the audience, you know --
prods them in the emotions. Here we're using words, word associations,
wordplay, instead of music.''
As we finish chatting, Aggiss muses -- ''I wonder what Vivienne
Westwood would feel about being called the 'Liz Aggiss of avant-garde
fashion'?'' I reckon she'd be well chuffed.
Divas presents Liz Aggiss in Absurditties at St Bride's Centre until
Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'My Lord . . .' Confession of a Nun, Hill Street Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764998</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE title might invoke saucy speculation but while this adaptation of
Denis Diderot's novel includes evocations of lesbian love this is
certainly not the stuff of nudge-nudge, wink-wink.
A deeply felt, scintillating performance from Maria Mamona, a Polish
actress performing in English, explores the full harrowing experience of
a young girl walled up in a convent against her will by a mother who
wants her to sacrifice her life to atone for her bastard birth.
Badly lit but beautifully staged, with a silvery bedstead and
high-backed chair becoming the bars of Mamona's prison, this is a
precious piece, tracing phases of frustration, torment, and flickering
sexuality. Gently erotic and fiercely passionate, it is played by Mamona
with luminous intensity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Alien Sex God, Hill Street Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976764999</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FRAMED within the traditional context of courtroom flashback, John
Constable's one-man show is a fantastical yarn which has him explaining
how he worked as a cook in a Little Chef in Colwyn Bay, became an
undercover agent for the North Wales Drug Squad, experimented with the
chemicals under investigation, and experienced a subsequent
''revelation'' from David Bowie that ''when you and I come together the
earth moves''.
There follows lots of mystical references to the Land of the Dead Cat,
gratuitous decadence with a desultory striptease in Berlin, manipulation
by an alien dictator and a near-cataclysmic sexual union with Bowie.
Sounds absurd? Sounds contrived? It is. It's a badly acted, thinly
veiled argument against anti-drugs legislation . . . Just say no.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tory-free Scotland could cost us all</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACLEOD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765000</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOT five years since Scots Tories astounded us all by dodging General
Election wipe out, we again predicted their ruin. In April 1992, in
fact, the party emerged with a credible quarter of the poll and a net
gain of one seat from 1987 yet, only yesterday, we read of Jim Wallace
laughing to scorn any prospect of the Conservatives matching that
performance next time; indeed, he thought they would do well to win a
tenth of the poll.
Well, we shall see.
Why do Scots increasingly hate the Tories? For one, it is felt they
have been in power far too long, should they win the next election --
and, after 1992, it would be a brave man who unhesitatingly wrote them
off -- our country will seem perilously close to a one-party state.
The Tories are unpopular in Scotland because they are seen as
culturally alien. They have also, of course, set their faces as flint
against any measure of home rule, still vigorously hostile to
constitutional reform. This makes Scottish politics boring. Many a
scribing pen, many an important radio voice, yearns for an Edinburgh
parliament and some northern arena on which to carve their own
reputation.
As recently as 1979 the Tories actually won a Scottish election: in
the first direct European poll, they took more votes and more seats than
any other party. In 1995 they hold no Euro-seats, only nine
parliamentary seats, and control not one of the new single-tier local
authorities. The looming prospect of a Tory-free Scotland tempts us to
gloat. In truth, however, it might prompt the thoughtful citizen to
worry.
Progressive Conservative annihilation is, in many ways, a sign of
sterility in the Scottish body politic. A healthy nation votes, in its
elections, on the issues before it. But too many of our polls, since
1979, have been debased into party political beauty contests. Elections
for local government are more and more referenda on affairs in London.
There is also, of course, the prevalent obsession with the
constitution; a debate in which the Tories have nothing new to say. But
too many political chatterers show a fervour on home rule unmatched in
the public at large. Most Scots agree that an Edinburgh parliament would
be a Good Thing. Few, however, immediately mention it when asked to rate
the important issues of the day. Like any sensible folk, Scots list
rather employment, housing, inflation, education, health care.
Michael Forsyth is one of our more interesting politicians. He is an
original thinker, a competent Minister -- held in some awe by civil
servants -- and not from the standard Tory mould. He is also very brave.
He deservedly won re-election to his Stirling seat in 1987, and again in
1992, against prediction and against a peculiarly personalised and nasty
campaign. He is hated by the left because he is young and articulate and
not in the least afraid of them. Sir Hector Monro, and that ilk, are the
favourite Tories of such as Brian Wilson -- old, decent, paternalistic,
unthreatening. Forsyth is in a different league, a match for any of
them, and so they loathe the man.
Forsyth's principal difficulty is that, while leading a party of the
right, -- committed to minimal government, low taxes, sound money, and a
general distrust of the public sector -- he cannot call on the emotional
power of patriotism -- in England the Tories can drape themselves in the
Union flag. In Scotland such ballyhoo is impossible. Scottish
nationalism is for others, an exuberant Britishness comes over as
English and alien. Political nationalism, as the 1992 election proved,
is much overrated in Scotland. Cultural nationalism is a different
matter entirely.
There are two or three useful things Forsyth might consider.
One is to change his party's name, and return to the old banner of the
Scottish Unionists: that would detach them from their English brethren,
and grant a distinct Scottish identity. The name has a certain ring to
it. Around a quarter of Scots remain hostile to home rule in any shape
or form, and allegiance to the Union is the cornerstone of Scots Tory
identity. Since the seventies the Conservatives have refused any truck
with devolution schemes.
Another, however, is to ponder realistically what saving the Union
might mean. Is it merely to fight and fight and fight again for the
status quo? That battle has cost the Conservatives dear. They have lost
their local government base, lost their last European seat, been driven
from the Highlands, the Borders, and Glasgow, and forfeited the support
of most of the Scottish press. Some flexibility is called for here.
There are signs that Forsyth is toying with a ''Scottish senate''
scheme, as outlined by Bill Walker.
The big question is, of course, if the Tories have in their hearts
given up all hope of retaining power at the next election. If they have,
then Forsyth and his colleagues must consider their approach to the
Scottish parliament which the Blair Government will be committed to
creating. In opposition, Conservatives will be sorely tempted to seize
upon it as a handy club to hit the Government about the head; it will be
much more difficult to steer the measure through the Commons than many
at present think.
But, if Forsyth and his friends look to regaining power early next
century -- as they should be favourites to do; Labour governments always
collapse in economic crisis -- then a Scottish parliament might be worth
keeping. Under a fair voting system, there could be a substantial Tory
presence. And a good price for preservation might be exacted: a
substantial reduction of Scottish seats at Westminster.
Still we bay for a Tory-free Scotland. Do we really want it? There is
an unpleasantly cosy consensus between the Opposition parties --
principally, a belief in the unfailing usefulness of Government
intervention, a delight in throwing lots of public money at every
problem, an unhealthy ''intellectualism'' that uses power to pursue
ideological social ends, feminism and gay rights and so forth.
At present only the Tories, in their weary and time-served way, sing
another song. A brief rest from the chorus might be welcome. But killing
the choir could cost us all.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Men Who Know, Pleasance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976765001</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALL hail the omniscient duo, Messrs Magenis and Plimmer, assisted this
year by three musicians who most definitely can, the Tiger Lillies,
whose vocalist is an arresting blend of Jimmy Somerville, Tom Waits and
Shane MacGowan.
He sings of choosing between heroin and cocaine, plus what it night be
like to be a down-and-out schizophrenic with a messiah complex.
The Men Who Know address the more taxing everyday questions which
attend every male's shuffling passage from cradle to grave. Haircuts:
which is best? Sex: where to get it? Women: why? The pair's every
utterance is an adventure; their words joyous truths. To know The Men
Who Know is to love them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Thomas Zehetmair, Greyfriars Church</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CONRAD WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976765002</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TO make Bach's music for solo violin sound technically easy is always
said to show a failure to grasp the fact that it is meant to sound
extremely difficult.
But if Thomas Zehetmair, in the first of his three late-night Bach
recitals, revealed no more strain than a Mercedes negotiating an Alpine
pass, he made clear in other ways that these sonatas and partitas remain
among the supreme challenges of the violinist's repertoire.
The challenge for this Austrian performer lay beyond the notes.
Getting these right, as the adagio and fugue of the G minor sonata
quickly demonstrated, was no problem to him. But the perfection of flow,
the clarity of articulation, the delicacy of tone were simply the means
whereby he was able to explore such matters as exactly how beautiful the
music should sound, how energetic it should be, how rigorous its rythms,
how dance-like its pulse.
Speed, too, was an issue, though not in the ostentatious sense -- for,
once again, these were performances that went beyond ostentation. Yet
they certainly moved. Seldom has one felt less conscious of time passing
than in these keenly integrated performances, which allowed no room for
self-indulgence, for phrases sentimentally shaped or unfurled with
slippery smoothness. Everything seemed to have been scrupulously
weighed, studied, polished, then delivered with an intenseness that
avoided all hint of glibness.
Yet there was also an appreciation of the romance of Bach's music, of
the sort that divides perceptive Bach playing from the dryly competent.
In the first movement of the B minor partita, the sudden switch from
jerky rhythms to flowing semiquavers was the marvellous moment Bach
surely intended it to be. The music became airborne. Then in the
flickering presto of the succeeding courante it flew even higher. This
was Bach playing of both authority and nuance whetting the appetite for
tonight's instalment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Panocha Quartet, Queen's Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976765003</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOME disappointing playing yesterday from the Panocha Quartet in their
second appearance at the Queen's Hall, where their programme was devoted
to the last two string quartets by Dvorak.
Part of the Panocha style -- and indeed, part of their attraction --
has been their tendency to play with restraint and reserve.
Characteristically, they sound as though they are having a private
conversation, in which the audience are onlookers, hearing every word.
Yesterday -- at the outset -- that discretion became something more
retiring, with the effect that the performance of the A flat Quartet was
merely tentative. Intonation and direction were unsettled, and busy
contrapuntal passages -- not the strong point of the Panochas anyway --
became a bit of a scramble, with sometimes a complete loss of harmonic
and tonal focus. Rapid changes of mood -- such as the change from serene
to ardent music in the third movement -- were conducted impetuously,
leaving the group sounding ill at ease.
Maybe it was the intense heat in the hall, who knows? Anyway, after
the interval, the players seemed to draw themselves together, producing
something more like their familiar, relaxed form in the G major Quartet,
notably in the great, slow movement where the first violin melody
entered on a bed of gorgeous string sound provided by the rest of the
group.
* Sponsored by Bank of Scotland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Phil Kay, Queen's Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976765004</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHY did you laugh? Phil at one point asked a mirth-convulsed member of
the front row. ''I've no idea,'' came the reply. ''That's the ticket!''
Phil replied. Indeed.
Phil Kay, Prince of Daftie. He makes you laugh. Not sure why. Not sure
how. But he does. By keeping soap in his sock. By staging impromptu
waltzing competitions. By imagining live ducks as footballer's shinpads.
By dividing the auditorium into two volleyball teams, the Halibuts and
the Peanut-Crunchers, and staging a match. Yon Phil Kay. As
audience-members, ours is not to reason why; ours is to laugh until we
cry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Folk Songs of North East Scotland, ScottishPower Gallery, Festival Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ADAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976765005</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INTRODUCING a programme of themes common to Highland and Lowland
cultures, the grand old man of Scottish folk music, Hamish Henderson,
stopped just short of accusing Highlanders of procuring Lowland tunes in
the same way as they procured cattle.
Just as well because there was enough fighting going on. Battles at
Killiecrankie and Harlaw, to name but two, raged as Norman Kennedy, in
splendidly weighty Doric tones, and Margaret Bennett, a clear Gaelic
singer if prone at times to over excitability, joined in.
From one F-word to another, both implicitly and explicitly, Kennedy
sang of amateur gynaecologists metaphorically stabling their stallions
before Henderson offered a more robust version. Whether Bennett's Golden
Cave continued this theme, I can't say, but it was a smashing song well
sung in another entertaining and well-subscribed trip to the Festival
Theatre's high-altitude folk club.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
