<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No nudes is good news in America</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RUTH WISHART</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL DIARY</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976765008</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN Edinburgh to catch some theatre before hurling back to London for a
gig with husband Julian Glover, was actress Isla Blair, star of the
final saga in the dramatisation of Michael Dobbs's House of Cards. Mr
Dobbs, you will recall, has already passed through the Book Festival,
loudly lamenting changes to the denouement of his yarn, and proclaiming
the state funeral of the Baroness Thatcher on television to be in bad
taste. (Speak for yourself, ducks.) However, the mini-series has
presented rather different problems for Ms Blair as she recounted over
much merriment during lunch with mutual pals.
She plays the PM's parliamentary private secretary, but is also having
an affair with the Foreign Secretary. And no, that's not her problem.
Parts for ladies of a certain age which include on-screen bonking with
fetching men are enough of a rarity to send female actors rushing to the
gym rather than the censor.
The problem transpires to be American coyness. Yes, you heard right.
For while US movies are not notably sensitive over matters sexual,
American television as screened by the Public Broadcasting Service is
quite another kettle of complexes. This series having been co-produced
with PBS, it therefore had to be scrutinised to make sure there was
absolutely nothing to offend network sensitivities. And on PBS, no nudes
is good nudes.
So Isla and co-star Paul Freeman had to reshoot a bedroom scene -- she
in hastily acquired black negligee and he in his undies. So far, so
silly. But wait. There is another problem, the actors are informed. They
will need to come back and redub the sound for the scene in question.
Apparently their orgasms topped the legal US sexibel count!
And aren't you glad you'll be seeing the version made for good old
raunchy Britain.
* AS we all know, do we not, Irish playwrights are a breed apart.
Hellraisers to a man. Think then of the damage being done to the
collective reputation by Frank McGuinness, author of the much-acclaimed
Observe the Sons of Ulster Marching Towards the Somme. For while
Edinburgh heaves with blithe spirits doing joined-up partying, your man
has left town for a few days. To go, bejasus, to Iona.
* ALAS poor Bluefest, we never knew you well. But as the ill-fated
Lesbian and Gay Festival quits this parish clutching a Herald Devil by
way of compensation, at least one solo performer will be seen again in
Scotland this year. Gerry, sometimes known as Jenni Potter, is Chloe
Poems or alternatively Paddy Fields. Confused? You certainly will be. So
perhaps I should add that Gerry/Jenny is a Scouser whose character,
Fields, is a Tory MP by day metamorphosing into Chloe, transvestite
socialist poet by night, and known to her legion of admirers as The
Gingham Diva.
I'd like to tell you that it's unmissable but it closed before I got
there. However, Gerry with Jenny and Paddy and Chloe have now been
booked for Glasgay! this autumn and will be at the Arches from November
1.
* STRIDING manfully at the head of 3000 pipers on Sunday afternoon,
the square-jawed figure of Gavin Hastings heaving a thigh for Marie
Curie. Trotting along apologetically at the rear, Fringe press officer
Alison Forsyth who was really just trying to get to Fringe Sunday in the
Park. It took her two-and-a-half hours but then again she's now note
perfect in five reels and a Strathspey.
* DURING his appearance at the Book Festival, BBC diplomatic editor
John Simpson guessed that the way things were going he could be back in
Bosnia in a few days.
In fact, the way things went, he would end up in Amman. Which was very
bad news for one little old lady in Sarajevo. A Serbian resident in a
housing block whose other residents have no reason to love her
countryfolk, she is largely ignored by her neighbours and has no means
of support. Which is why Simpson always visits her with what supplies he
can.
Proof that journalism is not entirely peopled by folk selling their
grannies for stories.
* AND now, an important SOS. James Clapperton, the Aberdeenshire-born
composer and pianist, had his new work Elrich Fantasyis played by the
Hebrides Ensemble on Sunday as part of the Scottish Premiere Series
sponsored by my own dear Radio Scotland. Unfortunately such home games
are a novelty for Mr Clapperton. Although he'd love to come back and
work in his beloved North-east, all his employment opportunities emanate
from the deep south where he is currently exiled with his Canadian wife.
So perhaps out there somewhere is an oil multi-national with the wit
to commission half-a-dozen concertos or sponsor a residency.
Listen, the boy can't find anyone in Sussex with the Doric.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>France faces legal challenge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765009</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE HAGUE: New Zealand, in a bid to block France's planned nuclear
tests in the South Pacific, as asked the International Court of Justice
to re-examine a 1974 nuclear test case against France.
Wellington is seeking an interim injunction to stop the series of up
to eight underground blasts at Mururoa Atoll in French Polynesia. A
court official confirmed that New Zealand was attempting to reopen legal
action, filed in 1973, against French testing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANNE SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765010</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FASTER and faster the authority of Ireland's Catholic hierarchy is
unravelling. But the composure of the men who wield the croziers has
been shaky ever since those incidents, three years ago, when official
subterfuge was seen to have compounded the sin of paedophilia among
certain errant priests, and Annie Murphy ousted a bishop by venting an
abandoned lover's wrath.
Now more turmoil is being visited on the Catholic establishment by
another of their own as Brendan Comiskey, the Bishop of Ferns, almost
daily urges the church to listen to the questioning voice of the laity
and not denounce its desire for a debate on priestly celibacy. There is,
perhaps, an element of opportunism here.
Comiskey, after all, has never been a notable liberal although there
are those who now describe him as Catholicism's Martin Luther, a man of
spirit resolutely challenging the orthodoxy of Rome.
But more quickly than most of his brother bishops, Comiskey has
grasped the fact that much of the faithful already regard the Irish
hierarchy as obsolete. ''A huge reservoir of goodwill is being lost,''
he says, ''by a perception among major sections of our population that
they are not being heard.''
Such reflection is hardly the stuff of heresy but, coupled with
Comiskey's implication that marriage should not be outlawed for priests,
it has been sufficient to mark him down as an agitator deserving of a
clip around the mitre from Ireland's conservative Cardinal, Dr Cahal
Daly, and its papal nuncio.
Not that this has silenced the bishop. Instead the initial rebukes
only brought to the surface the high level of support for his opinions,
persuading the Cardinal that a measure of appeasement might be better
than outright war.
So, contrary to rumour, when Brendan Comiskey is summoned to the
Vatican next month to explain his views there will be, in the words of
one Rome-watcher, ''no chopping off of the head, or anything else'', but
a low-key mannerly discussion with Cardinal Bernardin Gantin of the
papal court.
Even so the malaise in the Irish church -- so outwardly unthinkable 10
years ago -- can no longer be disguised, its root cause being the
xenophobic fundamentalism which has maimed religious practice in the
past. Today with the old nationalist party Fianna Fail in disarray, and
Europhile politicians in the ascendant, De Valera's snug alliance
between church and state is finally over.
As evidence the coalition government, the other day, allocated a
#500,000 budget to promote a Yes vote in November's divorce referendum.
Meanwhile a recent international survey indicates that compared to the
rest of Western Europe Irish Catholics are ignoring the church's
teaching on social issues in greater numbers than elsewhere.
As to the issue of sexual abuse, the sense of betrayal among people
remains profound, and for those victims directly involved it is
difficult to see how any recompense will ever fully heal wounds hidden
by fear for so long. But on the subject of married priests there is no
public shock or horror at the proposal.
Significantly it was not Dr Eamonn Casey's affair with the American
divorcee, Annie Murphy, which scandalised people but the fact that he
rejected her when she became pregnant, then secretly siphoned off church
funds to support their child.
All this, of course, gave the Casey episode a Faustian dimension,
forcing his resignation as Bishop of Galway, and redemptive exile as a
missionary in Latin America. But if nothing else Casey's mortal frailty
exposed the cruel puritanism of the celibacy rule. The real concerns
were that he, like other priests, had been driven into aberrant
behaviour by a terror of the truth, and had also been able to cover his
tracks because others of high rank colluded to ensure nothing tarnished
his public image.
Yet braver priests wishing to marry were, and still are, pleading for
Rome's blessing only to be drummed out of the church as subversives,
often forced to suffer the whisperings of sanctimonious bigots. But
among radical clergy there is an acceptance that anyone trying to divert
the timid steps already taken towards cultural pluralism in Ireland is,
at last, on a loser. Ireland, semper fidelis, always faithful . . . not
even those who hear the sins of the people can be sure the ancient
incantation still holds sway. In this, the last five years of the
twentieth century, that old gravitational pull towards the confessional
is also in decline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ultimate bond of purging sorrow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FILM FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976765011</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WILLIAM RUSSELL applauds a sensitive Irish film about family bonding,
a short Scottish films tackling issues of male sexual fantasies, and an
unusual story of alienation.
SCOTTISH cinema has been putting up an unusually strong showing at
this year's Film Festival, so Cathal Black's captivating Korea, based on
a short story by John McGahern, is a timely reminder of how good Irish
cinema can be. It draws on Ireland's past to great emotional effect.
Although only 75 minutes long, it is too slow for its own good, but a
little cutting would do the trick.
Ravishingly photographed by Nic Morris, it is set in the early 1950s
before the EC bonanza transformed rural Ireland into the Promised Land.
The story centres on village life round a lake in Cavan where Eamon
Doyle, sensitively played by Andrew Scott, lives with his embittered
widower father John -- a beautifully judged performance from Donal
Donnelly.
Eamon is helping his father while waiting for his exam results on
which his future depends. John is a freshwater fisherman whose
livelihood is at risk, the authorities preferring to keep the fish stock
for the tourists.
Eamon is in love with Una Moran (Fiona Molony), whose father, Ben, is
the water bailiff. John Doyle detests him for reasons that go back to
the time of the Troubles. Ben's son Luke, who emigrated to America, has
been killed in Korea, hence the title. John insists that Eamon, who has
''got the education'', must go there too, a ploy to get him away from
the Morans.
It is a mood music piece, and Black has used the waters of the lake,
the eels struggling in their traps, the rain streaming down, the
sunshine piercing the clouds and catching the water's surface, and the
greens of the countryside to enhance this tale about a sorrow purged as
father and son come to understand one another at last.
Scottish cinema is represented by The Contract, a short film written
and directed by Ewan Morrison. A sharp-edged black comedy, it tackles
male sexual fantasies without actually indulging in any on-screen sex,
which does make a change. A young man, obsessed with the philosophy of
Leopold Von Sacher Masoch, goes to a sex therapist, played with style by
Jacqueline Pierce, a born Madame Whiplash, for help.
They make a contract -- she is to abuse him in the hope this will cure
his fantasies. Shot in black and white by Kathleen Friend, it makes
highly imaginative use of its Glasgow locations, notably the City
Chambers, to suggest an ornate, exotic world in which perversions can
occur quite naturally.
Another interesting Scottish film was Morag McKinnon's 3, a 75-minute
feature made for a mere #40,000. A story of myth, magic and alienation
it is visually astonishing, but suffers from some dreadful acting and a
script which, when it is not unspeakable, is highfalutin rubbish.
Carl, a graphic designer, haunted by a mysterious figure, The Elder
(Tam Dean Burn), seeks the help of a fey girl singer called Sri to do
something or other, find himself I think. The highly imaginative opening
sequence in which Carl is born augurs well, and some good songs follow,
but the real achievement was getting it made at all. Given a decent
script and more money, Ms McKinnon should go far.
* Korea, 9.30pm, Cameo 1
* The Contract, 6.30pm, Filmhouse 2
* 3, run ended yesterday
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Business of sport</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765012</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I HAVE, I suppose, for a West of Scotland fiftysomething male, an
ambivalent -- some might say deviant -- attitude to competitive sport.
The desire to participate is fast slipping away. But neither it nor the
will to compete, in my case, was anything like turbo-charged in the
first place.
Contemporaries who still play serious five-a-side football or pull on
a veteran's rugby jersey seem to me near-certifiable. My early
scientific training baulks at a recently reported academic finding that
baseball-playing countries enjoy economic growth rates 123% higher than
those which prefer the more leisurely pace of cricket. Sport can't be
that important, I reassure myself.
I enjoy watching football and rugby, golf and athletics, but only up
to a point which is, as often as not, reached long before the final
whistle has blown or the winning putt has dropped. Team tribalism or an
encyclopaedic knowledge of the personalities and performances involved
in this sport or that leave me, for the most part, in a state of
marginalised indifference.
Last week's orgy of Ally McCoist worship on the sports pages for
putting one past the Greeks had me thoroughly bemused. Wasn't Super
Ally, according to those same pundits, a yard or two off the pace not so
long ago after breaking a leg, a charmer dogged by injury, in the
twilight of his competitive career?
But I'm not so much of a sporting curmudgeon that I can't thrill at
McCoist's chutzpah, marvel at the diminutive Ethiopian Gebreselassie
slicing 11 seconds off the world 5000 metres record, or revel in Brian
Lara's effortless stroke play. It's just that, in my life, sport is of
distinctly secondary significance.
I still try to swim every week and may soon, thanks to the brimming
enthusiasm of a newly teenage son, be lured back on to the tee to
address a little white ball I last seriously confronted in the deep
rough of the Whinhill public course high above Greenock, in my own
teens. Ewan's already got me back to the snooker table although I've
left it to his granda to introduce him to the bowling green.
I bought a bike last year, but have used it almost exclusively for
undemanding family outings. Ten years ago I ran a couple of marathons
within six weeks of each other (3hrs 47mins and 3hrs 36mins
respectively, for the statistical omnivores among you), lured into the
experience by a Stewart McIntosh campaign in this newspaper to bring
fitness through running to the over-forties.
McIntosh's big sell to guinea pig friends like me was the chance to
train and get fit under the supervision of cardiologists at Glasgow's
Western Infirmary. McIntosh has much to answer for. The reality was
that, after the trauma of the tests the medicos inflicted on us,
pounding round 26 and a bit miles of Inverclyde or Glasgow was a breeze.
How would you like to be sat on a monocycle, clutching a large steel
sphere (enclosing a gamma camera) with both arms, pedalling to
exhaustion against a wickedly rising braking strain, while assorted
white-coated technicians draw blood every few minutes from one arm and
inject a gold isotope into a cannula in the other, just so they can take
pretty coloured snaps of a heart near bursting point? Sad to say, I've
hardly run the length of myself since. Swimming, they tell me, is less
punishing on the knee and ankle joints.
But, no matter how hard I try, I can't quite manage a complete divorce
from competitive sport. It's not just the expectations of our resident
sports-mad teenager. It's not just the social hospitality whirl which,
occasionally, catches journalists like me in its eddies.
It's the fact that I'm supposed to know something about business. And,
as business and competitive sport become more and more enmeshed, I get
dragged in professionally, from time to time, to dissect the
balance-sheet implications of, for example, booting a ball around a
football pitch.
My own modest financial relationship with sport has never wavered from
a bright red deficit. A recent afternoon at Hamilton races left me #20
the poorer, with not one winner to my credit. I should have known
better.
But I can read a balance sheet. So, when editors or newsdesks get
excited about this sporting business deal or that, I tend to get
involved. I try, as I always try to do in mainstream business stories,
to get at the facts.
When David Murray first took control of Rangers, I was the only person
in the newsroom who had ever met him or knew anything about him. I wrote
a lot of the background copy. When, a few years later, I carried out a
critical investigation of Murray's involvement in property development,
you would have thought I had personally planted land mines all over the
Ibrox centre circle.
Those property interests were rapidly restructured. But, in the way
that competitive sport can distort normal human behaviour, I stood
accused of waging some sort of personal vendetta against the Rangers
chairman. I am not, as it happens, much into vendettas.
More recently, in an even-handed sort of way, I helped to carry out a
critical assessment of the Celtic share prospectus. I was summoned to
Parkhead for a three-hour re-education programme by Fergus McCann's
financial advisers. I stuck to my downbeat analysis. The fans plunged in
anyway and left the issue hugely over-subscribed.
I've been back to both Ibrox and Parkhead since. David Murray chooses
not to speak to me. Recently, at Parkhead for the Liverpool friendly, I
met Fergus McCann again. ''Yes, you're the journalist who thinks
football is a business,'' he greeted me, with a twinkle in his eye. ''I
used to think that when I first came here.'' And off he went, chuckling,
to shake other hands.
I recommend to both of them an interview with Chelsea director Matthew
Harding in yesterday's FT. Harding has put #24m of the #125m fortune he
has made from the insurance market into the team he loves.
''I don't want it back,'' he says. ''I also don't want to turn it into
#48m by virtue of a stock market flotation. But I would be bloody
mortified if the effect of that #24m was worthless.'' There speaks the
wealthy fan who knows that the only real profit earners in sport are the
elite sportsmen and women who were a lot further up the queue than I was
when the right genes were being handed out.
</TEXT>
