<HEADLINE>Scottish Chamber Orchestra, Usher Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976765013</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was always going to be Boris Pergamenschikow's night. Anyone who
heard the Russian cellist last weekend playing with Andras Schiff's
quintet was immediately struck by the huge, rounded sound he made, his
fabulous technique, and the rock-solid playing that poured from his
gorgeously rich, eighteenth-century Montagnana cello.
And apart from all that, in last night's marathon concert featuring
all three of Dvorak's concertos, Pergamenschikow, with the Cello
Concerto, quite simply had the best material to play. And he made the
most of it, piling in with a big, impassioned sound and phenomenal
articulation. He's a real lyricist of the instrument, completely
eschewing all the fancy tricks like half-breathed sounds and effete,
pseudo-poetic musical gestures.
Pergamenschikow, one of the most formidable cellists of the day, is
robust. That's the word for him. Everything he does is characterised by
a ruggedness. It's not insensitive -- far from it; in the slow-movement
beauties, or the ravishing moments at the end of the concerto, he was as
delicate as any master cellist. But what he has, and never lets slip, is
the ability to imbue everything he plays with a soulful intensity. It
marked every bar of his performance.
And the Scottish Chamber Orchestra, with Sir Charles Mackerras at the
helm, added their own layer of intensity with some magnificent playing,
and a fierce concentration that suggested they had been waiting most of
the night to get their teeth into something.
Not that there hadn't been some good things earlier. Andras Schiff,
opening the concert, had squeezed as much juice and sparkle out of the
Piano Concerto as there was to be had. His performance -- amazingly
dexterous in the face of Dvorak's torrential keyboard writing --
revealed an infectiously amiable piece, for all its longueurs and
gaucheries.
Less happy altogether was Yuuko Shiokawa's performance of the Violin
Concerto. It was almost as though she stood back from the piece, playing
it without identifying with its warmth. This was harsh, bright, and
soulless playing, with no lilt to its rhythms, no tenderness at its
core.
The SCO and Sir Charles Mackerras, accompanying stoically throughout
all this, had their own brief chance to shine -- which they did not miss
-- in an atmospheric and highly charged account of the incident-packed
symphonic poem, The Noonday Witch.
A long night, and not for the faint-hearted, though it has to be said
that the Usher Hall, steamingly hot, was packed to the rafters,
continuing to reflect very high sales this year for the orchestral
series. This, evidently, is a festival audience that is scared of
nothing. Bravo to them.
* Sponsored by NEC Semiconductors (UK) Ltd.
</TEXT>
