<HEADLINE>The slender epic. Sadko, Edinburgh Festival Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CONRAD WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765014</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A company with Rimsky in its bones brings conviction to this tale of
bards and sea nymphs.
IF Sheherazade contains Rimsky-Korsakov's most enduring orchestral
seascapes, then Sadko is its more massive operatic equivalent. Why,
then, is it so rarely staged outside Russia? The answer -- well, one
answer -- was provided by the Kirov Opera last night in a performance
that demonstrated how utterly Russian the piece undoubtedly is. A
production of it by Scottish Opera would be unimaginable.
Only a company with Rimsky in its bones could bring conviction, one
suspects, to this tale of bards and sea nymphs, in which singers and
dancers intermingle in a series of spectacular tableaux.
But there is another answer to the work's general neglect and that is
the sheer voluminosity of its structure. Because, in a very Russian way,
so many advisers got in on the act, what could have been a simple
fairy-tale ended up mixing elements of Swan Lake, Peer Gynt, and The
Odyssey in a four-hour epic whose slenderness of material became more
and more evident as it proceeded.
Conviction, however, the Kirov performance -- there will be another
tonight -- certainly possessed. Big tableau-esque operas are tailor-made
for big Russian companies, and Sadko, with its quayside and underwater
scenes, was predictably splendid.
Colour was employed with a vibrancy that made you wish someone would
do the same for Wagner's Ring -- a work by no means distant in intention
from Rimsky's Russian epic. Vladimir Galusin's portrayal of the tenor
hero certainly stressed the point, as also did Evgenia Tselovalnik and
Valentina Tsidipova in the roles of wife and seductress.
But the galvanising force, as in last week's performances of Kitezh,
was Valery Gergiev as conductor of the rough-edged but grandly sonorous
Kirov orchestra.
Rimsky, often dismissed as a cold technician, emerged as a composer
poetic and fanciful. And the biggest stage in Britain -- in spite of too
many offstage bangs and thuds -- showed that it could successfully
accommodate opera on the largest scale.
</TEXT>
