<HEADLINE>Dressing down as golfers get hot under the collar</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM SHIELDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>DIARY</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765015</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVEN in this oxter-searing hot weather, golf course gauleiters are
immovable in their dress code rigour. The hon. sec. of Balmore Golf Club
near Glasgow has seen fit to write to members ''following upon numerous
complaints regarding the deterioration in dress standards''.
We presume that golfers at Balmore have been going around the
clubhouse with top buttons on their shirts shamelessly undone. Some of
them may even have been exposing their legs.
The letter warns of seriously sweaty consequences: ''In the event of
the decline in standards continuing, Council will have no alternative
but to re-introduce a dress rule of jacket, collar, and tie at all
times.''
The hon. sec. reminds members that jacket, collar, and tie must be
worn in the lounge and dining room of the clubhouse after 7pm on
Saturdays and Sundays.
Tee-shirts, denim-style trousers, and trainers are a definite no-no
anywhere at any time. Shorts are permitted but only if tailored and worn
with top hose, as favoured by the British district commissioner in those
Somerset Maugham films set in the tropics.
Rising to the bait
THE scene is a small loch above Plockton where Hughie, a friend of a
friend of the Diary, turns up at 5am for a spot of fishing. He notices
there is a ground sheet and a collapsible stool occupying one of the
better spots on the lochside.
But there is no sign of any angler. Where is he? Has he drowned? The
mystery is solved when the angler turns up to claim his spot at 8am.
Yes, he was a German.
Splash hit
MORE tourist tales. This time the scene is the top of a sight-seeing
bus parked near the Scott Monument. An American lady asks her husband:
''Who was this man Scott anyway?'' He replies: ''You know, honey. He was
the guy who put his kilt in a puddle for Queen Victoria.''
Losing number
JUST one digit has prevented an exodus of staff from the Scottish
Conservative Party Scottish headquarters. The winning numbers for
Saturday's National Lottery were 5, 8, 23, 24, 28, and 48. The Tory
party staff had five of the numbers but 29 instead of 28.
The syndicate, including campaign director David Canzini and press
officer Bill Shaw, won a #1500 third prize instead of the #3.8m jackpot.
Captive audience
THERE has always been something exotic about the names chosen by
Rangers supporters clubs. Like the Bellshill Chosen Few, the Honest Toun
Loyal, the Hull and Grimsby True Blues, not to mention the Mark Hateley
(Sunderland) Loyal. To this proud legion of clubs we can add a new name,
Her Majesty's Prison Shotts Rangers Supporters Club.
According to the fans' notes in the Rangers News, ''interested
supporters must be season tranny holders''. We presume this is a
reference to transistor radios which would be the true blue inmates'
method of access to Rangers matches. They certainly will not be getting
out to many games.
The contact for the Shotts prison club is Jim Baillie, prisoner 1046
in C Hall. The supporters' notes contributed by Mr Baillie to the Gers
newspaper are pretty cryptic but it appears he relies on videos made by
fans on the outside to keep the blue flame burning while he is an
enforced, and we presume entirely loyal, guest of Her Majesty.
Service resumed
THE ceasefire in Northern Ireland has brought a small but welcome
peace dividend to visitors to Edinburgh. During the Troubles, the Tattoo
was recognised as a prime terrorist target. Thus the Royal Mail
letterboxes on the Royal Mile were traditionally blocked up and put out
of service for the duration of the military entertainment at the castle.
This year it is different. The peace process has brought literally a
chink of light. The letterboxes have been adapted to incorporate a slit
in the metal just wide enough for the tourists to pop in their
postcards.
Recipe for success
WE should know better than to rely on the publisher's blurb when
writing about new books. Keeping up with Magda we said was a bit of
bodice-ripping debut of a novel by Isla Dewar, laying bare the seething
sexual undercurrents of a fishing village not a million miles away from
Anstruther in the east Neuk of Fife.
We have had a chance to read it and, while there is a high-hormone
factor, the book is mainly notable for its acute observations of
small-town life. The motor mechanic who spots that a car belonging to a
newcomer to town needs a new exhaust. He slips under the car and does a
temporary repair with some string. Not out of any sense of a friendly
welcome. He didn't want to risk the exhaust finally breaking down
elsewhere.
The eponymous Magda is a wonderfully strong female character. Asked by
the town Mary Whitehouse if she is against sex before marriage, Magda
replies: ''Absolutely. It rumples your wedding frock and your veil goes
all askew.''
Asked her opinion of men she replies that, on balance, she is in
favour of them: ''They're one of my favourite sorts of human being. I'd
let my daughter marry one. But I wouldn't want to be one.''
What the publishers missed in their blurb was the sheer sensuality of
Magda's cooking -- the duckling with baby turnips, smoked fish
omelettes, pesto-topped baked salmon, buttered brioche spread with
bitter marmalade dipped in fresh orange juice and baked in a creamy
vanilla custard. Now that's the stuff to get the juices flowing.
</TEXT>
