<HEADLINE>Student denies pistol shot menaced prince</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765016</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sydney
A STUDENT who fired a track starter's pistol at the Prince of Wales
during a royal visit to Australia last year went on trial in Sydney
today.
David Kang, 24, denied threatening unlawful violence to the heir to
the throne.
The incident happened in a central Sydney park on January 26, 1994,
during a ceremony to mark Australia's national day.
Kang was arrested seconds after he lunged on to a stage where Prince
Charles was standing. The prince was unharmed.
Prosecutor Patrick Power told the court that Kang struck after he
wrote a letter complaining about the Australian Government's detention
of Cambodian boat people.
Kang, who is of Korean origin, had psychiatric treatment for months
after his arrest.
The prosecutor said that in a videotaped interview, Kang told police
he had been surprised that no guards had shot him as he ran towards the
prince.
At earlier hearings Kang's lawyers argued that he never intended to
harm the prince. If convicted he is likely to receive a brief prison
sentence or fine.
* High Court Judge William Deane was today appointed Australia's next
governor-general until the end of the century, when the Labour
Government hopes to end formal links with Britain and create a republic.
Deane would replace Bill Hayden as the local representative of the
Queen on February 16, Prime Minister Paul Keating said.
He added that Sir William would end his appointment the day before
January 1, 2001, Keating's target date for the Australian
republic.--AP/Reuter.
</TEXT>
