<HEADLINE>'I just love this -- reading, writing, interviewing people'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DICK LOUDEN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDUCATION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765017</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Pupils can't get enough of the creative challenges offered by a new
joint supported-study scheme, reports DICK LOUDEN.
A GREAT deal of favourable publicity has been generated recently by
supported study schemes, under which pupils from areas of priority
treatment come into school after normal hours and study in a pleasant
environment with support from teachers and access to resources.
While Strathclyde region was developing these innovative schemes, the
Prince's Trust, a registered charity, was funding others in Belfast,
London, Bradford and Liverpool. Now the two have come together and
expanded their focus by offering one-week summer supported study
schemes, whose aim is to develop pupil skills in areas such as drama,
music-making, graphic arts and video production.
At Linwood High in Renfrewshire 20 pupils from first year upwards
produced the first issue of a school magazine and set up a pupil
committee to oversee future editions. The youngsters were involved in
writing, editing, desktop publishing, layout, design and advertising --
and also enhanced their social skills through working within the
framework of a team.
They were guided by three teachers -- Lesley Hinde, Eddie Mack, and
Shirley Jones, the project co-ordinator, whosaid: ''The pupils were
volunteers. Before the summer we held lunchtime meetings and divided
them into three groups -- design, content, and technical. We then
sub-divided them into news, features, sport and public relations. We
have decided on the name -- PA3: Linwood High School magazine. It will
be produced twice a year and the first edition will be issued free to
all our parents and sponsors.''
She was delighted by the children's enthusiasm -- ''Some of them turn
up at half past eight and they won't even take their full lunch hour.''
For second-year pupil Ian King it was ''far better than sitting at home,
wondering what to do. I'm doing telephone calls to find advertisers at
#5 for up to a half-page. We're getting plenty of adverts -- some
businesses are getting them free because they've given us competition
prizes.''
Emily Brook, entering sixth year, wants to do a general degree before
becoming a journalist. ''I've been working on contents and PR,'' she
explained. ''Apart from preparing thank-you letters to sponsors, I've
done an article on the Bon Jovi concert in Sheffield, which I attended.
I might also write an opinion piece on our school uniform and what
changes might be made to it.''
Second-year pupil Johanne Paton was enthusiasm personified. ''I love
English, I love to fantasise, I love to speak my mind,'' she said. ''I
want to be an actress. The first morning was excellent. I phoned Asda
and this woman called Patsy gave me two #5 vouchers. I know the
shopkeepers, so I've written to them all. I just love this -- reading,
writing, going out to interview people, being part of a team, knowing
something will come of it.''
Now the Prince's Trust has expanded its sponsorship of supported study
to Lothian, in collaboration with the regional council and
ScottishPower, by running a summer school, based in Leith Academy, for
more than 200 third-year pupils from across the region.
The initiative was designed to focus on investigation and project
management skills as well as personal and social development. Andrew
Gibb, Scottish fund-raising director for the trust, hopes that the
summer school will be the catalyst for introducing supported study after
school hours into many Lothian secondaries this session.
This view is echoed by Anne Marie Carrie, project co-ordinator of the
summer school and Lothian's principal officer in charge of secondary
schools. ''Thanks to the trust and the region, we have funding to
establish evening supported study in three Edinburgh high schools --
Castlebrae, Craigroyston and Wester Hailes,'' she said, ''and we hope
that feedback from youngsters and staff involved in the summer school
will provide the impetus for other schools to start their own schemes.''
Forty teachers, all from different Lothian schools, were selected from
numerous volunteers and given a training programme. ''We looked for the
ability to work collaboratively,'' explained Anne Marie Carrie, ''and to
take a generic rather than subject-based approach.''
The pupils were nominated by staff of their own schools, usually on
the basis that they could obtain positive benefit in the approach to
next year's Standard Grade exams, or because they were not fulfilling
their potential through lack of social advantages at home. They were
invited to attend full-time for a week, selecting from several
activities, but such was the enthusiasm that many asked to return for
further weeks.
Kirsty McEwan, from Deans Community High in Livingston, admitted that
it had been ''better than I thought. Among the activities I chose were
confidence-building techniques -- like relaxation and role playing --
and roller-blading. I thought we'd have to write all the time but we've
had workshops, projects and group presentations.''
Another Deans pupil, Mandy Chan, who like Kirsty returned for a second
week, enjoyed ''working with pupils from other schools. We did a drama
workshop about teenagers stealing from shops. I also selected face
painting, the Internet and writing skills, to help me with my stories.''
David Skene from Castlebrae High joined the summer school because his
PE teacher told him he would get help on how to go about his PE Standard
Grade investigation for the new session. ''It was good,'' he said. ''I
was told all about the content, the layout and the amount of material to
put into it.''
An evaluation of the Leith Academy initiative is being undertaken by
Dr Brian Boyd, associate director of the Quality in Education Centre at
Strathclyde University. ''We issued the pupils at the start with a
questionnaire about their attitudes and we shall be conducting a
follow-up exercise in September to assess how attitudes have changed,''
he said. ''At the request of the Prince's Trust I shall also be
producing a handbook which can be used in connection with future summer
schools.''
</TEXT>
