<HEADLINE>Quality in quantity</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ERIC KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>MY JOB</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765018</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Quantity Surveyor: It's a profession that can take you far, learns
Eric Kennedy.
THESE days you don't have to join the Navy to see the world. How about
the unlikely profession of quantity surveying? ''A large proportion of
quantity surveyors have been involved in overseas work at some time or
other,'' says Keith Gourlay. And he should know -- he has worked in
Qatar and Tanzania.
He was abroad for two years and over four years respectively, handling
large-scale projects and enjoying a fairly high-flying lifestyle. ''But
even if you are working in dreary old Britain, you normally get out and
about a bit, meeting people,'' he says.
Quantity surveyors are responsible for the measuring and valuing of
building or civil engineering work. Those working for contractors act on
their employers' behalf, and those working on private contracts act on
behalf of the building or project owner.
Keith Gourlay entered the profession on leaving Falkirk High School in
1978, taking a job with a local private practice and attending Napier
College (now University) in Edinburgh one-and-a-half days a week. The
firm paid for that, and this was the accepted way into quantity
surveying at that time.
Nowadays about 95% of people take a degree course, at Napier,
Caledonian, or other college or university, graduating BSc. Some,
however, still take the day-release route. Either way, it entails a
great deal of hard work and home study.
Keith's way meant a five-year slog. He left his original employers,
who were encountering difficult times, just before completing his
studies and becoming an Associate of the Royal Institution of Chartered
Surveyors. He was a qualified surveyor, but to become a chartered
surveyor one must take a Test of Professional Competence.
This has to be preceded by the keeping of a diary of professional
experience for three years, under supervision.
Keith Gourlay sat and passed this in 1988, as it had not been possible
to do so earlier as the types of jobs he had meanwhile undertaken did
not offer access to this professional supervision. But meantime he
gained some terrific experience, taking jobs with another Falkirk firm
for two years before heading for Qatar to become involved in top-secret
Ministry of Defence projects for a further two years. He also had a year
out, in between times.
It was in 1987 that he returned to Britain, working with a major
contractor and concentrating full-time on a major refurbishment of
Perth's Salutation Hotel, the oldest in Scotland. His firm won a #30,000
bonus for completing the project ahead of time.
It was also, however, running into problems as the construction
industry continued to decline after the boom years of the seventies; so
he left to join a major building and engineering contractor, involved in
the #1.6m refurbishment of high-rise flats in Glasgow.
Then it was time to go abroad again, and 1989 saw him in Dar-es-Salaam
as project manager for a #5m multi-storey office block. In April last
year he came back to Glasgow, and to a senior position with Scotland
Track Renewals Unit, an emerging company formed by the privatisation of
British Rail.
At present he is involved in drawing up contracts for renewing track
in different parts of Scotland, and the company might soon be spreading
its wings further afield. But no real competitive tendering has taken
place in the railway environment before, so Keith Gourlay finds the work
challenging and enjoyable.
He would recommend quantity surveying to anyone. ''It's interesting,
demanding and rewarding,'' he says. ''You can't ask for much more than
that.''
</TEXT>
