<HEADLINE>The biotech boffins are going to market</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL MAGEE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<FLAG>TRAINING DEVELOPMENT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765020</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Great minds are being concentrated on the appliance of science to the
real world -- to see that lab developments are quickly transformed into
sales potential, reports Bill Magee.
SCOTLAND's expanding cluster of biotech companies is rapidly becoming
more market-led in its approach towards training up key personnel.
Further talks are being staged this month with a view to developing a
new approach, to ensure that any new bio-technological product develops
rapidly from laboratory and into the marketplace.
The industry, comprising more than 100 firms in Scotland alone, has
for years been responsible for a series of revolutionary technological,
chemical and medical studies in the fields of health care, food,
engineering and the environment. Yet it is still hampered by a
now-outdated image of white-coated lab-bound boffins.
Now, however, individuals with a career portfolio combining expertise
backed up by business knowledge, especially in marketing, are
increasingly in demand by companies as they bid to display more of a
sense of the marketplace and now the gap between innovative laboratory
work and bringing much-needed products to market faster.
John Bremner, head of Scottish Enterprise biotechnology unit, says a
great future lies ahead for the sector. ''Scotland has an established
cluster of biotech companies in the UK. As we progress, we are
increasingly relying on technical knowledge. If we can marry that to
business and commercial knowledge, we will be stronger and more able to
concentrate on opportunities that undoubtedly exist.''
One such company is Aberdeen-based Biovation, which concentrates on a
core technology of DNA and antibody manipulation, with special emphasis
on cancer research.
Enjoying close technical support from the city university, the firm
continues to seek assignments from pharmaceutical companies for contract
work.
Gavin Don, partner in Equitas, small-company finance specialists,
says: ''Anyone nowadays displaying scientific academic success coupled
with a business edge represents a doubly valuable asset to a biotech
company.''
Now a new training programme for the industry is being introduced.
Talks with varous interested parties to help companies become more
product-to-market orientated are currently being staged by the Advanced
Centre for Biochemical Engineering at University College London (UCL).
Programmer manager Dr Tony Bradshaw is a former Heriot-Watt University
graduate.
Scottish Enterprise, the Scottish Biomedical Association and Scottish
Biomedial Trust are high on his list, with the centre having recently
been awarded a major grant by the Sciences Research Council to develop
training for industry.
The UCL programme is part of an integrated graduate development scheme
and directed by leaders in the industry through the centre, which is now
well established in a new #12.5m facility.
Tony Bradshaw says: ''To remain competitive in what represents one of
the fastest growing manufacturing sectors in the UK, staff needed
continuous and flexible training to keep pace with rapid developments in
bioprocessing.''
His centre's programme does not necessarily offer a panacea for the
centre; it is, however, designed to provide scientists and engineers
alike with training to enhance their ability to translate novel
bioscience into industrial processes. This can ultimately lead to
getting a new bio-product to market faster.
The training is both integrated and based on a high-quality modular
approach to address the industry's immediate needs. ''Modules can be
taken individually or as a sequence leading to three levels of academic
achievement which includes and MSc in Bioprocessing.''
Training courses cover the areas of fermentation together with
biotransformation, downstream processing, bioprocess design, monitoring
and control, the impacts of DNA technology, biosafety and environmental
and validation issues.
Gavin Don of Equitas says: ''Society is currently involved in an
incredibly exciting period and biotech is going to do for industry what
personal computers did, but more so. There are revolutionary processes
in health care, food, the environment and engineering in the offing.
''The works in fact, as huge tracts of industry completely change
their methods of production with the next 10-20 years.''
However, biotech is not necessarily renowned for having a hard
business edge and this is where Equitas comes in: developing business
strategies for those small companies that found it far from easy to
separate the lines between finance and marketing.
Meanwhile, the UCL training programmes are all about the development
of multi-skilled fexible personnel, to enable the efficient and safe
design, operation and scaling-up of bioprocess sequences.
This would lead also to the speed-up of transfer of these processes
from laboratory to pilot stage and on to manufacturing scales, while
keeping those involved at the forefront of bioprocess technologies.
Dr Bradshaw says: ''Also addressed are improvements in the
collaboration between engineers and scientists, research, development
and production, and bioprocessing companies and their suppliers.''
Furthermore, the UCL training increased personnel motivation through
an enhanced professional status, the new MBI programme, to facilitate
the adoption of best practice in the biotech industry.
Candidates from Scottish biotech firms are being sought for the new
UCL training programme.
</TEXT>
