<HEADLINE>Why go to school in summer?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DICK LOUDEN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDUCATION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765021</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Vicki Speedie knows why. It gave her a remarkable degree of
confidence. And this Glasgow University initiative continues to be a
positive inspiration to those who call on its special kind of help,
writes Dick Louden.
IT HAS been a good summer for Vicki Speedie. She completed her Honours
degree at Glasgow University in physiology and sports science. Now, in
pursuit of her ambition to become an accredited sports psychologist, she
is going on to take a Master's degree at Exeter University. She is still
looking around hopefully for financial support but this talented young
sportswoman -- captain of the university swimming team -- is heading for
Exeter, come what may.
Vicki has shown this determination since she left Blantyre High School
four years ago. Her Higher passes were not quite good enough to gain a
place on her chosen university course, so she enrolled in the annual
summer school which was started by Glasgow University in 1986, enjoys
strong financial and professional support from Strathclyde region, and
now involves all higher education institutions in the West of Scotland.
The summer school is aimed principally at pupils from areas of
deprivation who may have little knowledge of university life and in many
cases, like Vicki, do not quite possess the qualifications for entry.
Though may not have achieved their full academic potential at school,
the summer school offers lecturers the chance to assess whether they
have the qualities to undertake a degree course. If they impress, they
could be offered a place.
This happened to Vicki Speedie and she returned to the summer school
this year to talk to the 230 youngsters who had enrolled. ''I told them
why I went and what I got out of it,'' she said. ''When I came to summer
school, I had only once been here before -- at an Open Day. The school
boosted my confidence. I was taught learning techniques, made new
friends, and came to terms with the hugeness of the place. I advised
pupils to stick at it and reassured them that there is no working-class
stigma in the university.''
Another who shared her experiences with the summer school students was
Gillian Brown, a former pupil of Possilpark Secondary in Glasgow, now
closed. Made of the same strong stuff as Vicki -- injured for two and a
half years, she came back to play basketball for Glasgow and the West of
Scotland and now coaches -- Gillian was the first pupil of Possilpark
for seven years to go to university, where she is just one archaeology
pass short of graduation in social sciences.
''My Highers weren't quite enough,'' she said, ''so I went to summer
school; but I would have gone anyway -- I wanted a head-start. I got
used to the volume of people and my nervousness disappeared. I talked to
this year's summer school about social sciences -- don't buy all the
recommended texts and be prepared to get a good seat in the library,
because there's a lot of research to do.''
The school runs for ten weeks from mid-June. The first week introduces
students to the university and its ways. Thereafter four subjects,
including English language, are studied at first-year university level
until the final week, when those students requiring a good report to
gain admission see their tutors for interviews, tests and assessments.
For William Dunn, the senior lecturer in education who has directed
the school since its inception, it is ''all about social justice. It's
pure philanthropy -- we are on moral high ground here.'' He feels that
''our reports can be more accurate predictors of performance than
Highers -- we're talent spotting''.
He sees the summer school offering other advantages. While it is
running, one-third of students change their planned courses. It also
acts as a clearing house -- students who can't be placed on their chosen
course may be offered alternatives. Moreover, summer school is not just
about school pupils. Places are allocated to adults with non-traditional
qualifications who can be deemed to be socially or economically
deprived, and to others who have already embarked elsewhere on science
or engineering courses.
One of the most popular subjects at summer school is psychology. This
high level of interest continues to be reflected in degree choices, with
around 900 students following psychology courses. For summer school
purposes, lecturer Margaret Martin has widened the focus. ''We don't
just stick to the first-year curriculum or restrict it to clinical or
abnormal psychology,'' she explained. ''This year we are concentrating
on memory. The students do applied work in the labs and have full access
to the Internet.''
Graeme Baillie from Gleniffer High in Paisley already has a place at
Strathclyde University to take a BSc in computer science and psychology.
''I came here for a good start,'' he said. ''I have gained an insight
into different subjects, learned about exam procedures and the structure
of courses, met a lot of people and found out where everything is and
how the system works.''
Helen Nicholas from Blantyre High, who wants to teach English, came to
summer school still needing an A and a B pass for admission to an
English Literature course. ''I never knew what university life was
like,'' she said, ''and I had never visited the campus. The psychology
we are getting is magic -- it really opens your eyes. I love it here,
though some might find the essays and research a bit forbidding.''
Joanna Mulvaney, from John Ogilvie High in Hamilton, originally wanted
to be an actress but now her ambition is to be a political researcher or
modern studies teacher. She has just completed fifth year but already
knows that she wants to attend Glasgow University -- ''It's the one you
hear about all the time and it feels like what a university should be''.
Hoping to study politics and sociology, she found summer school highly
enjoyable. ''The first week I wondered if I'd like it. Now I feel at
home -- it's flexible, you're not spoon-fed.''
</TEXT>
