<HEADLINE>Getting in a flap</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW POPPLE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FATHERS DAY</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976765022</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANDREW POPPLE refuses to mince words over the family diet.
WHAT creates in us our likes and dislikes about food, our addictions
(mine is chocolate, given the chance) and our
would-not-touch-it-with-a-bargepole phobias? They can develop very early
in childhood, and are very individual, with no obvious reason -- except
perhaps as with an uncle of mine who will not touch a roast potato. As a
child he was forced to eat all his Sunday dinner; he saved the best bit
-- roast potato -- until last, but on one occasion was too full to eat
it all. The resultant anguish over something he wanted to eat but
couldn't has stayed with him for 60 years.
Watching our two children eating, it is interesting to see the
preferences. Our girl will want mostly vegetables, will eat them first,
and is utterly adamant that she does not like animal fat of any kind. As
long as the fat is taken off, she is quite happy with white meats. Red
meats are very reluctantly taken. In total contrast, our son is the
family carnivore. Anything is fair game, but in the event of a temporary
lack of cow, dinosaur, giraffe etc, he will gaily tuck into the rest of
the dinner, vegetables (in moderation) included.
I am happy not to push the issue too far. Few meats are free from some
doubt over additives, what the creature was fed on, what disease it
might pass on to us, what nasties are living on it or in it. Similarly,
fruit and vegetables seem to owe more to chemical warfare than
horticulture -- genetically engineered, sprayed, treated, picked
immature and aged rather than ripened. Which will do you less harm? You
pays your money and you takes your choice.
So far our daughter's preference is based on taste and is not
emotional or political. It is not a reaction to the production of meat
-- relating to the animals, being against possible cruel living
conditions and so on. She knows where our meat comes from, relates to
the animals in the fields as its source but is sanguine about their
fate. On television it is not uncommon to portray families with
vegetarian children. Preparing individual meals to cater for each
preference is seen as funny. Tedious would be my word for it. Perhaps we
have this to come, but as it is, we have no need to resort to parallel
meals. I slant the ratios of meat and vegetables, and everyone is happy.
Neither of our children has a diet so unbalanced that it is of concern,
and mealtime battles are rare.
However, it is essential to keep one step ahead in this game. I am
currently researching interesting vegetables and ways of serving them
for my forthcoming opus The Courgette and I.
Meanwhile, the kids have a saying: ''Flap, flap, splat, dinner is
served.'' This relates to an episode a few years back when one morning
we found a dead pheasant at the foot of our sitting room windows. The
poor beast had flown, or been blown, into them and had broken its neck.
They were intrigued to find we could cook and eat the bird -- it had
been dead no more than an hour before we found it -- and we did! It was
delicious.
The townie dad had a whole new experience plucking and so on, and the
children had an ''as it happens'' anatomy lesson, identifying, and
examining the various organs and where they fitted. Did it put them off
the roast pheasant? Not in the slightest. Having the head as a table
decoration just about did it for my wife, however.
</TEXT>
