<DOCNO>GH950822-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The golden rewards of fightingagainst the fear factor</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765025</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As the parent of a Down's syndrome child, Brian Wilson has welcomed
recent debate on testing for the disease, but stresses there is more
than one choice for those determining the fate of unborn babies
THE Lord works in mysterious ways. If He had wished to elevate the
debate about testing for Down's syndrome, even unto the pages of Hello!
magazine, then there was no surer course than to bestow an extra
chromosome upon young Domenica Lawson.
Dominic, the proud dad, is a magazine editor with strong opinions and
impeccable social credentials. To his credit, he has used both to
attract an enormous amount of attention to the ethical questions which
have been crying out to be asked about the presumed desirability of
pre-empting the birth of the great majority of children with the same
condition as his and mine.
By dint of being godmother to the new arrival, the Princess of Wales
has entered the drama. Hello! breathlessly reports: ''The Princess could
transform attitudes to the thousands of babies born in Britain each
year, suffering from Down's syndrome.'' Presumably by a wave of her
magic wand.
Hello! somewhat exaggerates the client group which may benefit from
the Princess's powers to influence. New arrivals of Down's children are
not counted in thousands, but in a steadily diminishing number of
hundreds. In England and Wales the number has dropped between 1982 and
1992 from 513 to 383. The trend in Scotland is similar; with just 58
born last year.
There is a very straightforward explanation for the reduction in
numbers which has nothing to do with ''cure'', of which there is none.
The simple fact is that more than 90% of suspected Down's pregnancies
are terminated. Medical science continues to devote much brain-power and
substantial resources to improving upon this remarkably high
strike-rate.
The debate which has developed in recent weeks is, I believe, healthy
and welcome -- not least because people with differing views have felt
moved to join in. Ethically or pragmatically, it is not a
black-and-white issue and nobody should pretend that it is.
I do actually believe in choice and certainly have no wish to
interfere in other people's right to exercise it. But choice without
balanced information is a false concept. And if all the information
coming at prospective parents of a Down's syndrome child is based on the
thesis that this is a disaster which can and should be avoided, then the
degree of ''choice'' involved is actually very limited.
Few people give much thought to the possibility of having a Down's
syndrome child, and the dilemmas it may give rise to, until the reality
is upon them. Why should they? My wife and I certainly didn't and all
the views which we hold on the matter have been formulated in the light
of subsequent experience.
We didn't know until Eoin was born that he had Down's. That cut out
any dilemmas. But we can now testify that it has, in our case, been far
from a disaster and we think that people in the same situation should
have access to some such positive thoughts and images before making a
difficult decision. It really is as simple as that. Who can argue
against it?
Quite a lot of people, actually. For an industry is growing up and
based on the demand for earlier and more sophisticated tests. As things
stand, the only point of these tests is to identify in order to
eliminate. If fear of the unknown is replaced by a more balanced
understanding, then the demand is inevitably going to diminish.
At the moment, frankly, that is a pious hope. The heavy pressures are
in the other direction. Science is looking for earlier, easier, more
accurate tests to identify ''risk'' or certainty of Down's syndrome. And
why stop at Down's syndrome? Well they don't, of course.
It was reported last week: ''An advertisement is about to be launched
by a British company telling readers of a women's magazine that they may
be among the two million people in this country who carry the gene for
cystic fibrosis, a chronic disorder of the lungs and digestive system.
''The advert, by University Diagnostics based in South London, urges
them to buy a test that establishes, on the basis of a mouthwash sample
sent off in an envelope, whether their future children may develop the
disease as a result of 'quirks of inheritance' if both parents are
carriers.'' The growth of such tests over a whole range of conditions
has prompted the House of Commons Select Committee on Science and
Technology to demand a regulatory body covering companies that offer
genetic testing.
That would be an advance. There has to be some control exercised over
companies and other interests -- which include the more commercially
minded wings of some NHS Trusts -- which are essentially trading in the
manufacture of irrational fear; a product which can always be disguised
behind a smokescreen of concern for the anguish and concern which the
poor parents might otherwise suffer.
With Down's syndrome, ''progress'' has moved faster and further
without any select committee hitherto interesting itself in the
implications. Perhaps that is because people with Down's syndrome are
identifiably different. It has been easier to sell the idea that, to put
it bluntly, getting shot of them altogether is a great mercy for all
concerned. That strategy, remember is now more than 90% effective.
The debate generated by Dominic Lawson's article has thrown up a lot
of interesting sub-plots. The mere fact that he and his wife are not
short of a few bob has encouraged some writers, including Clare Rayner
-- who should know better -- to take the populist line. It's all right
for the Lawsons, she wrote in essence. They can afford it. But what
about the poor people who have to bring up a Down's kid? And what about
society which has to carry ''the burden'' after mum and dad are gone?
Here indeed is a pernicious line of argument -- that the less well off
you are, the greater the irresponsibility of bringing a kid with Down's
into the world. Society, we are thereby invited to conclude, has no
obligation to redress the economic balance in favour of that child, from
the cradle to the grave. On the contrary, it is the parent's duty to
spare society a potential burden. Swallow that line of thinking and you
are on a dangerous journey, which certainly does not end at Down's
syndrome.
I decline many requests to write articles or take part in programmes
on this subject, because I have no wish to become a professional Down's
parent. There is always the danger of appearing to wear on my sleeve
something which I certainly do not feel belongs there. I suspect that
Dominic will also, quite soon, decide that he has done enough
campaigning on this matter to last for a while.
During the past couple of weeks, however, I have written and spoken
about it quite a lot. For this was indeed an opportunity, perhaps for
the wrong reasons -- Princess Di and all -- to put across that simple
message which I think we owe to our children and to people who might
face a choice that they have not at this moment ever contemplated.
The aim is not to preach or cajole, but simply to suggest: Check out
the 10% before joining the 90%. There are two sides to the story and I'm
very glad that we ended up on the one we did. For the time being what
matters is that at least the debate exists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
