<DOCID>GH950822-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>For the unborn future</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>AILEEN LITTLE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765027</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The help of young people has been enlisted to enquire into the health
of the Moray Firth and raise awareness of it, reports AILEEN LITTLE.
A PROJECT which was underway on the shores of the Moray Firth this
summer should help answer the plea made by Magnus Magnusson in the
foreword to his book The Nature of Scotland. All those concerned with
the future of Scotland's natural heritage, he urges, should ''take
better care of it for the sake of the unborn future''.
Writing specifically about Scotland's rich coastal waters, the
chairman of Scottish Natural Heritage goes on to acknowledge that modern
times put traditional marine resources under increasing pressure --
which is why, as an important habitat for cetaceans such as dolphins and
porpoises and birds including guillemots, razor bills and eider duck,
the Moray Firth is the focus of a three-year SNH project.
But Scotland has another resource -- children. Towards the end of the
last school session, SNH formed a partnership with the Scottish Museums
Council and the Crown Estate to enlist the help of young people
inquiring into the health of the Moray Firth. They were invited this
summer to take part in a co-ordinated recording project.
''Using schoolchildren as well as members of the public fits in with
our own educational materials; we hope our resources will encourage
schools to join in,'' explains Inverness-based SNH project officer
Rachael Harding-Hill. Called Ocean Watch, this short-term project is
designed to raise awareness about the need for wise usage of the Firth.
For its part, the Scottish Museums Council is keen to become more
actively involved in promoting environmental awareness. ''People think
of museums as final resting places, but they have a significant role to
play in their community's perception of the local environment.
''In the seventeenth century museums were investigating places, going
beyond the limits of the building,'' points out Stephen Mora, assistant
curator of Inverness Museum and the person responsible for co-ordinating
the involvement of 10 museums and historical centres along the 250-mile
Firth.
Each centre -- such as the The Buckie Drifter Fisheries museum and
Groam House in Rosemarkie -- has mounted a ''starter'' exhibition about
the shoreline, including a handling collection and books on
identification. In addition, members of the public are invited to choose
from five surveys dealing with such issues as human activity, evidence
of dog whelks (numbers indicate the extent of toxic anti-foulants
painted on the base of boats) and marine debris.
''We want fishermen, the sailing fraternity, school classes and
families to share their environment with us,'' explains Stephen Moran.
''We all have a degree of knowledge which are are trying to formalise.''
Ultimately, copies of results will be sent to the Marine Conservation
Society for inclusion in its national shoreline database.
Sadly, delay in procuring funding has meant that surveys were not
available until a few weeks before the end of last session -- and
returns are due by the middle of next month. Teachers keen to
participate were faced with the choice of cramming an outing into busy
end-of-term schedules, organising an outing over the holiday, or
tackling a survey immediately on their return next session.
Tony Thornton, head of science at Raddery School for children with
special needs, chose the first option and set out to investigate marine
debris. ''Here in Fortrose, we're only three minutes from the beach. By
doing a survey of the beach, the boys can learn more than by simply
walking along it. My main criticism is the bad timing.''
One of Thornton's pupils, 14-year-old Alex Watson, reports finding
''mostly cans, plastic bags, balls and a pair of shoes. The beach isn't
very clean''.
Crown Primary School in Inverness has a nature club led by parent and
local dentist Richard Castro ''We made a start and plan to continue
after the holidays,'' he says. His group studied a section between
Alturlie Point and Fort George measuring strips of sand and gravel. This
work was repeated elsewhere on the shore during the vacation by David
McAllister, head of biology at Tain Royal Academy.
A founder member of the Highland Biological Recording Group, he
devoted a day to helping children conduct surveys. His afternoon party
carried out pollution surveys, while the morning group of 32 five- to
eight-year-olds searched for marine life. Eight-year-old Theo Watssman,
from Tain's Craighill Primary, is proud of his contribution: ''I found a
crab in seaweed, some dog whelks, winkles and a mussel. It's a very good
idea.''
At Groam House, curator Susan Seright is enthusiastic about the
educational implications of the scheme. ''It's extremely worthwhile.
There are seals, dolphins and porpoises in the Moray Firth, so it is
relevant for us to be involved in natural history. I'm keen on the
community aspect, too -- we have visitrs from oral history groups.''
At the end of last term, she admits that she failed to foresee the
difficulty posed by secondary school classes taught in 40-minute blocks.
''I had hoped the surveys would fall into the Friday afternoon 'leisure
activity' category.''
Not withstanding a number of problems, however, the Scottish Museums
Coucil is pleased to have launched what it believes is the first
environmental initiative in the field of education -- a good example of
schools working for the wider community.
New threats (such as the infamous PCBs) face Scottish wildlife on land
and sea and it is not known if the environment can be rid of them. One
important safeguard is to encourage the next generation to protect
habitats, while appreciating, using -- and benefiting from -- Scotland's
heritage.
</TEXT>
