<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lack of sympathy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765035</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Am I alone in feeling an utter lack of sympathy with the manner in
which Alison Hargreaves met her death?
Should I pretend not to notice the unnatural way her husband talks
unemotionally about the wife he'll never see again? Can there be a flaw
in my character as I walk round a hole in the road acknowledging the
obvious danger?
If my wife walks up the centre lane of the M8 then tells me next week
she'll attempt the Kingston Bridge at four o'clock on a Friday
afternoon, how do I react? Tell my children she's a heroine? Aye,
that'll be right!
Selfishness belongs to the immature, for life with your children is
far too important and exciting in itself to be bothered with mountains
and potholes.
Tom Gill,
51 Mains River,
Park Mains,
Erskine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Women's needs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765036</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT completely baffles me how a woman columnist for The Herald cannot
''understand'' Alison Hargreaves's need to climb over-riding her need to
be with her children (August 19).
Has Margaret Vaughan absolutely no idea that some women have a burning
desire to achieve feats outwith the conventional role? Even in 1995 very
few women have the talent or are allowed to achieve ''great things.''
Alison Hargreaves wasn't a wife and mother who liked to climb, she was a
climber first.
This must be a very difficult time for those who loved her and who
will not see her again, but she had what most men, gifted or otherwise,
take for granted, a supportive partner who makes it possible for them to
lead a happy domestic life and who is understanding enough to give them
the freedom to achieve what they will.
Instead of questioning Alison Hargreaves's priorities, surely women
should number her as one of the special members of their sex.
Mr Ballard must have understood very well the kind of partnership he
was entering into and in my opinion the children are with the parent who
is best equipped to cope with their needs.
Marta Emmerson,
Low Cottage,
Croftamie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Preserving the Scottish press</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765037</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR all the brave futuristic talk about the Internet and the
information superhighway, most of us still get our news and background
information from newspapers. That Scotland still has four daily
broadsheets which combine international, national, and local news is one
of its great blessings.
As Alf Young argues (August 18), no good would come of the Scotsman,
the Press and Journal, or The Herald being bought by London operations.
If they agree on nothing else. Scots of all political persuasions must
surely concur that Scotland, with or without an assembly, is
sufficiently different to require the services of an independent quality
Scottish press.
The traditional rivalries of the four city states must not be allowed
to obscure the seriousness of the issue.
I do not know enough of the economics of newspapers to understand why
the staff of the Scotsman and the P&amp;J are not contemplating management
buyouts or whether the Scots Tory group led by Professor Ross Harper can
mount a serious bid for the Scotsman.
But I know enough about the centralising tendencies of the British
state, the ignorance and arrogance of London ''medians'', and the
difficulties of maintaining a quality press to be fearful of yet further
erosion of Scottish intellectual and cultural life. A few pages of
tartan tack-on to an essentially London product will not suffice.
How are we to preserve an autonomous Scottish press? There are obvious
reasons to be concerned about one Scottish publisher owning three of the
four serious dailies (and the one quality Sunday paper) but if a single
company will allow those titles to be controlled by people who know and
care about Scotland then it is an opinion that should be seriously
entertained.
Professor Steve Bruce,
Sociology Department,
University of Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Moderator launches #1.5m appeal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765038</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Moderator of the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland, the
Right Rev. James Harkness, yesterday launched an appeal to raise #1.5m
for church-based community projects in needy areas.
The Priority Areas Renewal Foundation has been set up, despite
criticism of the church's refusal to accept National Lottery funding.
At yesterday's launch in St Paul's Parish Church, Provanmill, Glasgow,
Mr Harkness denied it was a ''gamble'' to try to raise such a large sum
when the church had already turned down the opportunity of lottery cash.
Last month, the Rev. Dr William Morris, Minister of Glasgow Cathedral
and one of Scotland's senior churchmen, questioned the Kirk's stance,
and said it was up to individual congregations to decide if they wanted
to apply for money.
The General Assembly voted to veto lottery money earlier this year
when it was decided it would be ''inappropriate'' to apply for
Millennium Fund money to mark a celebration of Christ's birth.
Mr Harkness said yesterday: ''We are not taking a gamble, we are
presenting a challenge to the church and the whole community and they
will respond. This way we can help people to help themselves rather than
doing so from the top down.
''There is no confusion over the church's official stance on the
lottery. The General Assembly has spoken and it is not for me to
contradict it.''
Announcng the new scheme, Mr Harkness said: ''The General Assembly
gave a very clear direction requiring the appeal and those directly
involved to address the material needs of communities wherever they are,
but also remember there are spiritual needs as well.
''This partnership should be for the good of the community,so that the
community can in turn be good for itself.''
It is hoped the #1.5m target will be raised by congregations and
adminstered by a central fund committee, which will include
representatives from Methodist, and possibly, Roman Catholic churches.
The appeal was started with a #1200 donation from Dalgety Parish
Church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
