<DOCNO>GH950822-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Egotistical drive</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765040</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
You devoted three full pages, including front-page headlines, to the
K2 heroine (August 18). In actual fact she was an ass.
She did no more than succumb to an egotistical drive which led her
onward and upward to her death. This addiction-gone-wrong scenario isn't
fair on Alison Hargreaves's children. As for her husband, all we get
from him is some stupid Tibetan ''she died a tiger'' saying.
All in all this sorry story serves as a timely reminder that for
children home is where the heart is and also where parents ought to be
-- not on some mountain-top pretending to be heroic.
Frank O'Hare,
8 Finlarig Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765041</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALF YOUNG correctly describes recent attacks on Caledonian Newspapers
as vituperative and his analysis on the need for some form of Scottish
media control of the Thomson Regional Newspapers titles up for sale is
similarly accurate (August 18).
However, there are two predominant strains to this issue -- the
editorial independence of the newspapers, preferably under progressive
Scottish ownership, but also the jobs and conditions of the employees
involved.
Any merger between Caledonian and TRN would immediately put under
threat jobs in all departments across the six titles involved. There
would also be a long-term threat to the wage levels of journalists
employed in The Herald and Evening Times.
While running the risk of accusations of fronting a self-interest
group, I believe both of the aforementioned strains can and should be
protected in this so-called Scottish media Sale of the Century.
Paul Holleran,
Scottish Organiser,
National Union of Journalists,
114 Union Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
