<DOCNO>GH950822-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'Prosecution' claim angers cheese man</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765043</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHEESE maker Humphrey Errington was fuming last night after a food
hygiene expert claimed his company had been prosecuted for selling
contaminated cheese. He said: ''This is just not true and I will be
seeking legal advice.''
The outburst came on day six of Mr Errington's court battle with
Clydesdale District Council, which is seeking an order to destroy
#27,000 worth of Lanark Blue, made from unpasteurised ewe's milk.
In court Mr Errington had heard Dr James McLauchlin give evidence that
he had sent his personal CV ''around the world'' to back up his claims
that he was an expert.
The CV describes how he had been called in February to give evidence
in the ''prosecution of the manufacturer of Lanark Blue because of
contamination by listeria monocytogenes''.
Mr Michael Jones, QC, acting for Mr Errington, pointed out that this
was not true.
In February a JP sitting in private granted the council the power to
destroy a batch of the cheese because it allegedly contained
unacceptable levels of listeria. But Mr Errington fought a legal battle
to win a fresh hearing. He has never faced prosecution in connection
with his cheese.
Dr McLauchlin is a clinical scientist in charge of the Food Hygiene
Reference Unit at the Public Health Laboratory Services in London. In
evidence, he said yesterday: ''I apologise to Mr Errington.''
The case continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>With pride and honour</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765044</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I FEEL sorry that the 50-year anniversary of the end of the war is
being sidetracked by the squabble over Japan's responsibility to the
former prisoners of war.
Of course Japan should apologise and pay compensation, but after 50
years I cannot see her ever doing that.
I would prefer to celebrate the end of the war by remembering our
Servicemen with pride. We seem to forget that the 14th Army in Burma
soundly defeated the Japanese. They took them on in their own ground,
held them, stood up to them, and then completely defeated them. There
was no other theatre of war where the Japanese were so soundly beaten.
I would therefore like to remember all those involved in the war
against Japan with pride and with honour. They all did a fine job, in
very difficult circumstances and came out of the conflict with honour.
Kenneth G Ross,
316 Albert Drive,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
