<DOCNO>GH950822-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Militant held over Paris bombings</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765049</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris
A SUSPECTED Algerian Muslim militant was detained in Sweden today for
questioning over bombings in Paris that have killed seven people and
wounded more than 100 in the past month.
Abdelkrim Deneche, believed by French investigators to be a leading
member of Algeria's Armed Islamic Group (GIA), was detained in Stockholm
at the request of visiting French anti-terrorist magistrate
Jean-Francois Ricard.
On July 25, a bomb killed seven people and wounded 86 in an
underground train in the Saint-Michel station in central Paris, the
bloodiest attack in the capital since 1986. Last week, a new blast
wounded 17 people by the Arc de Triomphe.
Investigators are concentrating on theories that Algerian extremists
were responsible for both attacks.
Meanwhile, an opinion poll shows that most French people fear for
their safety after the two Parisian bomb attacks, but trust the
centre-right government to combat terrorism.
The poll for Le Parisien newspaper showed that 58% of French people
were either very or fairly afraid for their safety.
The survey also indicated that 69% had confidence in the government of
Prime Minister Alain Juppe ''in the struggle against
terrorism''.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>It's never too late to shine</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GERALDINE ABRAHAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>APPOINTMENTS,EDUCATION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765050</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Glasgow University offers a new degree of hope to those who missed
out, reports Geraldine Abrahams.
FOR the first time ever, the University of Glasgow is to offer people
who lack conventional higher-education qualifications the chance to
study part-time undergraduate courses which could lead to a
university-level award.
The initiative is the result of a project set up with funding supplied
by the Scottish Higher Education Funding Council (SHEFC) and is based on
a policy perception that there should be greater availability for people
to take university degrees.
One way of achieving this is to increase the types of delivery offered
so there would be more flexibility, allowing people to study for degrees
on a part-time basis out of normal hours.
The University of Glasgow has always had a flexible system for people
doing full-time degrees, allowing the transfer of subjects, but anyone
who wanted to do a part-time degree -- while it was theoretically
possible -- could only attend through the day.
There is nothing new in part-time degree courses, but the programme of
study starting this year is the first stage in introducing courses
largely for evening study, and providing courses that are either the
same or equivalent to existing undergraduate studies.
A large proportion of these will be recognised as qualifying courses
for degrees. They include Astronomy and Physics, Classical Greek
Civilisation, Computer Studies, English and Scottish Literature,
European Languages, Psychology, and Geography and Geology.
''In a sense they are 'access' courses because there is a minimal
entrance qualification -- you don't need Highers,'' explains Dr James
MacDonald of the Department of Adult and Continuing Education. ''In many
instances the applicants will be interviewed so that they know what they
will be taking on and so that they can be advised as to the benefits for
them. A conventional pre-university access course might be suggested if
they do not have a sufficient background or educational base to cope.''
The programme, starting in October, should appeal to people who
achieved their Highers some time ago and have retained an interest in
theoretical or practical learning, as well as those with a strong
informal background in a subject but who have no Highers.
The courses taught in the evening will have Scottish Credit
Accumulation and Transfer Scheme (SCOTCAT) credit ratings. In many cases
they will be the same courses taught to full-time students during the
day. One obvious drawback is that, where it takes one year to achieve 40
credits in one subject on the daytime course, the evening equivalent
will take two years.
Also, while full-time students will study three subjects
simultaneously, it is unlikely that a part-timer would be able to
consider more than two courses at a time. Recognising that this
timescale might deter some would-be students, the university has built
in further flexibility. ''We understand that some may want to exit
before completing the whole degree but would like something to show for
their study, so we have introduced 'sub-degree' qualifications,'' says
Dr MacDonald. ''Having achieved the equivalent of first-year
qualifications, the student would receive a Certificate in Higher
Education.''
Even if they do not complete the certificate, part-time students will
be able to ask for a transcript of the passes they have achieved and
could use this on their CVs.
One advantage of this new part-time study is its interchangeability.
Because it is the equivalent of the daytime undergraduate courses, a
student who has completed 90% of a full-time ordinary degree study
programme and has difficulty in finishing on that basis, will be able to
complete it part-time.
The converse is also true. Where others might start the degree on this
part-time basis, they may choose to complete it full-time, during the
day.
Unlike full-time students, those choosing to study part time will
generally have to fund the study themselves. The assumption is that most
people who choose part-time evening study are in work; but fees are
relatively low, generally between #120 and #200 per course, per year.
Accepting that not everyone can afford the fees, the university will
provide bursaries to meet the needs of some.
''We appreciate that there are people who are out of work or on
benefit who would have difficulty in meeting fees and incidental
expenses like buying books and travel,'' says Dr MacDonald, ''so the
university has some money set aside -- a part time incentives grant --
for supporting part-time work.
There may be room for some cynicism in all of this, given that SHEFC,
the Government-run funding body, has been involved in this project from
the early stages. Running part-time, self-funded undergraduate courses
will increase the numbers of graduates in the country without a
proportionate rise in the funding budget.
Whatever the motive, there can be no doubt that increased flexibility
and wider opportunity must be of significant benefit not only to
individuals but to society as a whole.
* For further information, telephone (0141) 330 4394.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scot fears 'whitewash' over arms-to-Iran tapes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER, RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765051</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOT involved in the arms-to-Iran affair, questioned last month by
Customs and Excise in Glasgow, last night expressed his anger at the
refusal by his interrogators to hand over tapes of his interview.
Mr John Anderson, a 64-year-old former banker in Glasgow and London,
said he was bemused, and believed the inquiry could end in a
''whitewash''.
At the end of July Mr Anderson, from Balloch but now living in the
north of Scotland, was called to Glasgow by the Investigation Branch of
HM Customs and Excise. For the period of questioning he was placed under
arrest.
When it was over, he was told he was ''unarrested'' and he returned
home to Fort Augustus.
Around the same time, his former business colleague, Mr Gerald James,
was undergoing similar questioning in London.
The two men claim their interrogators were interested in two lines of
inquiry.
One was whether they possessed evidence that proved one of their
companies, British Manufacture and Research Co, a firm based in Baroness
Thatcher's home town of Grantham, traded illegally in arms with Iran.
The other centred on the role of former Chief Secretary to the
Treasury Jonathan Aitken, previously a BMARC director.
No charges were levelled against Mr Anderson and Mr James, a merchant
banker, at the end of the interviews.
In a letter to Mr Anderson's solicitors, Customs and Excise said that
because the case potentially involved multiple defendants, it was not
general policy to provide copy interview tapes to the defence until such
time as a specific defendant had either been charged, or informed he
would be prosecuted.
The letter added: ''As neither of these circumstances currently apply
to Mr Anderson we will not be providing copies of the tapes to you at
this stage. If Mr Anderson's circumstances change then you will be
provided with the copy tapes forthwith.''
Last night Mr Anderson said: ''It was explained to me how the tapes
worked and I was promised copies -- the custody officer even offered to
do them there and then. The Customs and Excise investigators then said
they would take care of it and I cannot help feeling this has resulted
in a total whitewash.
''Perhaps they decided we named too many names and I am very angry
because I believe we are being picked on for telling the truth.''
He felt he had now reached ''a state of limbo''.
Mr Brian Wilson, Labour's trade and industry spokesman, said he was
concerned the emphasis still seemed to be on suppressing the
significance of what the two men had to say, rather than investigating
it.
''I don't understand why it took Customs and Excise all these years to
interview two men who have never sought to disguise the fact they were
involved in contracts with Iran.
''The crucial point is that if Ministers had initiated these inquiries
at the proper time, the Scott Inquiry would inevitably have been about
Iran and BMARC as well as Iraq and Matrix Churchhill.''
Last month's detention of Mr Anderson was his second encounter with
the authorities.
He had previously been taken from Fort Augustus by two police officers
and driven to Glasgow and put on a plane to Gatwick. A police car taking
him to Ramsgate was involved in a collision with another vehicle.
The next day, shaken and injured, Mr Anderson, who served in the RAF,
was questioned before being put on a flight home. He is still pursuing a
settlement from the police in connection with the incident.
No one at Customs and Excise in Glasgow was available for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
