<TEXT>
I MUST agree with what Gordon Graham says about the achievements of
the XIV Army being forgotten once again (August 15).
It should be remembered that General Slim welded together an army
containing British, Gurkhas, Indians, and Africans of all religious
beliefs, but serving the British Crown.
As far as possible their own type of food was supplied along with
ammunition, etc, by air drops on sites arranged by radio,
The XIV Army was scattered over hundreds of miles with battles raging
from the Arakan to Kohima or Moqurg and the crucial one of Mandalay and
Meiktila in March, 1945. No wonder General Bill Slim's victory in Burma
is recognised as one of the greatest of the Second World War.
During the campaign men of all religions fought together for the cause
of peace. How sad it is that 50 years after VJ Day we still have men of
different religions disturbing the peace of the world by fighting among
themselves.
Ian Purvis,
Tornaveen, Clachan,
Tarbert, Argyll.
</TEXT>
