<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765054</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE VJ-Day commemoration has been overshadowed by two important
factors, the atomic bombs and the treatment of POWs.
Gordon Graham brings to the attention of the public the fact that the
14th Army fought in terrible conditions and completely crushed the
Japanese Armies in Burma (August 15).
The Indian forces in the 14th Army have been recognised and praised
but I have seen no mention of the two West African divisions and
one-and-a-half East African divisions. Their part in the victory cannot
be ignored.
Bill Slim's book, Defeat into Victory, gives due honour to our British
soldiers and their comrades in arms.
Dr John Devine,
28 London Road,
Kilmarnock.
</TEXT>
