<TEXT>
WHAT a footering, bletherskite to go looking for bike or byke in a
Concise Oxford Dictionary (August 18). That's a fushionless thing to do.
One book to turn to is Chambers Scots Dictionary where bike and byke are
shown -- W E Thornley from Helensburgh would have found both words and
meanings.
We had a wasps' bike in the back here a week or so ago and the council
mannie came out to see to it for us. In conversation we used the phrases
a wasp-bike and a wasp-bink. No-one tried to do any spelling, but we all
knew what we were talking about.
Jean Rafferty,
6 Hampden Terrace,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
