<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Accuracy about 40 per cent rule</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765057</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROBBIE Dinwoodie is wrong on a point of fact when he states that
persons who died before polling day in the 1979 referendum on Scottish
devolution counted as having voted No (August 12).
The number out of which 40% said Yes had to be obtained to pass any
amendment to the Scotland Act was reduced below the number on the
electoral role specifically to avoid this effect, as Robbie Dinwoodie
would have learnt had he bothered to ask me about this point.
I have long ago ceased to expect accuracy in British journalism, which
seems to me to bear the same relationship to journalism proper as
British sherry does to the real thing.
But I still cannot get used to the fact that journalists and their
editors and sub-editors have so little sense of shame in getting facts
wrong.
My old professor, Sir Lewis Namier, was proudest of the tribute
someone paid to him as a historian: ''Lewis, when all the facts are
known, you will need to add but you will not need to correct.''
Is it too much to hope that our journalists should seek the same
tribute?
George Cunningham,
28 Manor Gardens,
Hampton, Middlesex.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Letters about Monklands</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765058</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOE CARLIN is now rightly enjoying the chance to put across his case
(August 15). The difference is that those -- and there are many in
Monklands -- with a different opinion can have their views made public
as well, something the Airdrie and Coatbridge Advertiser had stopped
practising until its new editor arrived.
If Mr Carlin concedes that letters are ''invariably biased towards the
author's opinions'', how can he justify the non-publication week after
week of scores of letters, including mine, which challenged the
Advertiser's bias and yet which never saw the light of day?
How can he defend the dropping abruptly of the MPs' coloumns -- again
happily restored -- precisely when John Smith became Leader of the
Labour Party?
Mr Carlin wonders ''Who might have been frightened?'' by these
letters. I would have thought that those who watched the hideous
behavour, amounting to open hatred, outside Airdrie Town Hall on the
night of the Monklands East by-election would have no difficulty in
answering the question.
Such fears were not lessened when the Advertiser, admittedly less so
again under the new editor, published pages of photographs of sectarian
marches. Mr Carlin would no doubt defend this on the grounds that
marches are almost ''invariably biased towards the marchers' opinions''.
What did the Advertiser think this was doing for the image of
Monklands?
If we are to believe that Mr Isdale, Ms McAuley, and now Mr Eric
Wright, have just been ''promoted'' would it not be wise for those now
running this paper to ''promote'' Mr Carlin as well? Readers would then
perhaps believe that the stable had been truly cleaned out and that the
real ''Monklands Mafia'' had been removed.
The most startling part of Mr Carlin's letter was the assertion that
''the reason why the Black Report and the Advertiser's original
accusations remain unanswered is that they are true''. How partisan can
he be? Not even Professor Black claimed that everything fed to him was
true.
Finally, Mr Carlin says I should have declared an interest. The
reality is that I was not a member of Monklands District Council during
the three years of damaging and distorted journalism that I have
described, nor was I a member for the period covered by the Black
Report.
The interest I do have is as a citizen concerned about the future of
my community, a concern which is clearly not shared by those who have
done so much to besmirch its reputation.
Desmond O'Neil,
106 Woodside Street,
Coatbridge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Destruction of Scots economy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765059</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I ACKNOWLEDGE my indebtedness to Andrew Brocklehurst for his amendment
of my estimated Scottish population without emigration from 1981 to 1991
(August 18).
The amended figure is 15.7% of 5,103,935 (805,525) plus natural
increase of 60,000 and 612,597 born outside Scotland. With a reasonable
economy, the population of Scotland would be over 6,612,598 with a
labour force of 2,705,679 instead of 2,407,188.
Scotland is a country with relatively no racial or religious
prejudice: an addition to our labour force of 298,491 workers born
outside Scotland is more than welcome in the context of full employment,
it would reduce taxation and improving services.
Since the Scottish people has no interest in policing the world and
competing in the arms race, our contribution to the family of nations
would be positive: full employment without emigration would enable us to
ensure a more peaceful world by financing projects of human development
in the Third World.
An economy with 27% of the workforce unemployed or underemployed and
805,525 emigrants seeking work elsewhere as proved by the 1991 census
fuels my sadness at the continuous destruction of the Scottish economy
since 1707.
Rev James Small,
St Catherine's,
Westcraigs Road,
Harthill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Old faces recounting the deeds of young faces</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>BOOK REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765060</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT has been a long, long time from May to now. They have been
lengthiest months. Ageing is how they have been. Sometimes the V days
have felt like yesterdays from a nearly new calendar. Oftener they have
seemed to belong to another aeon in a different place. At other times
there has been a wonder whether they happened at all.
There have been so many old faces recounting the deeds of young faces,
except they are the same faces.
Nearly always were fags sticking out of them. Nicotine was a staunch
ally. How to explain that to anybody who wasn't there and to whom l945
might as well be halfway back to medieval times is a teaser.
Even language is a barrier. Reminiscence has to run a blockade of
terms which have become as ancient as the spear and the pike.
Doodle-bugs, displaced persons, demob suits . . . What are you on about,
greybeard? Gie's peace.
Even more dating is to relate everything in the past half century to
how it occurred after what young people abbreviate to WW2, meaning what
some of us insist on calling the war.
''That would be just after the war,'' you say to them. They looked at
you askance, if anybody does look that way any more, or ever did.
Whatever else the V celebrations have done, they have ended the way of
looking back that made l945 into a year dot. There can be no more of
that. As for trying to label events as having taken place before the
war, the gum does not stick. Pre-war is practically pre-history. Popular
memory is so short now.
But VJ Day remains extra epochal when it coincides with a big-little
and bright-black day in your own life. This year's bumper amount of
looking back has been laid on top of what it is hard not to kid myself
may be feelings of maturity.
Old age, they say, just comes. You wake up one morning and you've got
it. You know so because kind people insist on saying how well you look.
You should reply that if a year had l5 months in it, you'd be one fifth
less ancient than the record books show.
But it slips the mind to say so, as much else slips. You are reduced
to following the rule that if you can't remember something, then forget
it.
One wartime memory that had escaped the memory was the expression for
the duration. Rationing and other joys of the six years were often
imposed ''for the duration of the war''. They'd last until it was all
over.
Echoes of the phrase have been stirred by a new little book, World War
II In Renfrewshire, whose publication brightened the weekend's
fireworks. In a glossary Moira Burgess, the author, revives the
expression, while she exhumes also demob suits for young readers. They
were clothes supplied to service personnel to go home in. ''They were
not high-fashion items,'' the book observes coolly.
Moira Burgess, novelist and short story writer, recalls how it became
a catch phrase in general use. For an instance she quotes: ''Are you in
that bathroom for the duration?''
If Renfrewshire's slice of the global conflict may seem thin, it was
rich. Erskine Hospital is in the old county. Hess landed there. It was
the fledgling nest of the RAF's 602 squadron. At Lobnitz's shipyard in
Renfrew the floating piers for the Normandy landings were created.
Greenock deserves much attention for the battering it took.
For one day in May after an air raid in l941 the Greenock Telegraph
had to be produced by hand. Its one-page edition was pasted around the
town on walls. ''Greenock is thought to be the only place in Britain
where this was done,'' Moira Burgess writes.
Her World War II in Renfrewshire (#4.95; Renfrew District Council)
uncovers that even Lochwinnoch had its war secrets and keeps some of
them. An unexplained number of air crashes happened on its surrounding
hills. Wreckage of a Wellington bomber that hit Box Law on an
undisclosed mission was later blown up and buried.
After another crash on Queenside Hill, white heather was said to have
grown on the site for two years.
Two other shire mysteries have still to make print 50 years after.
They have to do with the rumoured parts played in Renfrewshire's war by
Lord Haw-Haw, whose whimsical broadcasts from Germany were meant to
demoralise the nation, and by Randolph Scott, the square-jawed hero of
many cowboy pictures.
Haw-Haw is said to have put Paisley into the front line. Allegedly, he
made it a primary target of a German invasion for the strategic reason,
he claimed, that Paisley had seven women for every man. And according to
county folklore, Randy Scott was the officer in charge of a negro
battalion encamped outside Renfrew.
True or false, both tales sounded worth a look. But however long, long
a time it has been since May seems not to have been long enough. Now
battle fatigue has set in and it is only sensible to let well alone for
a while, or even for the duration.
My new maturity says forget it. For last week, otherwise not half bad,
had a birthday in it, another birthday. For the first time the thought
occurred that the candles would cost more than a cake. But thanks for
the unsigned card with the sweet violet on it, whoever you are.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000132</DOCNO>
