<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hopes grow for end of seven-week ordeal of Britons held in Kashmir. India set for hostages deal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765061</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Srinagar
A DEAL to secure the freedom of two British hostages held in Kashmir
could be on the table, following reports that India is ready to make
concessions.
Three of the 15 jailed militants whose release has been demanded by
the extremist Al-Faran group holding four Westerners could be freed,
according to an Indian Government source.
Two other militants could be released with them, said the source,
quoted by the BBC.
The news appears to be the most positive development in the seven
weeks since Keith Mangan and Paul Wells were kidnapped from a camp site
while trekking in the troubled mountain region.
The move would represent a climbdown by the Indian Government, which
until now has constantly refused to meet the kidnappers demands.
A BBC correspondent said the release would be made to look like a
routine event and it would take at least a week before the men were out.
A spokeswoman at the Indian High Commission said they had no
confirmation of the BBC report.
''We've always said that no militant will be released in exchange for
the hostages,'' said Mrs Hema Bhagirath.
She said the government had been conducting a dialogue with the
kidnappers to persuade them to release the hostages safely.
Fears for the Westerners' lives became acute after Al-Faran murdered a
fifth hostage and threatened to execute the rest unless their demands
were met within two days.
However the deadline passed with no new horrors, and Indian officials
say they have been assured by the kidnappers that the four men are safe
and well.
The governor of the state of Jammu and Kashmir has ruled out use of
force to free the hostages, saying diplomacy was the best hope for their
release.
''The government has no plan to launch a military operation to secure
the release of the four abducted tourists,'' said Governor K V Krishna
Rao.
Officials were optimistic that the four would be freed unharmed.
''It looks hopeful, but it has had its ups and downs,'' a spokesman
for Jammu and Kashmir state told reporters.
He said the government talked with Al-Faran guerrillas holding the
hostages last night.
''We have been maintaining contact with the kidnappers,'' the state
government spokesman said. ''We have made repeated appeals to them to
set free the hostages.''
He said the government believed the four were safe, but had not yet
received the photographs and tape recording it had requested as proof of
their well-being.
India has repeatedly ruled out swopping jailed militants for the
hostages.
Asked today to comment on speculation in Srinagar that an exchange was
being considered, the state government spokesman said: ''I wouldn't like
to comment on a swop at this stage.''
In December, 1989, separatist guerrillas abducted the daughter of a
former Indian home minister. She was released five days later in
exchange for five jailed separatists.
However officials said Kashmir's separatist revolt, in which police
and hospital sources say more than 20,000 people have died, had not
erupted at that time and New Delhi was now under greater pressure to
refuse such a swop.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Skipper's wife collects haul of #3.8m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765062</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DAIRY clerkess Janice Wilson had every reason to feel like the cat
that got the cream yesterday.
She collected a cheque for #3.8m from the organisers of the National
Lottery at its Glasgow office.
At her side was husband Alan, a fishing boat skipper, who had cut
short a trawling trip to join her for the cash catch.
The couple, from Fraserburgh, Aberdeenshire, were clearly stunned by
the size of their haul, which makes them the biggest named National
Lottery winners in Scotland.
Mrs Wilson, 26, said: ''I have not had time to think about it yet. It
has all come as a bit of a shock.''
The couple have played the Lottery since it began, and Mrs Wilson
staked #5 on Saturday's rollover jackpot game, choosing the numbers at
random.
''I checked the winning numbers on Teletext at about ten past eight
and my initial reaction was total disbelief.''
She contacted her husband who was on the fishing boat Cardiva in the
North Sea, north-west of Shetland, to try to give him the good news.
Mr Wilson explained: ''We spoke on the ship-to-shore radio link, but
the line was very bad. She said that something very nice had happened.''
It was not until he took the boat into Orkney and called her from a
payphone that he finally confirmed they had won the big one. Instead of
sailing with the boat on the final leg home from Scrabster to
Fraserburgh, he hired a helicopter.
The couple have known each other since schooldays and married a year
ago.
Mrs Wilson was one of five people who shared Saturday's #19.1m
jackpot.
* LOCH Ness is featured in a new scratch-card game from the National
Lottery. The UK Treasures game, which has a series of five different
card designs depicting scenic landmarks, offers a top prize of #10,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New peace questions</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765063</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE object of yet another bus bomb in Israel is the destruction of the
peace process between Israel and the Palestinians. That much is obvious,
especially as yesterday's incident is the latest in a long line of
outrages which have killed scores of people since the peace agreement
was signed in September 1993. The key question is whether the Israeli
public will be so angered by the violence that they will exert
sufficient political pressure on Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin to force
him to delay the process indefinitely. The other part of the equation is
whether the Labour Government in Israel will be so damaged by
association with a discredited peace process that it will lose the
general election due in November of next year to a Likud coalition which
is hostile to the peace process and does not feel bound by the
agreement. Interestingly, the caller who claimed responsibility for
yesterday's bus bomb for the Islamic militants of Hamas said that their
campaign would last until the Israeli elections. These are fairly basic
calculations, but there is nothing more basic or brutal than a bomb.
The stage of the peace process which is being negotiated at the moment
is significantly behind schedule. The many delays, which have added more
than a year to the timetable, are largely because of the complexity of
the issues involved, although there is no doubt that a small proportion
can be ascribed to the aftermath of terrorist attacks. After the last
bus bomb at the end of July the talks were postponed for six days, yet
the wider context illustrates the fact that Israel has been tardy in
reaching agreement on an expansion of Palestinian control in the West
Bank precisely because of security fears. The agreement reached in Oslo
in 1993 provides for a redeployment of Israeli troops out of some
Palestinian towns and from certain areas of the countryside around them.
This will be followed by a Palestinian election, hopefully before the
end of the year. The irony in all this is that both sides, after
fretting over the security issues and other aspects of the agreement for
so long, suddenly realised in recent weeks that if progress was not made
quickly the entire edifice might tumble. The resulting accelerated talks
have now been brought to a temporary halt because of the latest bombing,
which is in itself a clear acknowledgment by the militants of progress
in the talks.
The basic realities remain simple. People are dying because militants
want the peace process to fail. The reaction by both the Israeli
Government and by the Palestinian peacemakers is heartening. Both sides
appear determined to ensure that the talks will continue and that they
will succeed. Israeli Government spokesmen have made clear the fact that
the suspension in talks which was imposed after yesterday's bombing will
be very limited. Foreign Minister Shimon Peres underlined this approach
when he said that time was needed for mourning. He might have added that
time will be needed for the shock of this latest attack to fade.
Yet, whatever the level of determination to press onwards, both
Israelis and Palestinians know that total security is a myth and that
further attacks are certain. The Israeli people know this too, and it is
to their credit that throughout these assaults on their society a
majority of Israelis questioned for opinion polls have spoken in favour
of the peace process. Israel is a very small country and the pain which
these talks cause is not easily apprehended by us. What is clear is that
the process must continue; without it the future will be even worse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Refreshing report</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765064</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE first fruit of Mr Michael Forsyth's attempt to open a dialogue
with other sections of Scottish opinion -- other than the Conservative
Party and business community, that is -- is a paper from the STUC which
will be presented to the Secretary of State this Thursday. It is a
cogent and reasonable document which deserves a serious response and
will probably get one, even if all of its recommendations are unlikely
to be endorsed. It really is, for example, most unlikely that the
Government would establish a new Scottish investment bank. This has been
a constant proposal, in different contexts, from left-wing groups since
1945 and some have been created -- the giant Investors in Industry,
floated only two years ago, was an early example of this sort of
institution which succeeded on an enormous scale. Others were less
successful; but the key point is that Scotland is already awash with
financial institutions anxious to lend and with the capital to do so. If
the STUC really means state-subsidised capital for new enterprises, that
could be another matter (though it might encounter difficulties with
Brussels) but cheaper money generally could be even more beneficial. The
paper's opinion that the Secretary of State should be backing the
Chancellor's stance on interest rates is a good example of where they
might enjoy a joint effort. Scotland's economy would be a major
beneficiary of cheaper money.
It is probably easy for the two parties to agree on such general
points, and on the STUC's declared view that the Scottish economy is too
narrowly based and dependent on too few industries, even where the
latter are successful, like whisky and electronics. It will be harder on
specifics such as the need to protect the National Engineering
Laboratory at East Kilbride (where the STUC is broadly right) and the
Tate and Lyle sugar refining business at Greenock where prospects for
survival are slim. In both cases there are fundamental disagreements of
principle involved. There ought to be none, however, to prevent Mr
Forsyth endorsing the suggestion of a Scottish Labour Market Research
and Development unit -- there is a need for objective data in this, and
indeed other areas of Scottish economic life. The same degree of
collaboration surely also applies to training where unions have special
knowledge as well as interests in encouraging improvement.
On taxation there is little chance of the difference between the two
being bridged. The STUC's views about the role of taxation in investment
are not likely to command much acceptance outside the Labour movement
(and not always even there) and a shift back from indirect to direct
taxation would be a non-starter even if this paper were being presented
to a Labour Secretary of State: Governments throughout the Western world
are encountering ever-growing resentment to higher direct taxes on
income, even though there is plenty of demand for the services taxation
funds. The switch to indirect taxes is irreversible (and vital to the
running of the EU, for example) but it should still be possible to
protect the poor from their worst effects (by continuing zero rating VAT
on essentials like food).
Yet apart from the obvious areas of disagreement there is something
refreshing about this report -- it represents a genuine attempt at
discussion. It is not a mere string of declarations and assertions
expecting to meet a similar response; and it would be a pity if that
were its fate. Mr Forsyth's new departure was intended to address the
unavoidable weakness of a Government which speaks for only a minority of
the Scottish people, and a small minority at that. It has to persuade
and it has to compromise. That is admitted in theory; Thursday's talks
may show how far it can work in practice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bombay becomes Mumbai</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765065</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Bombay
BOMBAY, home to 12 million and India's financial capital, has been
renamed Mumbai after a Hindu goddess.
The name change was ordered by a Hindu party, the Shiv Sena, that in
March won control of Maharashtra state.
''Mumbai harks back to a past that is glorious, '' said Bachi
Karkaria, the Bombay Times editor. ''Bombay, on the other hand,
represents grit, gumption, and a go-getting spirit that's perfectly
suited to the present and future.''
It is not clear whether the change requires approval from the federal
government.
The change really applies only in English. The city always has been
Mumbai in the Marathi language of this region. The word Bombay was first
used by the British in the late 17th century.--AP
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>520 loseout as pools jobs axed. Winners appreciate the magic of Camelot, but Kirk spurns cash and rivals feel the pinch.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765066</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABOUT 70 jobs are expected to be lost at Littlewoods Pools' operation
in Glasgow, because of competition from the National Lottery.
They are among 520 redundancies announced by the company yesterday,
and come on top of nearly 600 job losses announced six months ago.
It is expected that most of the 70 staff affected at the company's
base in Hillington will be casual employees. The firm says it hopes many
of the redundancies will be voluntary.
In addition, the company intends to close its Cardiff operation in
November, with the loss of 320 jobs, and to reduce its workforce on
Merseyside by about 130.
Managing director Colin Thwaite said: ''The National Lottery has had
an adverse impact on our business. We have had to fight on unequal
terms.
''Although the Government has made some concessions, it has been too
little and too late, with the consequences we publicly predicted more
than a year ago.''
He added: ''These have been very painful decisions, and we will give
the employees affected every help to find new employment.
''Our employees have given us their full support in all our business
initiatives, and we deeply regret that some of them will not be able to
share in the continuing success that we confidently predict for
Littlewoods Pools and its customers.''
Despite intense competition from the lure of big multi-million pound
National Lottery prizes, Littlewoods still receives about 6,500,000
coupons each week.
Public affairs spokesman Mick Casey said: ''We estimate that
12,000,000 people have a regular interest in the Saturday football
results. But faced with the reduction in income caused by the National
Lottery, and our commitment to maintaining the same level of prize
money, we have reluctantly been forced to shed jobs and cut costs.''
The limited concessions from the Government had included allowing TV
advertising for the pools -- several months after the National Lottery
enjoyed this advantage -- and a slight cut in betting tax.
''Since the launch of the National Lottery, we have been making
repeated representations to the Government to get fairer competition. We
shall continue to lobby Ministers on this crucial issue,'' added Mr
Casey.
The job losses announced yesterday will cut the company's workforce to
about 2200. The latest redundancies are in addition to almost 600 job
losses announced in February, about 80 in Glasgow.
Camelot, operators of the National Lottery, said it was sorry to hear
of job losses, but had always believed there was enough room in the
market for both pools and lottery.
A spokesperson added: ''Indeed, the National Lottery has been good
news for the pools, in that there have been a number of changes in the
law which have benefited them.''
Meanwhile, Camelot plans to increase its top scratchcard prizes to
#100,000, or more, and sell its cards in every pub and club. Trial sales
have started in 75 licensed premises throughout Britain in a bid to
increase flagging turnover on scratchcards, now down to #29m a week,
compared to around #63m to #65m spent on the National Lottery.
</TEXT>
