<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rwanda refugees flee repatriation troops</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765067</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Goma
Thousands of Rwandan refugees among them the blind, lame, and infants,
fled camps in Zaire today to avoid forced repatriation while Zairean
troops expelled more than 2000 by dumping them on the border with
Rwanda.
Cheering and waving rifles, Zairean soldiers made no secret of their
joy at seeing the Rwandans go, dragging a man on crutches over the
border as terrified refugees watched and barefoot children scattered in
panic.
Peter Kessler, a spokesman for the UN High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR), said 26,000 Rwandan refugees had abandoned three camps near the
eastern Zairean town of Uvira and fled into the hills to avoid being
forcibly repatriated.
Zairean troops in the Uvira region forced 400 refugees into Burundi
and 100 into Rwanda, while soldiers in the border town of Bukavu forced
200 more back into Rwanda.
Further north, refugees were forced out of Mugunga camp near Goma town
to a border crossing, where they were manhandled off buses and trucks in
no-man's land leading to the Rwandan town of Gisenyi.
UN officials said 400 Hutu refugees crossed from eastern Zaire into
north-west Rwanda this morning and by late afternoon 1600 others were
abandoned in no-man's land.
Zaire said it would ignore a letter from the UN High Commissioner for
Refugees, Sadako Ogata, asking it to stop expelling Rwandans.
''Tomorrow we hope to speed things up,'' said Mutiri wa Bashara,
refugee adviser to Prime Minister Kengo wa Dondo, who is under strong
opposition pressure to resolve the refugee crisis on Zaire's borders.
Some one million Rwandan Hutus fled into Zaire a year ago after the
Hutu-led government and army -- responsible for the genocide of a
million Tutsis and moderate Hutus -- were defeated by rebels of the
minority Tutsi tribe.
Defeated Hutu soldiers are also holed up in the Zaire camps, refusing
to return out of fear of being arrested or attacked in revenge for last
year's massacres.
Zaire began to deport the refugees on Saturday, expelling more than
200, and said it would keep doing so daily until the United Nations took
responsibility for their return.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
