<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Disaster blamed on human error</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765070</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ferozabad
THE death toll in India's worst-ever train crash rose to at least 335
today as Prime Minister Narasimha Rao blamed human error for the
disaster.
Rescue work outside Ferozabad station was continuing 36 hours after
the Purushottam Express smashed into the back of the stationary Kalindi
Express while travelling at 60mph early yesterday.
Army rescue workers sifted through the twisted steel strewn around the
railway embankment, collecting remains from the wreckage.
A railway official said 320 bodies had so far been recovered from the
crash, and another 15 to 20 bodies remained inside the mangled shell of
a carriage still to be cleared.
Rao, in charge of the railways in the absence of Minister C K Jaffer
Sharief, who is in London for medical treatment, ordered an inquiry into
the crash.
''Prima facie, it is a human error but the real cause will be known
after the inquiry,'' he told Parliament.
Angry opposition MPs demanded Rao's resignation in a six-hour debate
on the crash.
Senior railway officials said a signalman had given the Purushottam
Express a green light without checking whether the other train had left
his sector, and the guard of the Kalindi Express had failed to switch on
a flashing light to indicate his train had stopped after hitting a cow.
The Press Trust of India (PTI) quoted Northern Railways general
manager V K Aggarwal as saying the signalman who gave the green light to
the express had fled.
Parliament passed a motion of sympathy for the relatives of the
victims and stood in silence as a mark of respect for the dead.
Several coaches on the Purushottam Express from the pilgrim town of
Puri in eastern India were filled with soldiers, and officials said
there were at least 68 army personnel among the dead. Sixteen young
athletes returning from a training camp also died.
India's previous worst train accident was in 1981 when 270 people were
killed after a train plunged into the Bhagmati River in the northern
state of Bihar.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
