<DOCNO>GH950822-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Oil deal for Nigg terminal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765072</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE large oil terminal at Nigg on the Cromarty Firth is to get a new
lease of life transferring crude oil from the Alba field between
tankers.
Oil from the North Sea field, which lies 124 miles north-east of
Aberdeen and is operated by US firm Chevron, will be taken to Nigg in
small tankers where it will be loaded into larger vessels for export.
The Nigg terminal was built in the late 1970s to handle oil coming
through the pipeline from the nearby Beatrice field.
However, its output has declined to just one tanker-load each month.
An additional twelve tankers a year will use the terminal for exporting
Alba's output.
A similar number of vessels use Nigg for exporting oil from the
Gryphon Field in the Moray Firth, in a deal struck last year.
BP said yesterday it was confident that the trans-shipments, which
will start next month, could be done without risk of pollution, after it
had commissioned independent safety reports.
</TEXT>
