<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tougher entry qualifications for teacher training courses</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765073</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOUGHER entry requirements for teacher training courses were announced
yesterday by the Scottish Office.
From the year 2000, candidates for places on the BEd or postgraduate
certificate of education courses to become primary teachers will need
Standard Grade mathematics at the top credit level.
Presently they need a credit or lower general level Standard Grade in
the subject.
Ordinary degree graduates seeking admission to the one-year,
postgraduate course to become secondary school teachers will need to
have studied the subject they plan to specialise in for three years at
university, rather than the two years presently specified.
The announcement came after an extensive consultation exercise on the
main proposals for the entry requirements for teacher education courses.
The deputy general secretary of the Educational Institute of Scotland,
Mr Fred Forrester, said: ''Improvements are always to be welcomed but
the practical implications have to be looked at.
''We want to know how many existing entrants to teacher training would
be excluded under these arrangements but we have not had an answer from
the Scottish Office.''
The number of teacher training places is controlled each year in an
effort to match demand for courses with vacancies in schools.
* Scottish Education Minister Raymond Robertson yesterday announced a
#750,000 training package for careers teachers aimed at improving the
advice and information schools provide to youngsters.
Careers teachers and librarians in secondary schools will benefit from
the initiative, which is part of an #8.5m funding package for careers'
education and guidance.
Mr Robertson said: ''Poor information or advice from teachers can lead
to school leavers choosing the wrong jobs or education and training
courses.
''A poor choice when leaving school can leave a young person
demoralised and dispirited.''
Over the next three school sessions careers teachers would be able to
receive training to update their knowledge and skills, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000145</DOCNO>
