<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tranent's bloodiest day carved in history</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765074</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MEMORIAL to one of the bloodiest atrocities in Scotland is to be
unveiled nearly 200 years after the event.
Twelve people were killed and up to 20 injured by regular cavalry
units during the Tranent Militia Riot of 1797, which was sparked off by
the Government's decision to introduce a militia -- a form of compulsory
military service -- into Scotland.
Regarded as ''Scotland's forgotten massacre'', it will be remembered
on September 2 with the unveiling of a 10ft bronze statue, commissioned
for Tranent by East Lothian District Council, in the town's Civic
Square.
It depicts local woman Jackie Crookston who is said to have led a mob
through Tranent before the riot, beating her drum, and calling on people
to stand up for their rights.
Local councillor Tom Ferguson said yesterday that this was ''a
politically important as well as bloody episode'' in Scotland's history
and the subject of a cover-up at the highest level.
''It is now fitting that the events surrounding the massacre will be
remembered and the lives lost marked in such an appropriate fashion,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Council warns US not to ship waste to Dounreay</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765075</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HIGHLAND Regional Council has written to the US Department of Energy
warning it not to consider shipping nuclear waste for reprocessing at
Dounreay until sources of radioactive contamination at the Caithness
plant have been properly identified and remedied.
It also warns that any move to send waste would become a source of
considerable political conflict.
The region's director of law and administration, Mr Harold Farquhar,
wrote to Washington following reports in The Herald on July 20 that a
consultation process was being conducted by the Department of Energy
over 60 days into what should happen to highly radioactive waste from
research reactors across Europe and elsewhere.
The American public have been asked to consider three options:
acceptance and management of the foreign reactor spent nuclear fuel in
the US; facilitating such management overseas, most likely at Dounreay;
or a combination of the two.
The consultation period ended last month but the Department of Energy
agreed to accept comments from Highland Regional Council after the
closing date.
In his letter to Mr Charles Head, of the Office of Spent Nuclear Fuel
Management at the Energy Department, Mr Farquhar says Highland Regional
Council has concerns about Dounreay, as the planning authority and in
its wider political role.
He writes: ''Concern has, for example, emerged with regards to
standards of waste accumulation and management, with particular
reference to the feature known as the 'Dounreay Shaft' and to the Low
Level Waste Pit System.
''There has been further recent adverse publicity regarding the
identification of instances of environmental pollution which may also be
linked to the issue of the shaft.
''Such concerns have been raised as a matter of business before the
full council and are the subject of further investigation by the
appropriate regulatory bodies.
''The uncertainties in respect of the shaft and environmental
pollution have led the council to conclude that no negotations on
further reprocessing at Dounreay should take place until all such
matters are properly investigated and remedial actions put in place.
''The council will be seeking assurances from the UK Government that
remedial work will be started as soon as the most appropriate options
are ascertained.
''It must also be said that, in addition to the council's basic
concern at the prospect of continuing reprocessing, many members have
strong reservations regarding the whole question of the importation of
foreign fuels.''
Mr Farquhar adds that the council hopes to have an early meeting with
the appropriate regulatory bodies. It had also resolved to examine the
planning issues.
He continues: ''It is not at this time clear that Dounreay has all the
necessary statutory permissions to undertake the work that may be
offered and obtaining such necessary permissions will almost inevitably
attract the closest public scrutiny and debate, with the possible
prospect of potentially lengthy public examination of the issues and, at
this stage, no guarantee that such permission can be obtained.
''Even if the permissions were obtained, all the evidence is that
political activity at a local and national level would continue, making
the matter one of open, public conflict over a protracted period.''
A spokesman for the Atomic Energy Authority at Dounreay told The
Herald last night that he could not comment on a letter he had not read.
He stressed, however, that the reprocessing work that was being
considered had been a feature of the plant's activities for nearly 40
years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Don't bank on the dog deterring the burglar</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765076</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DOGS do not scare off burglars, according to a bank, and it has
scrapped plans to bring in cheaper house insurance for owners.
Research by Barclays shows that there may be a sign saying beware of
the dog, but thieves seldom do.
Barclays already gives lower rates of home contents insurance to
security-conscious householders with window locks, alarms and those who
are members of neighbourhood watch schemes.
It decided to investigate whether households with dogs are broken into
less often in order to become the first insurance firm to extend the
discount scheme to dog owners.
Its study found that the burglary rate for homes with dogs compared
with those without was negligible: just 2%. Twelve percent of dog owners
have been burgled, compared with 14% of households without dogs.
A bank spokesman said: ''We do offer discounts on home contents
insurance for a variety of reasons, so we decided to see if having a dog
might also lead to a cheaper rate.
''However, we found there was no real difference to speak of, just 2%
which is not enough for us to offer doggie discounts.''
The bank is warning people who may buy a dog simply for security.
''Dogs make great pets and can truly be man's best friend. But people
should think twice about getting a dog just for protection,'' the
spokesman said.
''A dog is not a substitute for good locks on all doors and windows
and an approved security device.''
Mr Alan King, assistant marketing director of Barclays Financial
Services, reinforced the warning. ''There are people who believe that
Fido is a good alternative to installing an approved security device and
taking out a home insurance policy.''
Its research also disclosed that 41% of Britain's 22 million
households have a dog or have had one in the last five years.
The most popular are mongrels, kept by 26% of dog owners.
Preferred pedigree breeds include collies, labradors, alsatians,
Yorkshire terriers, Jack Russells, and golden retrievers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bid to make planning an easier business</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765077</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Office is to make it easier for councils to set up
special zones where planning procedures are simplified to help promote
local business development.
There are at present only four Simplified Planning Zones -- in
Coatbridge, Dingwall, Grangemouth docks, and Alness/Invergordon. The
complicated procedures which have been needed to establish such zones
have been identified as the main disincentive.
SPZs grant planning permission for specified types of development
within a zone, rather than for each individual development.
In future, councils will not be legally bound to hold a public local
inquiry when a zone is set up. Instead, they will be able to consider
any objections themselves or appoint a person to consider the objections
for them if they think a full local inquiry would not be appropriate.
Scottish Industry Minister George Kynoch said the new SPZs could make
planning procedures easier for businesses and could be a useful tool for
councils to promote particular areas for development.
They were often used as part of a package of measures to help urban
regeneration.
Mr Kynoch said the new procedures aimed to encourage both local
authorities and developers to bring forward planning proposals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scotland's spiritual soil in Estonia</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHARLES KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765078</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Charles Kennedy finds himself in strangely familiar surroundings in a
little corner of Estonia.
THERE is part of a far, foreign field that is forever -- Scotland. As
the former Soviet Baltic state of Estonia prepares to commemorate the
fourth anniversary of its independence, another celebration is being
planned in the country's capital, Tallin, to mark the second birthday of
the city's popular Scottish Club. Soti Klubi, it seems, has captured the
mood of the new, self-confident Estonia.
''Estonians just love your whisky,'' explains the club president, Awar
Ravam, a real-estate dealer. This summer he will lead his second
planeload of intrepid Estonians on something of a ''whisky pilgrimage''
to Scotland. Toivo Lepik, the Klubi's managing director, confirms the
attraction of our greatest export, detailing with pride the 75 different
whisky brands arranged around the agreeable bar.
It seems that some healthy collaboration between the president and the
MD (whose architect wife runs a high-profile building restoration
business -- projects including the presidential palace and the national
parliament building) has helped achieve the quite remarkable outcome
which is this cosy, secluded, but highly popular venue. The club is set
in an attractive strip of land adjacent to the ancient fortified city
walls; it's rather like securing planning permission for a bistro
beneath Edinburgh Castle. A small putting green with St Andrew's flags
in the holes is under construction.
The club has certainly been attracting the movers and shakers of the
capital city. The Prime Minister and the British ambassador feature as
members. On my afternoon visit I came across an Estonian member of
parliament.
Clearly the club has God on its side. It was blessed on day one by His
Holiness the Pope. The Pontiff's Baltic excursion took the Popemobile
past the front door of Soti Klubi.
The club and its rapid success are testament to the growing links
beween old Scotia and the new Estonia. Post independence, a division
from the tartan army turned up in town a couple of years back to see the
Scottish football team triumph; more than a few still seem to be here.
Independence in Europe and the Scottish team winning have proved an
irresistible elixir for diehard nationalists like Phil Lawrence from
Buckie (exploring publishing opportunities regionally) and Chris McLean,
the SNP's former head of communications, now engaged to a local lass and
developing a travel business. I hope that Alex Salmond is pursuing an
Estonia foreign registration drive.
I was amused to learn that the Estonian national musical instrument is
the bagpipe.
The Scottish input is also apparent on a more official level. Scottish
Enterprise is represented here by Stephen Hall -- his role being to
advise the Estonian Investment Agency. Strathclyde Police have been
helping with some law and order training locally.
Her Majesty's Britannic Ambassador, the majestically titled Charles R
L De Chassiron, tells me that the only serious headaches he's had over
the Scottish-Estonian link have come when some of our number have kicked
up a rumpus over a refusal to accept Scottish pound notes. Since I could
take you to shops in Westminster where a similar complaint could be
made, this seems not too fundamental a problem.
I also took our man in Estonia's advice over that formidable gantry of
whisky around the bar. Soti Klubi may constitute Scottish soil
spiritually, but even the visiting political drinker does not enjoy
subsequent diplomatic immunity. Still, at least my self-control leaves
all the more whisky for the second birthday party, which club members
seem unlikely to be able to remember.
* Charles Kennedy is the Liberal Democrat MP for Ross, Cromarty and
Skye.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000150</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000150</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Blair faces renewed fight over all-women shortlists</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765079</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leader Tony Blair last night faced pressure to retain the
controversial women-only shortlists after the next General Election.
His plans to drop the idea could face opposition, the Shadow Minister
for women, Ms Clare Short, warned.
Ms Short insisted that there was ''a chance'' that the shortlists
could remain in place, and said it would take more than one attempt to
transform the face of Parliament.
Mr Blair said in an interview with PA News last month that the process
had ''not been ideal'' and claimed it was strictly a one-off experiment.
The shortlist is designed to ensure that women candidates are selected
to fight half of all marginal seats, in an attempt to increase
dramatically the number of women MPs.
The system, already under threat in the courts from disgruntled
would-be male candidates, has been strongly backed by leading women MPs.
Ms Short appeared to add to the problems facing Mr Blair over a long
summer in which restless Labour left-wingers have accused him of
adopting Kremlin-style tactics in party management.
She told BBC Radio 4's The World at One there was a worldwide
recognition that democracies were incomplete and political parties
distorted through a lack of women representatives.
''Mr Blair must speak for himself. He is not backing away from it now
-- we are going through it for this cycle -- what he has said in one
interview with the PA is we might not repeat it in the next cycle and we
may not. We will look at it again.
''The failure to have women in Parliament in equal numbers is part of
the inadequacy of democratic representation in the world,'' she said.
''What we are saying is we should have an equal chance for men and
women, half and half in different regions of the country, so that in our
next round we will have equal numbers of men and women coming in, and if
we do that a few times it will transform and improve the British
Parliament.''
A spokesman for Mr Blair made it clear that, although the policy would
be reviewed formally after the election, the leadership remained opposed
to continuing it.
Mr Blair told PA News last month: ''It was always seen as a one-off
process and these arguments are by and large being settled and we are
manging to work by consent.''
The Labour leader yesterday resumed the holiday he broke for VJ Day
commemorations, leaving his deputy, Mr John Prescott, to warn of the
danger of too much open dissent and ''unhelpful criticism'' of the
leadership style.
He said the party did not want to ''shut down debate'' but warned that
the Tory high command was waiting to seize on every show of disunity.
''We do want to say to some of our colleagues: do remember we are in
the propaganda season and the Tories clearly intend to use their
remarks, however unhelpful or perhaps not intended in that way, to best
propaganda effect,'' said Mr Prescott.
However, the thinly-veiled dispute over women's shortlists once again
highlighted the simmering discontent over the pace of change in party
policy that could yet undermine Mr Blair at the Labour conference in
Brighton in October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Spirits and beer worth #200m held after raids</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765080</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CUSTOMS officers and police yesterday seized spirits and beer worth up
to #200m, and made more than a dozen arrests, in what they believe to be
Britain's biggest excise duty fraud.
Around 250 Customs officers, aided by police -- some armed -- raided
38 premises, including cash and carry outlets, bonded warehouses, and
private addresses across London.
Officials believe the drink, marked for tax-free export only, was
destined to be sold on the domestic market without taxes having been
paid. The potential loss in duties to the Inland Revenue is estimated at
more than #100m.
The operation, codenamed Fluke, was the culmination of a
two-month-long surveillance exercise.
Transport companies were also targeted and several commercial vehicles
were seized. It is understood the drink was destined for distribution
through a chain of cash and carry spirits outlets around London.
The alleged fraud involves drink being purchased from legitimate
producers and stored in bonded warehouses. Documents are then falsified
to indicate it has been exported. In fact, the goods are moved around a
succession of warehouses before being channelled to outlets across the
capital.
It is then sold on at normal prices without duty being paid by the
distributors.
Commenting on the investigation, Mr David Heathcoat-Amery MP,
Paymaster General and the Minister responsible for Customs, said: ''This
successful operation underlines our determination to crack down on those
carrying out such frauds against, not only the taxpayer, but also
legitimate businesses.''
The inquiry is continuing, a Customs spokesman said.
</TEXT>
