<TEXT>
AMBITIOUS plans by the Edinburgh International Festival to convert
this nineteenth-century church into its headquarters were yesterday
unveiled to a wider world audience.
Taking advantage of the global media in the capital, festival
organisers organised a tour of the grade-A listed Highland Tolbooth,
only a stone's throw from Edinburgh Castle.
The festival is to seek lottery funding of #3m towards the #7m cost of
converting the kirk, once the home of the General Assembly of the Church
of Scotland. It is in partial use as a cafe and souvenir shop but
organisers hope to create a round-the-year arts attraction, which could
also be used as a conference centre, and provide administration and
ticket offices and a home for the Festival Club.
It is hoped to begin work next year with the building reopening in
1997 to mark the festival's 50th anniversary. Lothian region and
Edinburgh district councils are to be asked for #250,000 and some
#500,000 has already been pledged by Lothian and Edinburgh Enterprise.
</TEXT>
