<HEADLINE>Mother asks for public's help over body-in-drain killing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765082</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE GRIEVING mother of catering assistant Deirdre Kivlin, whose
decomposed body was found last week dumped in a drain behind an
Edinburgh tenement, yesterday branded her killer ''a cruel, vicious and
twisted person''.
Mrs Ruth Kivlin sat calmly at St Leonards police station -- a few
hundred yards from where her daughter was found -- and sent this message
to the killer:
''I don't know how you can live with what you've done. You are a
danger to other people, and for your own sake you ought to give yourself
up.
''There was absolutely no reason to do this to her and leave her in
such an appalling way.''
The body of 24-year-old Ms Kivlin -- well known for her community work
as well as her role as a karaoke singer under the stage name, The Voice,
at clubs and pubs -- was found by workmen last Thursday in a drain
beneath a manhole cover behind tenements in South Clerk Street.
Ms Kivlin left home in Greendykes Drive, Craigmillar, on July 8, and
it has now been established that the last sighting of her was around
1.40am the next day, about 30 yards from where her body was found.
She was seen standing alone at the corner of Newington Road at West
Preston Street, close to the Goodwill Chinese restaurant.
Her mother, 56, accompanied by her son, David, 29, told a news
conference on the fourth day of the investigation that her daughter had
loved life and was always smiling.
''She just wouldn't do a bad turn to anybody. She loved her drama,
music and karaoke and she was only happy when she was helping in the
community.
Mrs Kivlin, who said her daughter had helped in nurseries and play
schemes, said: ''I knew either someone was holding her against her will
or she had been murdered.
''We were very distressed when she went missing, but for this to have
happened is horrible and very hard to come to terms with.''
Urging the public to help the investigation, she said: ''If you know
anything at all, please tell the police, so the person who did this to
my daughter can be brought to justice before another horrible crime is
committed.''
Detective Chief Inspector Ian Cowden, who is heading the
investigation, said that when last seen Ms Kivlin was alone and at that
stage wearing a beige and fawn anorak -- which had been recovered -- a
short black dress, a black blouse knotted to the front, black tights and
black, high-heeled shoes.
She was carrying a black shoulder bag, which detectives are still
trying to find.
''Deirdre seemed to be quite fond of jewellery and we have not
accounted for it all. That is a very strong line of inquiry at the
moment,'' Mr Cowden said.
He said that the young woman had died of head injuries and there was
no indication of sexual assault.
</TEXT>
