<HEADLINE>Rage of hawks and Hamas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER DOBSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765083</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Christopher Dobson explains why Hamas and Jewish militants have common
cause in seeing the Israeli-PLO peace agreement fail
THE euphoria which greeted the Israeli-PLO agreement two years ago has
virtually vanished under the series of suicide bomb attacks mounted by
Hamas militants. Now, with each bomb, the survival of Yitzhak Rabin's
Labour government and the entire peace process becomes increasingly
questionable.
One has only to look at the fury on the faces of the Israelis,
overwhelmed by anger and grief, as rabbis pick through the wreckage of a
bus to find pieces of what were once human beings, to appreciate the
dangers faced by the peacemakers.
''Murderer,'' shout the demonstrators -- not at Palestinians but at
their own Prime Minister. He reacts in the only way he can by shutting
off Gaza and suspending, but not cancelling, the peace talks. ''We shall
continue,'' says Foreign Secretary Shimon Peres, architect of the Oslo
agreement. But for how long will they be able to do so?
There will be a General Election in Israel next year and if the latest
opinion poll is correct the Labour Party will be overwhelmingly defeated
by the far-right Likud. Well aware of the danger, Rabin is hurrying to
conclude as many agreements as possibly with the PLO leadership before
time runs out.
Only three days ago the Israeli Cabinet approved the handing over of a
range of civilian powers in the West Bank to Yasser Arafat's Palestinian
authority. They include responsibility for transport, labour, mail, fuel
and agriculture and the Ministers were told that a full agreement
extending Palestinian rule throughout the region could be reached within
the month.
Then came yesterday's bomb, with the threat of more to come. If the
talks are suspended every time an atrocity is carried out, then Prime
Minister Rabin will not achieve his objectives by the time he goes to
the country. And, of course, the temper of the country will grow more
ferocious with every outrage.
Hamas, deliberately, is playing into the hands of those Israelis who
believe that the only good Arab is a dead Arab. These are Israelis who
are just as fanatical as the Islamic fundamentalists. These, curiously,
are not very often the ''sabras'', the Israelis who have lived all their
lives alongside the Palestinians -- and fought against them -- but
religious theorists from America who believe that the whole of Palestine
should belong to Israel.
They were always going to oppose the peace settlement, but stood
little chance of destroying it until the suicide bombers struck. Now
they are gaining support from many who gave cautious approval to the
settlement but under the impact of the bombs have begun to fear that
they and their nation could never be safe with militant Palestinians
controlling the West Bank and Gaza and with Syria in reoccupation of the
Golan Heights.
Among them are respected men like David Bar-Illan, executive editor of
the Jerusalem Post who wrote of his doubts about the peace accord when
it was signed: ''One would have to believe . . . that the Middle East,
where there is not one democracy except Israel, can turn into a European
Community, with Jordan, 'Palestine' and Israel forming a Benelux of the
Levant. It is the kind of leap of faith which would make Scheherazade
green with envy.'' Now he has even more cause to be doubtful. It is this
ground-swell of fear among the moderates which poses the greatest danger
to Rabin.
The man who would take over if that ground-swell sweeps the Labour
government away next year is the hardline leader of Likud, Benjamin
Netanyahu. He has personal reasons for hating the Palestinians; his
brother, Yoni, led the Israeli special forces in the raid on Entebbe and
died rescuing the hostages.
He accuses Rabin of leading Israel towards war rather than peace,
arguing that the army's planned withdrawal from the West Bank would
create a base for Islamic terrorism, second only to Iran. As for the
Golan Heights, he says there has been no trouble there because the
Israeli guns are within spitting distance of Damascus and while they are
there President Assad ''does not have the option of making war''.
He is contemptuous about Gaza. He says that if Likud wins the
election, ''we will not re-enter Gaza on a permanent basis. Arafat can
keep Gaza''. His implication is that if there were any further trouble
from terrorist organisations operating from Gaza, they would be severely
dealt with.
What would Likud's policy be?
He spelt it out in a Knesset press conference: Israel would break off
talks with the PLO, reinstitute the right of ''hot pursuit'' into Gaza
and Jericho and offer the Palestinians a modified form of autonomy
limited to municipal affairs that would not give them any control of
security or territory. They would have less power than a British local
authority.
Obviously, no Palestinian leader could accept such conditions. It
would be tantamount to signing his own death warrant. Under such a
regime the peace process would inevitably collapse, which is precisely
what Hamas -- and the Israeli hawks want.
Middle-Eastern politics has thrown up many strange bedfellows, but to
have Hamas and the hawks working together for the same ends is bizarre.
Both want the peace process to fail and both are prepared to use extreme
methods to bring about that failure.
It would only be after it had been achieved that their aims would
differ. The Israeli hawks would rely on the power of the Israeli armed
forces to crush Palestinian opposition. Hamas would seek the removal of
Israeli settlers still living in the Gaza Strip, withdrawal from the
West Bank and reoccupation by the Arabs of East Jerusalem. Meanwhile,
according to Hamas leader Aymad Fallouji, the divinely ordained armed
struggle against Israel must go on.
Earlier this year General ''Arik'' Sharon, a former Defence Minister
and a leading member of Likud, outlined a draconian plan for dealing
with the Islamic terrorists. He would deport the families of the human
bombs, take action against terrorist leaders living abroad, and mount
security sweeps to seize ''wanted terrorists'' in Gaza and Jericho and
take them back to Israel for trial. Sharon, always the advocate of the
iron fist, left no doubt that he would use it if he came to power.
Asked if he was concerned that such action would destroy the
Israeli-PLO accord, he replied: ''This agreement is supposed to provide
security, but instead it brings bloodshed and many more casualties; who
needs this peace?''
The only answer to that question is: the rest of the world.
</TEXT>
