<HEADLINE>Terrorist 'martyrs' from mean streets</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER DOBSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765084</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* HAMAS, the Palestinian group which has claimed responsibility for
yesterday's suicide bombing in Jerusalem, is in the long line of Islamic
secret societies stretching back to the eleventh century when Sheik
al-Jabal, The Old Man of the Mountains, sent his hashish-eating
assassins out from his mountain fortress of Alamut to impose his will on
the Middle East by murder. They were deadly because they were not only
prepared to die for their cause but welcomed it as a step towards
paradise.
Today, the shadowy leaders of Hamas send out their assassins from the
slums of Gaza to wreck the Palestinian peace process. They too go
willingly to their deaths. And when these ''living martyrs'' die, their
families celebrate, for they have achieved immortality and their
families are honoured.
Hamas is an acronym for Islamic Resistance Movement and in Arabic it
means Zeal. The organisation came into being in the late 1970s as a
religious and cultural organisation and it did much good, providing
nursing and educational facilities in the West Bank and Gaza, obtaining
much credit among the poor, dispirited people of those areas.
At first it was tolerated by the Israelis as a counterbalance to the
secular PLO; but when the Palestinian revolution, the ''intifada'',
broke out spontaneously on the West Bank and Gaza without the help of
the PLO, Hamas provided an increasingly militant leadership for the
young stone-throwers.
With its roots in the mean streets and the villages, unlike the big
hotel and diplomatic life of the PLO leaders, it talked the same
language as the fiery young men who battled on the streets with the
Israeli army. And it was the intifada as much as any other factor that
led to the handshake between Yitzhak Rabin and Yasser Arafat.
When the PLO made peace with Israel, Hamas became more political and
more religious. It is totally opposed to any agreement with Israel.
The Israelis are finding Hamas an elusive enemy. In the old days when
a PLO-affiliated organisation such as the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine carried out an operation, the Israelis knew
where to find them. Within hours, Israeli warplanes would hurtle over
the Lebanese border and pound a PFLP headquarters.
They cannot do that with Hamas, for it has no established
headquarters, no camps with big guns and equipment to destroy -- all
Hamas needs to carry out its acts of terror are a few pounds of
explosives and a young man willing to die for the cause. It is that most
deadly of terrorist organisations: fanatical but with no infrastructure
and no expense accounts.
The ''living martyrs'' are sent to Iran and Sudan for their training
and then infiltrated back into Gaza where security is now in the hands
of Yasser Arafat's police. It is a simple matter for them to join the
thousands of Palestinians who cross into Israel every day to work.
</TEXT>
