<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fears over safety could end playing in the park. Anxieties that keep children inside</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765085</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PARENTS' anxieties about their children's safety have reached
unprecedented levels, to the detriment of parents and children alike,
according to a report published today by the children's charity
Barnardo's.
A survey conducted for Barnardo's presents a bleak picture of confused
parents who think their children spend too much time watching
television, too much time on their own, and less time outdoors. Yet most
of them are unwilling to let their children go out more often without
adult supervision.
Barnardo's says that two-thirds of parents it surveyed say that
children being approached by strangers is a big worry for them when the
children are outside.
Yet the official statistics show their fears are unfounded. Between
1983 and 1993, an average of 86 children were killed every year in
England and Wales. However, the number murdered by strangers is an
average of five a year.
The truth is that children are far more likely to be killed by their
parents or people looking after them.
Yet because of fears about strangers, many children are kept shut
inside houses, possibly arresting their development, while play areas
outside are left empty.
Other parents attempt to compensate by taking their children to
paid-for activities such as sports centres and swimming pools -- but
these activities are often too expensive for poorer families.
As Mr Hugh Mackintosh, director of Barnardo's Scotland, said
yesterday: ''Today's children, particularly those from poorer homes, are
not getting enough freedom to play independently.
''In addition, in Scotland, we found that where there are play areas,
parents don't want to let their children go to them unsupervised for
fear of bullies, strangers, and traffic.''
He says it is fundamentally wrong if children's chances of playing
safely are affected simply because of where they live. ''Children need
to be able to play independently in order to develop physically,
emotionally, and intellectually.''
Mr Mackintosh pointed out that it was not just a question of parents
spending money on their children. It was important that they also spent
time creatively as a family outdoors, which did not have to involve
expense.
While parents believe they are protecting their children by keeping
them indoors more, the opposite may be happening. Child psychologist Dr
Ned Mueller, interviewed on the subject for tonight's Public Eye
programme on BBC, states that children deprived of the freedom to play
unsupervised often fail to develop vital social and language skills.
''Our survival depends on social development,'' he says. ''We have to
take play and use it in the service of joining with other people or we
are doomed.''
One indoor play venture in Essex is even introducing electronic
tagging of children using the centre to reassure worried parents.
Apart from what is called ''stranger danger,'' parents also have fears
about traffic, drugs, and bullying. Children from poor backgrounds are
nearly four times at risk of being knocked down and killed. Some of this
may be due to them being more likely to be on the streets. Parents with
cars are more likely to drive them to where they are going.
Over drugs, parents expressed worries about children playing in parks
where there may be discarded needles lying about, or drug users around.
The survey for Barnardo's shows that 60% of parents believe that
children spend less time outdoors than they did; 93% believe their
children watch more television than they did; 85% believe safety of
children playing outdoors has decreased; and 41% believe the amount of
time a child spends alone has increased since their day.
As one parent told Barnardo's: ''Years ago, we would play outside all
the time. We played netball and hide-and-seek. We used to tie ropes
around the lampposts and use them as swings. But things have changed
now. Kids can't go outside. The traffic is terrible here.''
How much of the risks to children is real or just imagined by parents
is open to debate. However, as the Barnardo's report, Playing It Safe,
states: ''A climate in which parents and children themselves feel uneasy
about their place in the world -- their right to roam freely, even in
their local neighbourhoods or nearby parks -- is clearly not good for
children's development and independence, nor for adult piece of mind.''
Mr Mackintosh says that play schemes, after-school clubs, and holiday
clubs must be considered a priority, particularly in the poorest
communities. Local authorities should work with voluntary agencies to
help nurture a sense of community.
He also believes the business community, which spends an estimated
#30bn a year targeting children, should plough some of its profits into
communities by funding play areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
