<HEADLINE>Garbo's guardian 'living in poverty'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765086</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GRETA GARBO'S confidante and live-in best friend for 31 years now
lives in poverty after being all but left out of her employer's will, it
was reported yesterday.
Claire Koger, 89, is surviving in a small fourth-floor flat without a
lift on East 66th Street, the New York Daily News said.
Garbo had promised that after her death, the Swiss-born immigrant
would be taken care of, Koger's legal guardian, Mr Richard Schmidt, told
the News.
However, the reclusive actress reportedly left Koger only #2000 from
her #20m estate, and the rest went to Garbo's niece, Gray Reisfield.
By the end of this year, Koger will be totally out of money, Schmidt
said.
Calling himself ''a huge admirer of Garbo'', he says he's not being
paid for taking on the financial dealings and emotional well-being of
the person he claims knew the Swedish-born actress better than anyone
else.
Koger reportedly screened Garbo's calls, did her tailoring and helped
the ailing star get around.
Schmidt has asked Garbo's niece and her husband for help through their
lawyer, requesting they pay half of Koger's monthly expenses. Schmidt
has received no answer to his letters, he said.
The Reisfields moved into Garbo's apartment overlooking the East River
after she died in 1990. Schmidt entered Koger's life shortly after, when
he sent her a sympathy note.--AP
</TEXT>
</DOC>
