<HEADLINE>Police to investigate local council</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765088</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE are investigating the misuse of public funds within a community
network in a deprived East End district of Glasgow.
This follows a move, earlier this year, by the city council to suspend
Cranhill Community Council and to send in a team of auditors.
Mr Iain Drummond, senior legal adviser, confirmed yesterday that
police had been informed of the findings and that the inquiry had now
spread. ''There are various other matters now under investigation,'' he
told city councillors.
The investigation covers many thousands of pounds of funding over the
last five years. It is now believed to involve the financial affairs of
three other organisations with links to the local Easterhouse
Initiative.
The auditor's report on Cranhill was tabled yesterday at a meeting of
a city council sub-committee which each month meets to monitor community
councils.
However, there was consternation when, without prior notice, a report
from the Community Councils Resource Centre was handed round the table
to committee members. This was a response to criticism in the auditor's
report that the Resource Centre had failed to provide active monitoring
of Cranhill Community Council.
Militant councillor Charles Stevenson, who originally raised the
matter of irregularities, was refused permission to address the
committee. He lost his Queenslie ward last spring to new councillor Gail
McCann who is a prominent figure in local community organisations.
The auditor's report revealed that about #4000 of grants received by
Cranhill were ''inappropriate''. In one instance, the same amount was
duplicated, by mistake, by two funding sources.
Meanwhile, according to the auditors, much of the money flowed out
without receipts, records, or proper documentation.
The report disclosed: ''The auditors were particularly concerned by
the introduction of a second bank account for no justifiable accounting
reason and by the withdrawal from accounts of significant sums in cash
without any supportive information.''
The city-wide supervision system was criticised for a ''lack of active
monitoring''. The report said there were no attempts by council officers
to meet local office bearers or attend management meetings at Cranhill.
Indeed one city councillor who raised concern in March 1994 about the
community council was given assurances and told it was still
functioning. ''This was misleading,'' said the report.
Councillor Ken Gibson, SNP, told the meeting: ''I think it is bad that
Councillor Stevenson is not being allowed to speak. He was the man who
first raised this matter last winter.''
He then asked whose names were recorded as the bank account holders.
But Mr Drummond advised that it would be unwise legally for councillors
to go into details in public. Members he said should simply note the
report.
Councillor Christine Devine, chairing the meeting, advised him to
forward any new information to the town clerk.
In light of the information submitted at the last moment by the
Community Councils Resource Centre, the matter was continued for further
consideration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000160</DOCNO>
