<HEADLINE>US peace plan stalled as Serbs spurn recognition</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765089</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington
THE American peace plan for Bosnia is in trouble. The Secretary of
State, Warren Christopher, has cut short his holiday and returned to
Washington, where he will meet Richard Holbrooke, the US official who
has been plugging the plan in the Balkans.
Three of Mr Holbrooke's colleagues were killed on Mt Igman on
Saturday, and he returned with their bodies today. Mr Christopher and
other senior officials went to the airport to meet them, and President
Clinton will return from vacation for their funeral in Arlington
Cemetery.
The accident occurred as Mr Holbrooke and the others were travelling
to Sarajevo to put their plan to the Bosnian Government.
However, the key to the failure was in Belgrade. Mr Holbrooke was
unable to persuade President Milosevic to make peace with Croatia when
they met in Belgrade last week.
Mr Milosevic refused to recognise Croatia. The essential element of
the American proposal has been that Serbia, Croatia, and Bosnia should
recognise each other. If they don't, the war will continue.
The first snag the American plan encountered was that the Bosnians
were reluctant to agree to exchange the last Muslim enclave in eastern
Bosnia, Gorazde, for land around Sarajevo, which the Americans had
suggested as part of a redrawing of the partition of Bosnia.
The Serbs would be allowed to keep most of their conquests, including
western Bosnia around Banja Luka and the Drina valley, with its formerly
Muslim towns Srebrenica and Zepa. The Muslims would get the hills around
Sarajevo.
As for Serbia and Croatia, the Croats would keep the Krajina, which
they recaptured early this month, and the Serbian refugees would have to
make a new life for themselves elsewhere. The status of eastern Croatia
and its main city, Vukovar, which Serbia captured in 1991, would be left
to the future.
There were signs that the Bosnian Serbs might accept the plan, and it
was assumed Mr Milosevic would be delighted with the proposal. The war
would end and sanctions against Serbia would be lifted. The Americans
expected trouble from the Croats, who want Vukovar immediately, and the
Bosnian Government, which hopes to reconquer its lost territories by
war. The US hoped, perhaps wrongly, that pressure from Washington and
Europe would bring Croatia and Bosnia into line.
But now apparently Serbia has balked. The defeat in Krajina means Mr
Milosevic can make no more concessions for the moment.
This would be a severe blow for President Clinton, whose efforts in
Bosnia have failed constantly. A new failure would mean Congress will
insist on lifting the arms embargo against Bosnia next month.
It might also mean trouble for the British contingent of 180 in
Gorazde. The Serbs are preventing a Ukrainian unit there from leaving,
and the British hoped to follow them later this month. If the war is
about to resume, the Serbs will keep these troops hostage.
Nato proposes to defend Gorazde with air power but did nothing when
Serbian artillery shelled the town today. It may be inhibited from
launching a full-scale attack on Serb positions if British and Ukrainian
troops are trapped there.
</TEXT>
