<HEADLINE>Judge throws out 'racist cop' tapes in Simpson trial</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765090</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Los Angeles
IN WHAT could be a serious blow for O J Simpson's defence team, Judge
Lance Ito today ruled that taped interviews allegedly portraying a
police investigator as a racist may not be introduced as evidence.
Ito said the defence motion to allow into evidence tapes by retired
detective Mark Fuhrman was ''incoherent'' and would not be considered.
However, he left open the possibility that the defence could refile the
motion in the double-murder trial.
Ito rejected the defence motion because it was poorly presented rather
than ruling on the substance of the request to bring the tapes into
evidence.
Simpson, a former US football star, has pleaded innocent to killing
his ex-wife, Nicole Brown Simpson, and her friend, Ronald Goldman, in
June last year.
Fuhrman, who found a bloody glove at Simpson's estate, is a key
witness in the long-running trial and has become a centre of attention
as the defence attempts to portray him as motivated by racism.
As part of this effort, the defence has fought to introduce the taped
interviews Fuhrman gave to a screenwriter over several years which
allegedly demonstrate Fuhrman is a racist policeman capable of planting
evidence to frame Simpson.
Ito singled out 10 instances in which the defence alleges Fuhrman made
racist comments or described police misconduct on the tapes, but said he
could not find the comments at the places the defence said they were in
the transcript.
The question of Fuhrman's credibility is seen by court observers as
crucial to the outcome of the case.
Ito's wife, police Captain Margaret York, is mentioned in the
recordings, but any reference to her was edited out of the tapes he
reviewed.--REUTER/AP
</TEXT>
