<HEADLINE>Stirring a storm from the pulpit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KIRSTY SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765091</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Kirsty Scott examines the row focused on Archbishop O'Brien and his
sermon at a VJ Day service.
IT HAS been a time of conflicting emotions: remembrance,
recrimination, rage and forgiveness, so no-one should have been
surprised at the outcry on Sunday over a VJ-Day speech by the Roman
Catholic Archbishop of St Andrews and Edinburgh.
Standing in St Giles' Cathedral, the Most Rev Keith O'Brien spoke at
some length on the subject of man's inhumanity to man and talked himself
on to the front pages for condemning the attacks on Nagasaki and
Hiroshima.
Yesterday, the Catholic press office was quick to defend the
archbishop, who was said to be uncontactable all day.
''If you take it out of the context it becomes political, and it was
not political,'' said spokesman Father Tom Connelly. ''I spoke to him
last night and I told him about the controversy. He is naturally sorry
about that but he didn't set out to offend anybody.''
In the address, the archbishop started with the Japanese and asked:
''How could they do it? How could so many people in Japan inflict such
suffering on those whom they were fighting, such cruel indignities on
those whom they captured, such ill-treatment and degradation of
thousands of so-called comfort-women . . . those of us who did not
suffer cannot ignore or forget the cry of those whose memories are
indelibly filled with thoughts of horrors and evils which they can never
forget.''
He then moved to the Allies: ''Yes, as we reflect on that question
directed to the action of the Japanese forces, so too must we direct it
to the Allies, to the American forces when we think of the introduction
of atomic warfare into our world, our global village.'' He touched on
current conflicts, nuclear weaponry and ended by calling for us to learn
from the past and look to the future.
Father Connelly said it was wrong to pick on one aspect of the sermon
and try to develop it as the key theme. ''In the first part of the
speech he said it was horrific what the Japanese did, it was cruel and
it was wrong. But he was saying we need to be reconciled and we need to
forgive one another, and if you are going to seek true forgiveness it
has to be based on truth, and the truth of the matter is that we, the
British, weren't without blame. We bombed innocent people in Hiroshima
and Nagasaki, that was equally wrong. Now we've set the record straight,
let's move on.''
Archibishop O'Brien has been the focus of controversy several times
since he was appointed to replace Cardinal Gordon Gray as archbishop in
1985.
He made the headlines for an apparent dispute with then Archbishop
Thomas Winning over the location for Scotland's seminary for training
priests. At the time the split was characterised as an East-West divide.
In 1988, Archbishop O'Brien attacked the film The Last Temptation of
Christ, labelling it blasphemous and saying he would advise people not
to see it. The same year he also spoke out about poverty, blaming
long-term unemployment and reduced social security benefits.
The key to the archbishop's sermon on Sunday was reconciliation and
looking to the future, but it has brought him head-to-head with those
who felt VJ Day should have been given over to looking back, and, more
importantly, looking back from the Western point of view.
While acknowledging the ensuing uproar, the Catholic press office has
been keen to underline the fact that the role of an archbishop is not
always to soothe troubled waters or avoid controversy.
''A prophet will not be popular in the marketplace, not ever,'' said
Father Connelly. ''The truth will set us free, but the truth will hurt .
. .''
</TEXT>
