<HEADLINE>'My father said when you go to Israel, don't get on a bus' --American passenger who fainted. Survivors tell of blast panic</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765092</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jerusalem
TAMARA ROSENBERG missed death by seconds.
She and a friend had just got up from their seats and moved to the
front of a Jerusalem city bus when an explosion ripped through back of
the vehicle today, turning it into a charred, twisted cobweb of metal.
''We are lucky to be alive,'' said Rosenberg, 19, who had arrived in
Jerusalem from Lyon, France, to study Hebrew for three months. She was
wounded in the right foot by flying glass.
Hadassah Segal, 27, from New York City, said she fainted after the
explosion, woke to see bodies next to her and jumped out of a window.
''My father said when you come to Israel, don't get on a bus,'' she
said.
Israeli Orli Ben-Yamini, 20, said there was panic after the blast.
''People yelled and trampled over each other. I was injured from pieces
of glass that were flying all over.''
London-born Esther Chipman, 44, who was watching from her flat across
the street, said: ''We heard screams coming from the bus, people
shouting 'Mummy, mummy'''.
Police suspect the bomber boarded the bus as it made its way across
town toward the Ramat Eshkol neighbourhood in northern Jerusalem.
The driver, Ronen Shmuel, said many of his passengers were students en
route to summer school at the Hebrew University campus at Mount Scopus
as well as policemen riding to work at police headquarters.
When the vehicle moved alongside another bus outside the Rene Cassin
High School, the bomb made up of several kg of TNT detonated.
Spontaneous protests erupted within minutes of the blast, and border
police and riot police were deployed to prevent revenge attacks on
Arabs.
Hundreds of demonstrators jeered and threw stones when Police Minister
Moshe Shahal visited the bomb scene under heavy guard.
President Ezer Weizman was forced to cut short his visit to the scene
after he was mobbed by angry Israelis.
''We want revenge,'' the protesters chanted. However the crowd's main
target was Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who was denounced as a
''traitor'' and ''murderer''.
Weizman, ringed by police for protection, grabbed a bull horn from one
of the officers to address the crowd. ''I came here to be with you, I
can also leave,'' he said testily.
Later, after visiting the wounded in hospital, he said: ''I have never
felt this anger from the public before.''--Reuter.
</TEXT>
