<DOCNO>GH950822-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>TV jester with secret burden</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALLAN LAING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765094</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Allan Laing reprises the trials and tribulations of the comic genius
Michael Barrymore, now being pilloried for declaring his homosexuality
THE damnable thing about cliches is the fact that they are usually
true. Take the old one about the tears of a clown, for example. Michael
Barrymore is one of the funniest men in showbiz but this morning he
probably won't find very much to laugh about. His marriage is in tatters
and his personal life has been laid bare in the pages of the tabloids.
Whatever he may or may not be guilty of -- and there's nothing to
suggest that he's done anything more than be enormously talented and
successful -- he doesn't deserve the merciless hounding he has received.
He's this year's target. It's his turn to eat the hamster.
You might say that, well, serves him right for being famous. It's
always open season on famous people. How dare he try to live what
society deems to be a normal life (he has a wife) when all this time he
has not been prepared to admit openly that he prefers to go to bed with
men? Peter Tatchell, for one, will be rubbing his hands with glee now
that Barrymore has, apparently, publicly declared his homosexuality.
Of course, if it had been someone like Kenneth Williams or Larry
Grayson who'd come out and confessed then no-one would have batted an
eyelid. After all, they were limp-wristed stereotypes. But Barrymore is
different. He doesn't look the part. He might camp it up occasionally on
stage but, when you get down to it, he looks straight -- and that's what
makes his story so damned sexy for the tabloids.
He's also the most popular entertainer in Britain -- everybody's
favourite -- and when you're up there on top then you're automatically
in the line of fire. We can make 'em and we can break 'em.
The sad truth is that Barrymore's roller-coaster life now begins to
make a kind of sense. On the one hand, it has been one of enormous
professional success (with Barrymore and Strike It Lucky two of the
hottest shows on UK television, regularly attracting 13 million viewers;
comedy awards by the barrowload; and voted personality of the year for
the past two years in succession) while, on the other hand, there has
been this tortured private life, a struggle to come to terms with his
sexual identity.
Now we know the burden he had to bear.
Personal problems have been his constant companion. For a start, he
found it difficult to come to terms with his family; he was always at
odds with his mother (his father, a violent drunk, left home when he was
a child). And then there was his battle with drink and drug addiction.
Last year, at the height of his success, he booked himself into a
Baltimore clinic to rid himself of the demon drink. Champagne was his
weakness as well as painkillers, Valium, and marijuana. The
ever-vigilant tabloids, of course, had been alluding to his problems for
years. Gosh, they said, wasn't he looking tired? And so thin. What on
earth could be wrong with him?
Stress and exhaustion, said his army of publicists. Then Barrymore
bravely admitted to his drink problem. Faced it head on. Apparently
conquered it and even joked about it in his show.
He returned to strength, a new man. Leaner and fitter, and maybe even
funnier than he was before. But lurid suggestions about his sexuality
continued to dog him. Was he gay? Bisexual perhaps?
There was the story, resurrected long after the alleged event, about
him stumbling the worse for wear into another male star's hotel room and
making a fumbling pass. Then there was the one about him having sex
(twice) with a former associate. And another about him being spotted
groping a man in a gay bar.
Though he strenuously denied the rumours, the situation placed an
enormous strain on his marriage. At one point he separated briefly from
his wife (and personal manager) Cheryl. Three days later they were back
together, holidaying in the south of France; the panic over.
Now, it seems, the marriage is over. After newspaper reports yesterday
that Barrymore, attending a gay pub in London, had joined a drag artist
on stage, thrown off his wedding ring, and (to the tune of New York, New
York) declared: ''Start spreading the news, I'm gay today.''
Hours after the reports were published, Barrymore's agent released a
statement saying that the couple had parted.
Now the 43-year-old entertainer must wait and see if this latest bout
of adverse publicity will affect his popularity. Providing he does not
despair and seek solace in a bottle, the chances are that it won't. For
a start, once he's picked up the pieces and returned to work, he'll make
a joke of it. That's his way.
Barrymore has built his comic reputation on honest human emotion. His
is an act which at once is surreal and manic and yet it still retains
good, old-fashioned, family entertainment values. That's why his appeal
is almost universal.
It seems unlikely that, in this day and age, his sexual preference
would affect the loyalty of his many fans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000166</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000166</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wheel play</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976765095</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARY BRENNAN encounters a dance company tackling the tacit prejudice
which faces the disabled.
EVER thought what it might be like if you were in a wheelchair? How
the rest of the world would react to you? PSSST! -- performed by Company
Pyke -- will give you a bit of an inkling.
David Toole, from Pyke, explains why: ''Actually it all comes from
things that have happened to us, things people have said or done when
they've seen us.'' Us refers here as much to CandoCo Dance Company as to
any individual. The Pyke performers are all part of CandoCo -- the
highly acclaimed integrated dance company -- and PSSST! is what they're
up to on their holidays.
The ideas started coming together, says Toole, almost as a reaction to
a reaction. ''There's this piece in CandoCo's repertoire -- it's by
Emilyn Claid -- that really used to shock people, upset them badly. And
what it was, was the sex. The sex and the violence. Because disabled
people aren't supposed to have that kind of anger, or those kinds of
relationships. And that set us thinking about all the other things we're
not supposed to want or do. And the way people behave towards the
disabled.
''PSSST! is just our way of saying 'take a look at yourselves'. It's
not out to get people, but it is realistic. It's us saying how things
are. And sometimes they're awful and sometimes you just have to laugh,''
says Toole.
Toole himself has been on the receiving end of widely differing
reactions all his life. Born without legs, he had learned how to move
not just in a wheelchair, but -- with speed and grace -- on his hands.
He was working for the Post Office in his native Leeds, when CandoCo
came to town with a weekend workshop. That chance encounter changed his
life.
Parents and close friends inevitably expressed concern when he elected
to join the group. The mail room in Leeds offered security, CandoCo
offered what seemed like a very public exposure. But Toole had tasted
something vital that swept all those considerations aside. In dance he
had found a way of being his own person.
At the time, however, the rest of the company were unaware of the
extraordinary power he had in his arms. He laughs as he tells what is,
by now, an oft-repeated story. ''We were rehearsing, and I had been
lifted out of my chair. When we stopped, I was being held on the other
side of the room. So I just dropped down and charged across the room on
my arms . . .'' Since then, Toole has dazzled audiences, and critics,
with the expressiveness of his dance. It's led, in fact, to a subtler
form of discrimination!
''People always tend to congratulate me backstage about Please The
Desert and totally ignore Kuldip'', he says with a wry grin. Kuldip
dances superbly in the duet -- but he happens to be able-bodied! It's
reactions like this, moments of well-intentioned condescension or
cavalier insensitivity, that Company Pyke has decided to make fun of in
a very serious way.
It's all a question of how you look at things and at people. Pyke had
decided to let us know how it feels like when the looks are sometimes
curious, not always kind.
* PSSST! is at the Pleasance from today until September 2 (except
August 30).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000167</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000167</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Courage to buttress the spirits</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN FOWLER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765096</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Diana Rigg shot to fame as a leather-clad Avenger -- but these days
she gets her kicks out of helping theatre at the grass roots. John
Fowler gets an earful of the new tune as she launches a new season at
Stirling.
SOOK, blaw -- surely there's some mistake. Diana Rigg playing the
moothie? She who was Emma Peel, the long-limbed, leather-clad Avenger?
It's not part of the dream that we males of a certain age cherish from
our tele-viewing in the sixties.
But times change and we all grow older. Young lithe actresses mature
and take up the challenge of the great classical roles.
Still, the moothie! But here she is telling me: ''I've got to learn to
play the harmonica,'' with scarcely a crinkle of amusement round her
hazel eyes.
Soon she's going to pay a visit to a music shop in Stirling where she
will buy a no-nonsense basic mouth organ and a
teach-yourself-the-harmonica primer. If that doesn't work she's got to
find a teacher. Whichever, she's got to be able to get some kind of
wheezing tune out of it in the next two and a half months for a play at
the National Theatre in London.
It won't be, I dare say, a virtuoso rendition, but then it needn't be
a Larry Adler, for the role which calls for this musical contribution is
Mother Courage, the loud-mouthed camp follower and provisioner of the
troops in Brecht's play about survival in savage bygone wars. The
production opens at the National at the end of October.
She is telling me this at the MacRobert Arts Centre, set among the
lakeside lawns of Stirling University campus, where she is soon to
appear, for one night only, in her own theatrical compilation of
theatrical reviews called No Turn Unstoned. This gala evening has been
arranged as a launch-pad for the MacRobert's ambitious autumn season.
There will be some black ties around, but it doesn't sound like a
starched-shirt affair. On the contrary, she says it's going to be fun
and a celebration, and she intends to mingle with the audience before
and after the show, which flouts theatrical convention. ''I very much
believe in mixing. There will be time for a drink and some talk before I
do the show, so the mystique is swept aside.''
Rigg has been chairman (no gesture to feminism here) of the MacRobert
for some years, invited ''out of the blue'' by a previous principal of
the university when she lived in the neighbourhood. At that time she was
still married to local landowner, businessman and former Guards officer
Archie Stirling, and though she divorced him later, she still visits and
retains an interest in the area.
Though this will be her first appearance on the MacRobert stage, she
is an enthusiastic supporter of all its activities.
''I have a passionate interest in the survival of the theatre,'' she
says, ''not only in the capitals and in the centres, but also throughout
the country. So I thought, here's my chance to put my shoulder behind an
arts centre in Scotland.''
Her own tastes chime with the MacRobert's function: ''I go to theatre,
opera, musicals, cinema. All the art forms, as far as I'm concerned, are
part of the whole.''
It was for her services to theatre that she was officially honoured
last year. Diana Rigg is now a dame.
As a girl of 11 she saw her first stage play -- it was a touring
production of Shakespeare's Henry VIII -- and she was so overwhelmed by
the experience that she persuaded her parents to take her to see the
Saturday matinee the following day. From then on her ambition was
settled. Now in her mid-fifties, tall and slim and fair-haired, she is
still devoted to the theatre, though it took second place when her
daughter Rachael was young.
She has also had plenty of experience in film and television. Some
eyebrows were raised when the promising young actress, fresh from a
successful stint with the Royal Shakespeare Company, jumped at the offer
of the leading role alongside Patrick Macnee in The Avengers on TV,
which in those days some people thought was debasing her art.
She had no qualms about it and is blunt about her motives. ''I wanted
the job,'' she says.
If she didn't exactly go in with her eyes closed, she was pretty
unaware of the medium: ''I didn't even possess a television. I'd no idea
what was involved.
''I pitched along with hundreds of other hopefuls and did my test. I
played a scene with Patrick and then I had to do a bit of fighting with
the stunt man. The poor stunt man was black and blue -- he'd been fought
all day by these actresses desperate to get the job.''
Sitting face to face with her, she appears as no shrinking violet, but
not what I'd call a natural born scrapper. ''I don't suppose my fight
scene was very good,'' she confesses, ''but they got better.''
She could have stayed on in the black leather gear, getting Steed out
of fixes with her new-found judo expertise, but after 51 episodes the
novelty had worn off and the formula was beginning to pall.
Week after week the outline was the same: ''Somebody gets killed, Pat
and I find the body, we go in opposite directions to investigate, we
touch base again about halfway through, then we go out again and one
gets into trouble and is rescued by the other. In a nutshell, that's
what happens.''
It wasn't enough. ''I was young and I wanted to learn some more. I
knew I wanted to go back to the theatre.''
Since then she has appeared on stage (in musicals as well as straight
theatre), screen and on the box. Most recently she has appeared on
American television in an adaptation of the Henry James story The Turn
of the Screw, and her last stage role -- as Medea in a new version of
the classical Greek tragedy -- was a huge success both in London and New
York.
She is modest about her films -- a career, she says, ''not glittering
in any respect. Which is partly my fault, because I prefer to work in
the theatre. The human contact with an audience means a lot to me, and I
love the collaborative business of the theatre.''
The trouble is, theatre doesn't pay well enough, and like others in
the business, she finds she has to take work which may not have the same
appeal but which delivers a fatter cheque.
I asked how she saw Diana Rigg in comparison with other leading ladies
of our time. It's not a comparison she was prepared to make, or at least
admit to. ''We've got wonderful actresses -- Maggie (Smith), Vanessa
(Redgrave), Judi (Dench) -- and I think it's entirely for other people
to decide where I am. I'm not in competition. We are completely
different, and I admire their work hugely and I go to see their shows.''
Her performance piece, No Turn Unstoned, emerged from a collection of
theatrical reviews, a selection of critical demolition jobs, which she
had put together as a book. She started off by writing to fellow actors
and actresses asking for their worst reviews, and then dug out some
examples from past history. The proceeds went to a home for elderly
actors and for a children's theatre, which pleased her as a contribution
to both ends of the theatrical spectrum.
The idea of a performance piece came during a spell out of work --
''everyone assumes that if you're famous you don't have periods out of
work. The only thing to do seemed to be something on my own.''
She consulted her friend, the actor Vincent Price, made a lecture out
of the juiciest bits of the book, and took it on the circuit round the
American universities ''who pay very well for out-of-work actresses.
Also I did it to the Library of Congress, which was quite a hair-raising
occasion, at Harvard, and various other places.
''Here I do it for students (for free) and I also do it to raise
money.''
All actors get bad notices from time to time, she says, and it always
hurts. The worst is when the critic gets personal. She remembers her own
anguish when the play Abelard and Heloise transferred to Broadway and
she was on the receiving end of a particularly offensive notice.
In one scene she was required to play nude (''hated doing it, but none
the less'') which elicited the following piece of prose: ''Diana Rigg is
built like a brick basilica with insufficent flying buttresses''.
It's hard to imagine what the man meant. But for a woman not yet 30,
having just had a huge success in the part in the West End, it was a
bitter blow to self-esteem. ''You get the drift,'' she says. ''You're
hurt. A total stranger says something very personal -- how would you
feel?'' She says that No Turn Unstoned has a lot of laughs in it -- but
I suspect a little of that pain may shine through.
* The gala evening with Diana Rigg at the MacRobert Arts Centre,
Stirling, is on Friday, September 8. Tickets at #25 include champagne
reception, performance of No Turn Unstoned, followed by canapes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
