<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000169</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000169</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Boy cleared of hockey assault</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765099</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN WHAT is believed to be the first case of its kind to come before a
Scottish court a Scottish schoolboy international hockey player was
yesterday cleared of severely assaulting a rival player with a hockey
stick during a match.
Steven Vidgen, 16, of Templon Cottages, Cruden Bay, Aberdeenshire, was
found not guilty of assaulting Neil Richardson, 16, on October 8 last
year at the Meadows, Ellon, by striking him on the face with a hockey
stick to his severe injury.
Vidgen was also found not guilty on an alternative charge of culpably,
recklessly swinging a hockey stick in Richardson's direction in such a
manner as to place him in danger of suffering injury, resulting in him
being struck on the face with the hockey stick to his severe injury.
Richardson, of Earlswells Road, Bieldside, Aberdeen, told the trial
that he was a member of the Milltimber Bieldside and Cults Hockey Club
taking part in a ''very aggressive'' league match against Peterhead
Academy with tough tackles and lots of swearing.
He said he was playing as sweeper and had just hit the ball when he
was hit in the face by Vidgen's hockey stick in a swing more associated
with baseball than hockey. He suffered a depressed fractured cheekbone
under his eye, a cracked nose bone and swelling and lacerations.
Richardson claimed he was hit by a wild aggressive swing and denied a
defence suggestion that the incident had been ''an unfortunate
accident'' when Vidgen struck the ball. The court heard that when
charged Vidgen told police: ''I took a swing and mis-hit the ball, the
follow through hit him on the face, he fell to the ground. I walked
forward and said 'Are you all right?' . . . my captain said it was only
an accident.''
Defence agent John McRitchie described the incident as ''an
unfortunate accident'' involving a schoolboy game of hockey.
Returning his verdict Sheriff Alexander Jessop noted there had been
conflicts of evidence from various witnesses involved and said he was
not satisfied the injuries had been deliberate and intentional.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000170</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000170</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fishermen claim Navy mine plans threaten livelihood</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765100</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FISHERMEN in Applecross, Wester Ross, claim their livelihoods are
threatened by a Royal Navy proposal to explode mines in a prime fishing
area.
They are to meet officers of Commodore Clyde in Faslane on Saturday at
the British Underwater Test and Evaluation Centre (Butec) in Kyle of
Lochalsh to discuss the plans for minesweepers to explode 88 kg live
mines within a ''buffer zone'' in the Inner Sound once a month.
Fisherman Alfie Edwards, 40, of Camusterrach, Applecross, says this
area represents the best local fishing ground and that, because fish
take up to three weeks to return after an explosion, the zone will
become a virtual no-go area for the whole year.
He claims the Navy is reneging on a guarantee it made 25 years ago
when the base was set up for no live fire in the buffer zone or outer
sea area which surrounds a restricted six-mile inner sea area for
torpedo testing.
Mr Donald Matheson, vice-chairman of Skye and Lochalsh Fishermen's
Association which represents trawlers and fishing boats, said the
explosions would have a knock-on effect for members if Applecross
fishermen were forced into their fishing zone.
''First trawlers were to be banned from the buffer zone, now there is
going to be this -- they will take over the whole area,'' he said.
Mr Matheson is also concerned about the repercussions the explosions
would have as the last explosion was felt in Gairloch 12 miles away.
''Fair enough once a year, but 12 times a year will have a detrimental
effect on the seabed,'' said Mr Matheson, of Kyle.
Butec commander Tony Grattan-Cooper said that, with the defence cuts,
it was important to keep a level of business going at the range
otherwise the local community would suffer.
He knew of no promise not to use live fire in the buffer zone and
asked how fishermen could know that fish would not reappear soon after
an explosion when there had been no underwater explosions in the area.
However, a spokesman for Commodore Clyde said the meeting was to
formalise the frequency of controlled explosions, ''which we have done
informally on frequent occasions without any objections''.
''We are not doing anything that we have not done in the past,'' he
commented.
''We have used the zone for trials on a regular basis and, while I
don't have figures, it has been fairly habitual over the past three to
four years.''
He added that the meeting would discuss the limits and objections and
explore the best solution to the problem for all parties concerned.
Mr Donald Cameron, 52, of Applecross, who has been fishing the area
for 32 years claimed there had been only one explosion in the Inner
Sound last year when he was given two hours to quit the area and lost a
day's fishing.
''We had a meeting with the commander when we reminded him about the
promise made when the range started, but he said circumstances have
changed,'' said Mr Cameron.
''They always do as they like and now this will become a virtual no-go
area.''
</TEXT>
