<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000171</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000171</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Survey shows decline on terrestrial channels. Stations' watch on TV violence</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765101</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE major broadcasters have pledged to set up a study of TV violence,
despite new figures showing it has declined by almost half on
terrestrial channels.
The BBC and Independent Television Commission will be joined by BSkyB
and the Broadcasting Standards Council in an investigation into how much
violence appears on our screens.
A survey published today by the BBC and ITC showed violence accounts
for 0.61% of the output of BBC1, BBC2, ITV, and Channel 4, compared with
1.1% in 1986.
If satellite TV is included, violence occupies 1.07% of programming
time on all channels.
The study, carried out over the past year by the University of
Sheffield Department of Journalism Studies, was the most comprehensive
ever undertaken in the UK.
Set up in the wake of the murder of James Bulger, it monitored the
four terrestrial channels and most-watched satellite channels -- Sky
One, Sky Movies, the Movie Channel, and UK Gold -- for four separate
week periods over six months.
Broadcasters were not told which weeks those were to be. The study
found:
* Violence occupied 1.07% of programme output time on all channels,
0.61% of terrestrial channels, and 1.53% of satellite channel time.
* Most violence occurred in feature films, 53% of all output. Other
drama accounted for 17% of the total, and home-produced series were less
violent than those bought from abroad.
* Most violence occurred after the evening watershed.
* Just a few programmes contained most of the violence portrayed. That
is, 1% of shows accounted for 19% of all violent acts and 2% of
programmes accounted for 47%.
The new joint study will follow much the same pattern, but will
monitor 28 separate days out of a six-month period.
The BBC and ITC are also carrying out a three-year study on the impact
of television on children.
Heritage Secretary Virginia Bottomley welcomed the newly-launched
study, saying: ''I am pleased that both the BBC and ITC have given this
issue a high priority.
''I applaud their decision to continue to monitor output and to carry
out further research, particularly the impact of television on
children.''
She wanted broadcasters to innovate but also to be responsive to
audience concerns, she said.
BBC chairman Marmaduke Hussey said: ''The BBC governors take policy in
this area very seriously and we believe the BBC's showing in the
monitoring report shows this.''
The subject of violence would be on the agenda at a corporation
seminar on taste and decency in November.
ITC chairman Sir George Russell, representing the ITV companies, said:
''The fall in the total amount of violence on terrestrial channels from
comparable research in 1986 is a move in the right direction.
''However, there is no room for complacency.''
BSkyB defended itself from charges that more violence featured on
satellite channels.
It said the four channels monitored were ''clearly unrepresentative''
of all 26 available, because they featured a high drama content, and 70%
of violence occurred in films or drama.
''Comparisons between thematic satellite channels and generalist
terrestrial channels will remain unrealistic,'' it said.
There were very few complaints to the ITC about violence on satellite
programmes, it added.
Mrs Mary Whitehouse, of the National Viewers' and Listeners'
Association, said: ''Because of technology and special effects, the
effect of violence now is definitely more than it was five or 10 years
ago. We are feeding ourselves with violence as entertainment.''
Labour media spokesman, Mr Graham Allen, said: ''It is encouraging to
see that the proportion of violence on terrestrial television has been
reduced in recent years and I hope that broadcasters and regulators will
keep up the good work.''
Developments in media technology would make regulation increasingly
important, he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000172</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000172</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Highlands temporary classrooms 'falling apart'. Call for action over school building crisis</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765102</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CASH-starved schools in the Highlands are reaching crisis point with
many in an ''intolerable'' state of repair, the chairman of the region's
education committee claimed yesterday.
Councillor Val MacIver wants Scottish Office Ministers to persuade the
Treasury to release extra funds for school upgrading and has invited
Education Minister Raymond Robertson to come and see for himself the
results of chronic Government under-funding.
She has also called on Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth to press
home the message in the annual funding talks with the Treasury. She
said: ''These talks offer the Scottish Office the chance to prove their
commitment to Highland education, which, like other Scottish
authorities, is being starved of money.
''Sound education is significantly diminished when physical
surroundings are grossly inadequate and decaying.''
Three of the area's worst schools are Portree High School, Ullapool
Academy, and Glenurquhart High School, near Drumnadrochit. It will cost
#19m to solve their problems with the construction of new schools to
remove the need for temporary accommodation.
Portree High School has had hundreds of thousands of pounds spent on
repairs but Educational Institute of Sotland officials say there are
still dangers facing pupils.
Ullapool and Glenurquhart's main buildings are surrounded by temporary
classrooms, which are cold in winter and unbearably warm in summer.
Depute director of education with responsibility for buildings, Mr Jim
Stevenson, said: ''Our priority is to get children out of temporary
accommodation and into proper modern buildings. But we don't have enough
money to do it and we need more cash from the Government to solve a
problem which is growing every year.
''This authority had made repeated pleas to Government for extra
funding but so far we have been unsuccessful.''
Mr Stevenson said the problem was inherited from bad planning design
in the sixties.
''We are having to plough money into repairs rather than investing in
new schools,'' he said. ''Over the next four years, we have urgent
projects costing #26m requiring to start. But we will only get around
#9m of Government money.''
The EIS spokesman for Highland region, Mr Stephen Dowds, said: ''There
is the potential for health and safety problems for pupils in some
schools, notably Portree High School. Highland Regional Council don't
have enough money to build new schools or keep up with the growing
number of emergency requests for maintenance work.''
The depute headmaster of Glenurquhart High School, Mr Eddie Broadley,
praised Highland Regional Council's commitment to education in the area
but admitted the authority was fighting a losing battle. He said: 'Our
buildings are falling apart. It's as simple as that.''
Some 85% of Glenurqhart High School's classroom accommodation is
temporary huts and Mr Broadley added: ''Quite apart from the poor state
of repair, we have been trying to teach pupils in temperatures of about
32C this summer. And in winter it can be absolutely freezing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000173</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000173</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Star player flies from US back to Back</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765103</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MYSTERY sponsor flew a local football hero back to the Western Isles
from the United States to play in a league clincher.
When Kevin Murray, 22, from the village of Back in Lewis, got the call
in Maryland last week Hurricane Felix was wreaking havoc.
It had closed his nearest airport at Salisbury.
The Glasgow University engineering graduate, now working on a student
scheme as a waiter in Ocean City, Maryland, dashed 300 miles to
Philadelphia airport.
He then jetted to Glasgow and on to Stornoway to play for Back against
local rivals Point.
But it was all in vain. Point won 1-0 in a hard-fought match.
A disappointed Mr Murray said yesterday: ''The ball just wouldn't go
in.'' A big crowd turned up at the match on Back's home ground on Friday
for his homecoming.
The former islands' under-21 player of the year dismissed the intense
pressure that he must have been under.
He said: ''It was well worth the hours of travelling. It was brilliant
to hear the roar of the Back crowd again.'' The blond striker revealed
it was a sponsor, who does not wish to be named, who stumped up the
hundreds of pounds for him to dash back across the Atlantic.
''I honestly have no idea who it was. I can only guess but I'm not
sure at all,'' he said.
It now needs a miracle for Back to win the local league as leaders
Ness, who have just clinched the Highland Amateur Cup for a record
fourth time, have a huge points lead.
On Thursday Mr Murray will have to fly back to Maryland, where he has
applied for an engineering job.
''But I'll be keeping in touch with the league results back home by
phone,'' he said.
* Mr Murray's father, Murdo, a champion sheepdog handler who won the
Grampian TV Sheepdog Trials screened at the weekend, was a star of the
Back side when they last won the league 20 years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000174</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000174</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scalding inquiry</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765104</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOCIAL work chiefs last night launched an immediate inquiry after a
young girl in foster care suffered scalding after allegedly being left
in a bath with the hot tap running.
Lothian Regional Council officials yesterday said they were ''very
concerned'' about claims in a Sunday newspaper that the youngster had
been left in the hot bath by a foster mother they had appointed.
But they refused to comment further on the allegations, including a
claim that the two-year-old girl, who cannot be named for legal reasons,
was in pain for two days before being taken to hospital.
Last night, the youngster, was being treated at Edinburgh's Sick
Children's Hospital for third degree burns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000175</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000175</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Designs for explosive device 'sent to paper'. Trial told of threat to bomb 'colonists'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765105</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO men alleged to be supporters of the Scottish National Liberation
Army mailed a communique to an Aberdeen newspaper containing detailed
designs for a home-made gas bomb and threatening to attack English
colonists, the High Court in Stirling was told yesterday.
The letter, which the prosecution alleges was sent by Mr Terence
Webber, 30, of Farquhar Road, Aberdeen, and Mr Kevin Paton, 27, of
Charles Gardens, Inverurie, Aberdeenshire, arrived at the Press and
Journal newspaper on March 5, last year.
Assistant news editor John MacDonald said the letter -- postmarked
Perth, Dundee, Angus on the previous day -- claimed to be from an
organisation called Flame, which was described as a paramilitary group
formed to oppose the English colonisation of Scotland.
It threatened to disrupt the lives and property of ''English
colonists'', and warned that estate agents who continued to advertise
Scottish homes for sale outwith Scotland would be targeted.
Mr MacDonald said the letter contained bomb-making instructions which
the organisation said were being circulated to activists throughout
Scotland.
The ''recipe'' for what was described as a home-made explosive device
involved a butane gas cannister and a dustbin full of petrol.
Mr MacDonald said he contacted the police after reading the letter.
Several weeks later, on April 18, Mr MacDonald said he received a
telephone call from someone who said he was representing Flame, passing
on a ''communique'' claiming responsibility for eight ''attacks'' using
inert letter bombs.
It said inert bombs had been mailed to Grampian Regional Councillor
Terry Penny, a man described as ''the colonist Roxborough'', lecturer
Malcolm Dickson at Dundee University, and Persimmon Homes, a company in
York.
The caller added: ''The police will confirm the devices used, only the
explosives were excluded. In future, they will not be excluded.
''We also have firearms and are just about to use them. The people
mentioned here have 30 days to quit Scotland or face death.''
Mr Webber and Mr Paton are accused of making threats and mailing fake
letter bombs in a campaign to force the Government to grant Scotland
independence, and of conspiring between January 1 and September 9, last
year, at Charles Gardens, at Union Grove, Aberdeen, and elsewhere, to
further the purposes of the SNLA and Flame by criminal means.
They are further accused of sending a letter to the Press and Journal
newspaper on March 4, 1994, containing instructions for the manufacture
of an explosive device, and threatening to attack English ''colonists'',
and threats to estate agents not to advertise Scottish homes for sale
outwith Scotland.
The pair are accused of sending letters on April 27, 1994, to the
Labour and Conservative parties, various newspapers, and the Press
Association, containing a threat that Mr Tony Worthington, Labour MP for
Clydebank and Milngavie, would be killed unless he left Scotland within
30 days.
Mr Webber and Mr Paton are charged with posting hoax letter bombs on
April 8, to Malcolm Dickson at Dundee University, Mr Terence Penny at
Grampian Regional Council, Mr Derek Roxborough at the Old Police
Station, Gairloch, Persimmon Homes, of Fulford, York, and Exchange and
Mart magazine in Poole, Dorset.
They are also accused of placing a hoax bomb at Aberdeen Sheriff Court
on September 8.
Both men plead not guilty. Mr Webber has lodged a special defence
claiming that if any of the offences were committed, they were committed
not by him but by Mr Adam Busby, of Upper Gardiner Street, Dublin, and
by Darrin Brown, address unknown.
The court was told by Councillor Penny, 47, a former Scottish Militant
Labour councillor, and Mr Derek Roxborough, 59, a Tynesider who has
lived in Wester Ross for 26 years, that they received Jiffy bags through
the post containing hoax bombs.
Earlier, the court was told that Sun journalist Allan Muir and
photographer Andy Barr met Mr Webber in a Glasgow public house on
February 9, 1994.
The journalist said Mr Webber told him the SNLA wanted Scotland to be
free of the shackles of England, and without the English being here
taking the jobs. He claimed Mr Webber said there could be a campaign of
disruption. He said the interview became ''sticky'' at that point, but
Mr Webber used the phrase ''take up arms''.
The trial, before Lord McCluskey, continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000176</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000176</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Climber's family set for K2 pilgrimage</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765106</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE husband of climber Alison Hargreaves is preparing to visit
Pakistan to see the mountain which claimed her life.
Mr Jim Ballard, speaking at Nevis Range ski centre near the family
home at Spean Bridge, close to Fort William, said he planned to take
their children, Tom, six, and Kate, four, within three weeks.
The weather would dictate how close he would be able to get, but he
hoped to reach the foot of K2, he said.
Ms Hargreaves, 33, the first woman to conquer Everest alone and
without oxygen, died on Sunday last week when she and six others were
caught by bad weather as they descended the 28,250-ft K2.
Mr Ballard said: ''When I get to K2, and when I have said my words to
Alison, and Tom has, and Kate has had a little cry, that will be the
shutting of a chapter. But I suspect it's only the first chapter in the
story of Alison Jane Hargreaves.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000177</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000177</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fish 'cooked alive' as heatwave continues</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765107</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE heatwave is taking its toll of wild salmon and sea trout stocks,
with large numbers of fish dying while trapped in shallow pools baked by
the sun.
Concerned anglers in Renfrewshire have reported several incidents over
the weekend as temperatures soared, with dozens of salmon killed on
stretches of the Black and White Cart rivers.
The fish, victims of thermal stress or oxygen starvation, were unable
to survive the combined effects of low water and hot conditions.
Mr Bill Gibb, secretary of the Abercorn Angling Club, who described
the problem as ''disastrous'', has reported the incidents to the Clyde
River Purification Board.
He said last night: ''It seems the fish have been unable to survive in
these stressful conditions. The temperature of the water in some of the
pools over the weekend was 23 degrees.
''The fish are literally being cooked.
''In the Black Cart, behind the old India Tyres factory at Inchinnan,
the problem has been exacerbated by the rapid growth of weed upstream,
which is blocking the river bed as the water level is so low.
''At low tide, the level in the stretches downstream drops so low that
the fish are trapped in shallow pools. It is tragic.''
Mr Gibb, who fears that without rain thousands of fish may die over
the next few weeks, added: ''We are all extremely concerned that we
could lose all of this year's fish.
''It is a disastrous situation, as both the White and Black Cart
rivers had recovered dramatically in recent times, with both showing
reasonable runs of salmon.''
The area officer for Clyde River Purification Board, Mr Keith
Johnstone, confirmed that water temperatures had been recorded at the 23
degree mark over the weekend, and said inspectors and a biologist were
to carry out an examination of the dead fish to confirm the exact cause.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000178</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000178</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Staff 'should have say in who is boss'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765108</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COMPANY heads should be selected by committee in consultation with
employees, investors, suppliers, and any relevant regulators, and
limited to an eight-year term of office, a leading economist said
yesterday.
The radical proposals, put forward by Professor John Kay, are designed
to improve the system of corporate governance, under fire after a series
of recent scandals, including the collapse of the Maxwell empire, Asil
Nadir's Polly Peck, and the Bank of Credit and Commerce International,
and allegations of boardroom greed in the privatised utilities.
Professor Kay, writing in the National Institute Economic Review,
challenged the widely-held view -- advanced by the recent Greenbury
report into executive pay -- that the best way of improving the way big
companies are run is to develop mechanisms to make them more accountable
to shareholders.
These include an enhanced role for non-executive directors, more
extensive involvement of shareholders in major decisions, and fuller
information about corporate affairs.
Professor Kay, head of the consultancy London Economics, said the idea
that shareholders owned large companies was a myth. Firms like BT and BP
were social institutions, owned by nobody.
Corporate managers were not the agents of the shareholders, many of
whom had little if any interest in monitoring the way a company was run,
he said, but trustees of the businesses' assets.
''Moreover, there are dangers in an attempt to breathe artificial life
into a model of accountability that has little practical reality,'' he
said.
Professor Kay's solution is a new Companies Act with several key
elements.
It would:
* Require all big companies with a widespread shareholding structure
or in a particular area (schools, water supply), as well as very large
private firms with few shareholders, to register as a public limited
company.
* Directors would be under a statutory duty to promote the business of
the company and to balance the claims of investors, customers, suppliers
and employees.
* Boards should be made up of an independent chairman and at least
three independent directors, none of whom should receive ''substantial''
remuneration in either salary of dividends from the company on whose
board he/she sits.
* Chief executives, who should not be chairman as well, should be
selected by a committee, appointed by the independent directors,
comprising independent business and professional advisers in
consultation with employees, investors, and suppliers and any relevant
regulatory agencies.
* The chief executive's appointment should be fixed for four years
with salary and bonuses determined at the beginning of that period.
* Like US Presidents, only one renewal of their contract would be
permitted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000179</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000179</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mental illness in young increases</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765109</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 25% INCREASE in mental illness among young people in Renfrewshire
since 1990 has been attributed to distress caused by bullying, exam
pressure and problems at home.
Based on a three-year study, a report published yesterday by the
Renfrew Association for Mental Health is the first in the UK to question
secondary schoolchildren about their experience and awareness of mental
illness.
Of 1800 questioned, 31% of girls and 15% of boys knew someone who had
been mentally ill, but almost half of all pupils wrongly equated mental
handicap with illness and 87% wrongly understood the nature of
schizophrenia.
Mental illness among the young is often confused with teenage mood
swings, said the report's author, Mr Peter Grafton, who added: ''Society
finds it difficult to accept that the young can become mentally ill in
what is seen as 'the best years of their lives'.''
He said parents should look for sleeplessness, severe appetite loss,
and truancy as indicators that children may be suffering mental illness.
The report calls for a national strategy involving school visits by
mental health professionals and ex-patients and for promotional
campaigns to be mounted in schools, similar to those involving drug
awarenss.
Mr Grafton said that, while school resource packages already were used
in Northern Ireland and were under development in England and Wales,
there was no corresponding provision in Scotland.
The survey was launched yesterday at the Out of Sight, Out of Mind
mental health exhibition at Kelvingrove Art Gallery, Glasgow, which has
attracted more than 500,000 visitors since its launch in February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000180</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000180</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Red Star row</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765110</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LEAKED document shows British Rail will have to pay the management
of Red Star to take over the parcels business when it is privatised,
Labour claimed today.
Shadow Transport Secretary Michael Meacher said managers planning to
buy the business had bid a nominal sum, thought to be #1, for the
loss-making organisation but would receive a first-year rent subsidy
from BR worth #1.5m.
In addition, BR could be left with a redundancy bill of up to #7m for
700 Red Star staff, he claimed.
Mr Meacher said a confidential ''information memorandum'' from Red
Star on the sale showed ''a business being savagely cut ready for
privatisation''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000181</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000181</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Eagle set to swoop on drugs problem</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765111</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE in Strathclyde yesterday presented Scotland's most majestic
bird of prey to highlight the latest stage in its drugs initiative,
Operation Eagle.
Annie, an 18-year-old golden eagle, helped to launch a campaign
involving the force and Safe Greater Easterhouse which will see the
area's 16,500 households receiving a drugs identification guide.
The guides, which will be delivered over the next two weeks in the
Glasgow estate, aim to:
* Provide education and raise awarness of Operation Eagle;
* Highlight the national drugs helpline number, 0800 77 66 00, which
provides assistance, encouragement, and harm reduction for drug users.
* Highlight the local number, 0141 771 3456, where information on
drugs dealers can be left in confidence.
Assistant chief constable Crispian Strachan yesterday stood nervously
as the bird was placed on his arm at the Shandwick Shopping Centre in
Easterhouse.
After his brief encounter he said he believed the protected bird,
which is kept in captivity by Clyde Valley Hawks in Crossford,
Lanarkshire, provided an active image for use in the campaign, pointing
out that the purpose of the anti-drugs drive was contained in the
acronym: eagle -- education, awareness, guidance, legislation, and
enforcement.
Mr Strachan rejected a suggestion the problem of drugs was more
serious in Easterhouse than other areas of Strathclyde.
''I would hesitate to say that anyone here has any worse problems. It
is individual choice very much with drugs.''
He said he had been greatly encouraged by the surrender of drugs at
police stations since the force introduced its amnesty last week.
This involves 79 stations binning then burning prescribed tablets and
capsules brought in by the public on a no-questions-asked basis.
He said: ''Some of the bins at the stations are absolutely full. We
are doing what we wanted to -- getting in any and every drug just to
take them out of circulation and take them away from people.''
The enforcement phase of the campaign, which has already resulted in
more than 2000 arrests including almost 800 dealers since June 1, begins
in earnest on September 1 and will run for three months.
Asked how many arrests could be anticipated by the end of the
campaign, Mr Strachan replied: ''Numbers are not the be all and end all.
What matters is taking drugs out of circulation, stopping dealers, and
stopping young people from falling into the trap of using drugs.
''If we could do it with six arrests we would. If it takes 6000
arrests we will do it.''
Mrs May McLeish, chairperson of the Safe Greater Easterhouse Project,
said locals were becoming increasingly concerned about drug abuse and
dealing. She said the effort to combat drugs would have the full support
of the community.
</TEXT>
