<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000182</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000182</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Government health warning</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765112</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is a classic case of physician heal thyself -- the physician in
this case being the Government which for 16 years has lost no
opportunity to hector us on healthy living.
Who can forget the advice of the former Junior Health Minister Edwina
Currie about the dangers of black pudding and chips and going to work on
an egg? Most famously she told businessmen travelling abroad the best
way to avoid catching Aids was to take the wife.
However, while such prescriptions are flying about it appears the body
politic itself is none too healthy.
According to figures released yesterday by Labour, it appears civil
servants in Whitehall top the league for days lost through sickness.
And, yes, the worst for sick leave appears to be the Department of
Health, where 69,363 days were lost last year, amounting to 6.2% of the
total number of working days.
The Government claims it cannot estimate the cost to the taxpayer of
more than 3.5 million lost working days -- a rate of absence
outstripping public and private sector averages.
The huge Department of Social Security alone accounted for almost a
third of all days lost in central Government.
The Confederation of British Industry said absence for sickness ran
nationally at 3.4% of total working time last year, which breaks down
into 9.7 days a person in the public sector and 6.9 in the private.
An analysis of figures released by Labour and gathered from Government
departments showed the average in 11 leading Whitehall ministries was
closer to 10.6 days.
Labour also claimed not a single department was able to provide the
cost of sickness absence.
A spokesman for the Health Department explained its figures did not
take into account time taken off in bank holidays by its 7500 staff, and
said they could be further skewed by time lost through preparations for
a far-reaching redundancy programme announced last autumn.
</TEXT>
