<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000183</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000183</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Call for 'suicide free' cells</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765113</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHERIFF yesterday called for prison cells to be made suicide free
following the deaths of three inmates at Barlinnie Prison.
John Grant, 50, and William Hallford, 43, hanged themselves from
ceiling light fittings, and Alan Scott, 23, from a bar on a window. All
used bed sheets.
The recommendation follows a nine-day fatal accident inquiry at
Glasgow Sheriff Court into the three deaths within a four-week period
last summer.
Sheriff Eric Galt returned formal verdicts on the three deaths. He
said the message of the inquiry was that cells must be provided where
suspension points were not available.
''This would at least reduce and hopefully, in time, eliminate deaths
by hanging,'' the sheriff added.
Grant, of Spey Court, Grangemouth was serving three years for wilful
fire-raising, and Mr Scott, of Carmuirs Avenue, Camelon, Falkirk, was on
remand facing a charge of rape.
Mr Hallford, of Birrens Road, Motherwell was on remand on charges of
robbery, drugs, and firearms.
Sheriff Galt found that, in the cases of Grant and Mr Scott, a failure
to observe them was due to a defect in the system of passing information
from the prison hospital to the halls.
Medical staff had put them on the ''ordinary observation'' category,
which meant they should have been looked at least once every hour.
This had not been done and the system had since been changed.
The sheriff found that Mr Hallford died in the Royal Infirmary on June
28 last year from heart failure and brain damage, eight days after being
found hanging in his cell.
He had been under ordinary observation and was found hanging from a
light fitting after a prison officers' tea-break.
Sheriff Galt said the furthest he could go regarding defects in the
system was to say that it raised ''at least a possibility that it
contributed to the deaths of John Grant and Alan Scott''.
</TEXT>
