<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000184</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000184</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Barrymore and wife separate after 18 years</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765114</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COMEDIAN Michael Barrymore last night admitted that he had separated
from his wife of 18 years.
A statement issued through his solicitor said: ''Michael and Cheryl
wish it to be known that they are presently separated and leading their
own personal lives. Cheryl will continue to act as Michael's manager and
continue to give Michael her full support in his career.''
The statement ended months of speculation about the marriage of the
television entertainer, who has been dogged by drink problems and
allegations that he had gay affairs.
Last night, Barrymore said nothing as he left his #750,000 Stanhope
Terrace home in London's Lancaster Gate to get into a chaffeur-driven
Volvo.
The comedian's health has been a problem for some years. He suffered
weight loss and spent time in an exclusive Baltimore clinic last year
when he admitted he was an alcoholic.
His wife has always been supportive and was by his side two weeks ago
as he auditioned members of the public for his new ITV show, My Kind of
People, at a shopping centre in Croydon. They had just returned from a
weekend break in Cannes where they tried to patch up their differences.
Barrymore gave her a kiss to cheers from thousands after singing:
''Smile though you heart is breaking.''
To add to the pressures on the star, there have been allegations that
his friends and relatives have been featured on his TV game shows.
Barrymore, 43, allegedly confessed to being homosexual in front of an
audience of more than 200 gay men in an East End pub after being
introduced by a drag act.
According to reports, he sang a saucy version of the Frank Sinatra
song, New York, New York, featuring the words: ''Start spreading the
news, I'm gay today.''
He was later pictured in an argument with a photographer outside the
White Swan pub.
His 44-year-old wife masterminded his career from being an
end-of-the-pier, bottom-of- the-bill comic to the millionaire star of
shows such as Strike It Lucky and Barrymore.
He headlined at the Royal Variety Performance two years ago when he
cuddled an Army sergeant-major and sang Will You Still Love Me Tomorrow
to loud applause.
One friend said last night: ''Michael's fans have been amazingly loyal
and he has had so many letters of support but it has been a great
strain. It is a great tribute to his professionalism that he has managed
to make the new show while going through all this pain in the
background.''
Mrs Barrymore, who is staying in an apartment attached to the
Athanaeum hotel where a double room costs #190 a night, refused to speak
about the state of her marriage. The couple have no children.
It had been claimed that Barrymore threw his wedding ring off at the
White Swan pub and invited customers back to his house for a party. His
brother, Mr John Parker, said nothing Barrymore had done would lead him
to think he was gay.
</TEXT>
