<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000185</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000185</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Group consulted on bus safety</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765115</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE South Lanarkshire unitary council has offered the Belt Up School
Kids (Busk) campaign the chance to shape road safety measures, including
school bus contracts.
The offer was made yesterday at a meeting between the new authority
and the Carnwath-Biggar branch of Busk, which was set up as a national
organisation just over two years ago, after a series of minibus and
coach accidents claimed the lives of 16 children.
The Carnwath-Biggar branch was formed after the Biggar bus crash, in
which two schoolboys died last February.
Busk had asked to meet council leader Tom McCabe to discuss plans for
school transport safety when the new council takes control next April.
After the meeting, Busk secretary Helen Mackenzie said it had been its
most constructive talks with either national or local government.
She said South Lanarkshire's offer to become involved in the planning
of school bus routes and pick-up points ''was the best news we have had
in two years''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000186</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000186</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Five die at hands of the 'engineer'. Hamas vows to wreck talks with more bombs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765116</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Israel-PLO talks were suspended last night after a suicide bomber
from the Islamic Hamas movement killed five people and wounded 100 in a
morning rush-hour bus attack in Jerusalem.
Hamas's military wing said in a statement signed by ''the students of
the engineer, Yahya Ayyash'' it also vowed to carry out more attacks to
derail the Israeli-PLO peace process.
Ayyash, known as the engineer, is top of the Israeli army's wanted
list. He is believed to have made or trained the makers of many of the
Hamas bombs.
Despite the blast, and threat, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said the
talks would be suspended ''for a few days'' but this would not affect
the timetable for reaching an agreement. PLO chief Yasser Arafat
denounced the bombing and called Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin to express
his condolences.
Both sides said they were determined to sign an agreement on extending
Palestinian self-rule to the West Bank on schedule in Washington next
month.
US officials said one of the dead was an American woman, Joan
Devanney. The bomber was also believed among the dead.
There were two unidentified bodies, one a woman.
The Jerusalem police chief said the condition of the woman's body
suggested she could have been holding a bomb. However, the Hamas
statement referred to the bomber as a man.
Thousands of right-wing Israelis and Jewish settlers demonstrated
throughout Israel and at the scene of the blast. Some were arrested as
they tried to block traffic.
Mr Rabin sealed Israel's border with the occupied West Bank after the
explosion.
The bomb exploded in the back of one bus as it passed another. The
explosion set fire to the second bus and blew out its windows.
Passengers on both buses were among the wounded.
Most of the passengers were students. Some were foreign students
attending summer Hebrew language classes.
UN Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali and US President Bill
Clinton condemned the attack, and Mr Clinton promised that ''these
enemies of peace will not succeed''.
</TEXT>
