<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000187</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000187</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Minister condemns sectarian attacks</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765117</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SECTARIAN arson attacks on Catholic and Protestant churches and
loyalist Orange Halls and the petrol bombing of private homes in
Northern Ireland were strongly condemned yesterday by the Government.
Security Minister Sir John Wheeler said that the attacks damaged
everyone who had been enjoying the initial fruits of peace.
They took the province ''back towards days we hoped we had left
behind,'' he said, adding that inflaming sectarian tensions jeopardised
the peace.
''Why are some people putting that at risk by their actions? Northern
Ireland, disfigured by sectarian attacks, can never be a stable society
at peace with itself.''
He challenged those who had influence to ''put an end to this risk to
peace''.
The Minister spoke out after three Catholic churches and a Baptist
church were damaged in arson attacks.
At the same time, an 80-year-old man was in hospital after petrol bomb
attacks on three houses in an east Belfast terrace and another on a
house in Lisburn, County Antrim.
The son of the elderly Catholic man said he believed the attack on his
father was a reprisal for the extensive damage caused to the Baptist
church a few hours earlier.
Mr Gerry Adams, the Sinn Fein President, called for a halt to the
attacks, saying that the irresponsible and unnecessary behaviour added
to the fears and tensions which already existed.
Meanwhile, Mr Adams was yesterday snubbed by the Orange Order after
seeking a meeting to discuss the attacks which have seen some 30 Orange
Halls damaged by Republicans in recent weeks and other reprisal attacks.
It was revealed that Mr Adams had twice written to the Rev Martin
Smyth, the Orange Order leader and South Belfast Ulster Unionist MP
seeking talks about the attacks.
Mr Smyth wrote back yesterday refusing to meet Mr Adams and accusing
Sinn Fein of stirring up sectarian tensions. He told Mr Adams he had
failed to use his position to influence those responsible for attacks on
Orange Halls.
A meeting would be possible only ''if you turn from using violence as
a political weapon,'' he wrote.
</TEXT>
