<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000188</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000188</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Murder trial told of blood trail at flats</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765118</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORENSIC scientist described to a court yesterday a trail of blood
where a woman was found shot dead.
Mr Alastair Burt, 35, told the High Court in Glasgow that Ms Sally
Cannon, 20, of Kelburn Terrace, Port Glasgow, had been shot in the mouth
and twice in the head.
Mr John Hemphill, 30, her boyfriend, denies shooting her and murdering
her. Mr Hemphill claims alibi.
He further denies being concerned in the supply of heroin and cannabis
resin between August 1992, and April last.
Police Constable Cameron Baillie, 27, told the court he found Mr
Hemphill at a car park with blood on his face, hands and jeans and that
he became emotional and asked: ''What kind of beast would do that?''
The policeman said Mr Hemphill told him he had left Ms Cannon in their
home on Saturday afternoon, April 22. He found her early on the Sunday
morning on the first floor landing.
Constable Baillie said Mr Hemphill told him she had been ''calling at
doors for help''.
Mr Burt told Mrs Fiona Reith, prosecuting, he went to the scene early
on April 23 and found blood on the stairs. There was heavy blood
staining on the carpet in Ms Cannon's ground flat house and a finger
print in a blood stain low down on a wall.
Mr Burt said it was the deceased's fingerprint and had probably
happened when she was scrambling about on the floor after being shot in
the mouth.
The forensic scientist then told of blood staining going all way to
the top flat and then heavier staining when she had come down to the
first floor landing.
Mr Burt said she had probably been ''down'' when she was shot twice on
the head behind the right ear.
He said he later examined a jacket and jeans belonging to the accused
and found stains of blood which could have come from the deceased.
Mr Burt agreed smears of blood could have been caused when the accused
held the dying woman in his arms, but in his opinion droplets on the
jacket and jeans had happened at the time she was shot.
He said: ''You require energy to break up blood.'' And he added the
force of the bullets striking the girl would propel the blood in
droplets.
Asked by Mr Donald Findlay, QC, defending, if all the spots on the
jacket and jeans were caused the same way, Mr Burt replied: ''I could
not tell.''
Mr Findlay suggested that the spots could have come from a last
violent attempt by Ms Cannon to clear her airway and asked: ''Did the
spots result from a gunshot?'' Mr Burt said: ''I could not say for
certain.''
Re-examined by Mrs Reith he said: ''It was likely they were.''
Acting sergeant Ronald Withers, 50, of the police firearms section,
said he was given three bullets after a post-mortem examination on the
woman. He described them as .38 lead bullets and all had been fired from
the same gun.
Mr Withers said the gun used had not been found but in his opinion it
was an Enfield revolver of the type issued during the Second World War.
He said this type of gun was often used in target practice.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000189</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000189</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pride and grief of pilot's family. Dead soldier's father tells of two telephone calls that brought first joy and then agony.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765119</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE distraught father of the pilot of an Army Lynx helicopter who died
along with three other British soldiers when it crashed into the
Adriatic Sea off Croatia said yesterday that his family had always
feared such a tragedy might occur but were still ''utterly devastated''.
Corporal Pilot Ian Macdonald, 29, whose parents live at Appin in
Argyll, was named as one of the victims when the helicopter from 3
Regiment Army Air Corps ditched into the sea on a regular training
flight on Sunday.
Yesterday his parents, retired Metropolitan policeman Derek Macdonald,
58, and his wife Josephine, 53, were being comforted by relatives and
friends at their home overlooking Shuna Island, Loch Linnhe, after
learning of their son's death from his 30-year-old widow.
Speaking as arrangements were being made to bring home the bodies of
the dead soldiers, Mr Macdonald told how two telephone calls within
weeks of each other brought great pride and grief to his family.
One was to say their son had at last been awarded his sergeant's
stripe; the other meant he would never wear it. He had received his
navigator's ring five years ago and his pilot's two years later.
Mr MacDonald said: ''He got the award for being the most improved
pilot on the course, near Andover, and we were told just recently he was
to be made up to sergeant. We were very proud but now we will never see
it.''
He added: ''I think obviously all parents, when their sons are in an
active duty environment like Northern Ireland and Bosnia, fear the worst
but we are still utterly devastated and very distraught by the news.''
Ian Macdonald had been married for five years. He met his wife,
Jeanette, in 1987 when she was a civilian clerk to the forces in
Germany. The couple had no children and lived in quarters in Gutersloh,
Germany.
Mr MacDonald said: ''When she phoned to tell us what had happened, she
was beside herself with grief. We are assuming she will return to
England to her parents' home in West London.
''We know no more about the crash than we have heard on television or
read in the papers. An officer came to see us, but he couldn't tell us
much though the indications are that Ian was flying the helicopter
though there was a more senior pilot on board.''
0 Ian Macdonald had wanted to be a soldier ''since he knew such things
existed'', according to his father, and became a junior leader in the
Army Air Corps at 16.
He went into the regulars at 18 and had completed seven years in
Germany and nearly three in Northern Ireland.
He was also in the Falklands and took part in Nato exercises
throughout the world before his secondment to the British contingent of
the multi-national Rapid Reaction Force.
He was an all-round sportsman and proficient in squash and ski-ing to
Army instructor standard.
The family's other son, Douglas, 31, who is in the Metropolitan Police
in London, was yesterday travelling north to be with his parents and the
local Church of Scotland minister, the Rev Douglas Robertson, was
planning to visit them last night.
Mr Robertson, of Appin Parish Church, said yesterday: ''This is a
small community which has been saddened by several fatal accidents in
recent years and I know there will be a lot of concern and support for
the family.''
The father of one of the other victims of the crash, Air Trooper Roger
Willingale of 7 Regt, Army Air Corps, said yesterday that he had ''got
his wings'' just weeks before he died and had ''the heart of a lion''.
His son had done two tours of duty in Northern Ireland and one in
Canada, which finished just before the regiment was posted to Croatia.
''He had seen his fair share of action,'' his father said.
The other casualties were Sergeant Martin Charles Osbourne, 30, of
Wattisham, Suffolk, and 20-year-old Air Trooper Graham Shane
Witherstone, from Scunthorpe.
The sole survivor of the crash was Air Trooper Ian Brain, 21, from
Loughborough, who was with 3 Regt Army Air Corps, said Major Gerry
Bartlett of 24 Air Mobile Brigade, based in Ploce, Croatia.
It was believed the bodies of the four soldiers, retrieved from the
sea on Sunday and taken to Ploce, would be flown home next week to RAF
Brize Norton in Oxfordshire, said Major Bartlett.
A spokesman for the brigade at its base in Colchester said it was
''pretty shocked'' by Sunday's accident, which happened five miles off
the Croatian coast.
It would ''continue as normal'' despite its first losses since the
brigade deployed in Croatia a month ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000190</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000190</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unionscall onForsythto listen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH, JONATHAN NORTHCROFT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765120</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish economy is suffering ''deep structural problems'' caused
by a dependency on electronics, chemicals, and whisky exports, the
Scottish TUC is to tell Scottish Secretary Mr Michael Forsyth when they
meet on Thursday.
The STUC will challenge Mr Forsyth to show he is a listening Minister
by adopting policies to help industries outside the core sectors which
it warns are still in recession.
This would include setting up a Scottish Investment Bank, giving full
support to blocks on further interest rates rises, and arguing against
an imposed incomes policy for public sector workers.
Mr Forsyth will also be urged to drop plans to take water services out
of local authority control. The STUC concedes it would be a bold move,
but believes that this one act alone would make a tremendous difference
to the Government's standing in Scotland.
The meeting will be the first between the executive of the STUC and Mr
Forsyth since he was appointed. Union leaders are keen to discover
whether Mr Forsyth is willing to listen to, and act upon, other points
of view, rather than simply following his own agenda irrespective of
whether it has public support or not.
Mr Campbell Christie, the STUC general secretary, concedes there are
issues where the STUC's approach will be at odds with Mr Forsyth's, but
he hopes to find some areas of agreement -- such as the need to reverse
the growth of local quangos in Scotland.
''Much has been made of the contrasting style of Michael Forsyth and
his predecessor, but the real test will be if there is a contrast in
substance.''
An STUC paper, to be presented to Mr Forsyth on Thursday details union
officials' concerns over the Scottish economy. It states that although
current economic performance appears relatively healthy, this position
is reliant on large electronic and chemical industries and that any
growth has been ''jobless''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950822-000191</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950822-000191</DOCID>
<DATE>950822</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Yard set for extra submarine work. Rosyth finds silver lining in loss of refit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES MCKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765121</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE refit of the Type 42 missile destroyer HMS Glasgow, which was
intended to be carried out at Rosyth as part of the core programme of
surface ship work to compensate for the loss of Trident submarines, is
now certain to go to arch-rivals DML in Devonport.
However, the decision is good news for Scotland. It now makes it
certain that Rosyth dockyard is set to win contracts for two additional
nuclear submarine refits.
Under the Government's original proposals, all nuclear submarines were
to go to Devonport after 1997. However, serious nuclear safety problems
there have made a nonsense of the programme.
In the meantime, the Babcock management would rather win two submarine
refits at the expense of a Type 42.
If this is good news for Rosyth, conversely it is disastrous for
Devonport. There is no doubt the yard is in a desperate situation.
HMS Glasgow, currently in the Adriatic on operation Sharp Guard duties
off the coast of former Yugoslavia, is not due for refit until next
year.
However, the ship's company already has been told that, despite the
original plan, it was now almost certain that the refit would be carried
out at Devonport.
Two of the Glasgow's sister ships -- Edinburgh and Newcastle -- are
being refitted at Rosyth as part of the core programme.
A Ministry of Defence official said yesterday that the final decision
had yet to be taken over the Glasgow. However, it was true that the
ship's company had been given an early warning of a likely change in
plans.
There were two reasons, he said.
The first was that the refit for each of the Navy's hunter-killer
S-class nuclear submarines had been extended from 80 to 95 weeks.
As two of these boats -- Sovereign and Superb -- were currently under
refit at Rosyth -- that meant the Scottish yard now had 30 additional
weeks of work.
A second reason concerned the report currently being finalised on
nuclear safety at the yards.
This report is likely to be published soon after MPs return to the
House of Commons after the summer recess. This in turn will allow an
announcement to be made that Rosyth has been awarded additional
submarine refit contracts.
A Babcock spokesman confirmed yesterday that additional submarine work
being awarded to the yard meant it would be unable to complete the refit
of HMS Glasgow on the time scale required by the Navy.
Nuclear safety concerns at the Devonport yard had already led to hints
from Mr Roger Freeman, when Minister for Procurement at the MoD, that
nuclear submarine refits would have to continue at Rosyth beyond the
previously planned date for the switch to Devonport.
Neverthless, the MoD has steadfastly refused to confirm reports in The
Herald in May that Rosyth would win at least two additional submarine
contracts.
Even yesterday officials would not admit that Rosyth had won the
additional submarine orders. However, a source admitted last night that
all that was waiting was a formal announcement.
Within months of the promise of the core programme of surface ship
refits for Rosyth, a spokesman for the Scottish Office said on behalf of
Mr Ian Lang, then Scottish Secretary, that the MoD had made it clear
that ''the allocated programme for work is a very clear and unequivical
commitment by the Government to Rosyth''.
If that was true for Rosyth, then promises made to Devonport over
submarines were also being seen by the Government as a firm commitment.
However, yesterday an official at the MoD said: ''What was said in
1993 was not meant to be read as the likely end result. I don't think
people took it as carte blanche. Clearly things were likely to change.''
It was not the impression given at the time.
During a visit to Scotland, Mr Freeman said: ''We are going to start a
process of discussing with Babcock whether they can take some more SSN
refits beyond 1997.''
He then conceded that while Rosyth would welcome additional work, he
was aware the management would not see the programme of refitting
surface work jeopardised in any way.
That might have been the company's view then. However, it was obvious
last night that events had moved on. As far as the company was
concerned, two firm submarine orders were more than compensation.
It is obvious that the nuclear safety problems at Devonport are worse
than originally anticipated. However, last night the MoD remained
adamant that the yard still would refit Trident submarines.
</TEXT>
