<HEADLINE>Absence makes the Festival pay</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765122</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORE and more Edinburgh home-owners are cashing in on the Festival by
renting out their homes and heading off on holiday.
Letting agents said yesterday that increasing numbers of residents
were escaping the city's crowded streets, pubs and restaurants by
leasing out their homes during the three-week event.
Mackay's Property Agency, one of the biggest leasing agents in
Edinburgh and the Lothians, said that about 20% of the property it
handled at this time of year was for the Festival.
General manager Ms Patricia Balharrie said the average rental ranged
from between #400 and #1200. However, even luxury accommodation, costing
thousands of pounds each week, has been snapped up by Festival visitors.
Chestnut House, at Melville Castle, Midlothian, which had a weekly
rental of #3000 during the Festival, was one of the first to be leased,
said Ms Balharrie. The property, which includes its own swimming pool,
sleeps between 10 and 12.
Ms Balharrie said: ''We do advertise for properties for the Festival,
but quite a number of people actually come to us, having been suggested
by word of mouth.''
Leasing agents believe many residents use the opportunity to take a
break -- paid for by letting out their homes.
Ms Balharrie added diplomatically: ''I do think Edinburgh residents
participate quite extensively in the Festival. There are many who would
be taking a summer holiday anyway. No doubt their holiday is paid for by
leasing their homes.''
* Comedy acts on the Fringe said yesterday they planned to disrupt the
Perrier awards, after claiming they had been barred from taking part.
Groups from Chicago claimed they had been banned from the annual
awards, made to the best comedy acts on the Fringe, because their
improvised shows were ''unscripted''.
Talks are now taking place between a number of Fringe acts and the
soft drinks company, Fruitopia, over the possibility of setting up rival
awards. Final approval for the move has still to be given by Fruitopia's
parent company.
A dozen companies from Chicago are taking part in the comedy aspect of
the Edinburgh Fringe, under the Chicago Mafia banner, with many of the
shows heavily improvised.
Mr Kevin Mullaney, producer of one of the shows, Harold on the
Hollyrood, said: ''Apparently Perrier believe that improvisation is
somehow inferior to scripted comedy. If our show is inferior, then why
not simply consider us and not give us the award?''
He said a ''peaceful protest'' was planned by improvisers from around
the world at the Perrier ceremony this week.
The French mineral water company later denied the groups had been
barred from the awards.
Perrier spokeswoman Ms Mica Burns said: ''The Perrier awards are so
highly regarded they are now treated as a benchmark by the public when
they want to see comedy acts, and when improvisation is involved it can
be good, or not so good. There is no guarantee of quality.
''We work very hard to make sure that everyone who can possibly be
included is eligible.''
</TEXT>
