<HEADLINE>Strathclyde boost as curbs spread. Scottish water in pipeline for Spain</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACCALMAN, KEITH SINCLAIR, DUNCAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765123</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS hundreds of thousands of Scottish consumers begin to be affected by
hosepipe bans, Strathclyde is getting ready to export between 15 and 20
million gallons of water a week to Spain.
The region has been in negotiations with an international shipping
company to transport excess capacity from Loch Katrine to Majorca and
the southern mainland.
Strathclyde's acting director of water, Mr Donald Davidson, yesterday
disclosed that negotiations on exporting water to Spain had been in
progress for many months, long before the current hot weather. No deal
has yet been struck.
Despite the hot spell, there is still plenty of spare capacity in Loch
Katrine, currently 20 million gallons a day.
It is actually easier to ship the water to Spain than to supply other
areas of Scotland or England that are suffering shortages. This is due
to the absence of a pipe network to take the water, for example, to
Fife, while there is one to the Glasgow docks where it formerly supplied
the yards and foreign ships.
Mr Davidson explained: ''We have spare capacity in the Katrine system
and we have the infrastructure available. The trunk main goes down to
the dockside where it would be loaded on to tankers. These would carry
the water into the firth and then load it on to a much bigger vessel
further west.''
The move was revealed as the Government was coming under attack for
controversial new plans for saving water in England and Wales where the
supply is in the hands of private companies. Measures being considered
by Environment Secretary John Gummer include urging the water companies
to press ahead with metering.
The chairman of the new water watchdog body in Scotland, former Labour
MP Dick Douglas who is now prominent in the SNP, last night made it
clear that any attempt by the Scottish water authorities to introduce
similar measures would face close scrutiny from him. Three new public
boards will take over water and sewerage services from regional councils
in April next year.
Meanwhile, Strathclyde water levels are holding up well and there is
still no prospect of a hosepipe ban in the region.
At the end of last week, levels in the three main reservoirs serving
Strathclyde were:
* Loch Katrine (Greater Glasgow's main supply) -- 103 days;
* Loch Bradan (Ayrshire's main supply) -- 85 days;
* Daer Reservoir (Lanarkshire's main supply) -- 84 days.
However, the use of hosepipes is to be banned in more parts of
Scotland.
Fife became the first regional council to impose a hosepipe ban
throughout its area, which covers 150,000 homes; a ban in parts of
Highland region is to be extended; and Dumfries and Galloway is to
introduce a ban unless there is a dramatic change in the weather.
Fife Regional Council said the move was necessary because consumption
was still running at 10% above normal, despite an appeal to the public
to use water sparingly. It had left the region's reservoirs at 42.6% of
capacity.
Residents caught breaching the ban could be liable to a fine of up to
#1000.
Although it applies only to domestic hoses and sprinklers, with
businesses not affected, the council's engineering services committee
chairman, Councillor Bert Turpie appealed to all industrial consumers to
cut back on consumption and waste wherever possible.
The council also revealed although it is spending #2m a year replacing
water mains, 25% of supplies still leaks away. But half of the loss is
not within the council's control as it happens on consumers' premises.
Strathclyde's Mr Davidson said that the country's largest region also
lost an average of about 25% of supplies through leakage, but stressed
that this did not cost the council much because Strathclyde has a very
cheap supply of water.
''We do search for leakage in particular areas but we balance what it
costs to find with the volumes we have. Obviously, if we were short of
supplies we would increase our efforts to make sure we weren't losing
water.''
A spokesman for Highland Regional Council said: ''In principle, the
argument is that in Scotland we are so well resourced that it is very
rare that we would ever get excited about leakages. But every authority
checks for leakages and takes them seriously because of the consequences
of damage to other people's property from water escaping.''
Highland region, which imposed a ban on the use of hosepipes and
sprinklers in the Dingwall and Black Isle areas last Tuesday, yesterday
decided to extend the ban to the Strathspey area, which includes
Grantown-on-Spey, Aviemore, Newtonmore, and Kingussie.
The council said the action was necessary because outflow from the
local source of water, Loch Einich above Glenmore Lodge in the
Cairngorms, was depleted because of what the council takes from the
loch.
Dumfries and Galloway Regional Council also decided at a special
meeting to impose a ban on the use of hosepipes from next Wednesday
unless there is a significant break in the weather or a change in
demand.
Water manager Donald Darrant said: ''Reservoirs are not yet at a
critical level but because of the increased demand we are having
problems with treating the supply and getting it into the mains network.
It looks as if the only way to cope with the situation will be to impose
the hosepipe ban. There will be no exemptions and it will be
region-wide.''
Mr Darrant said demand had increased by between 30% and 40%, due
mainly to increased agricultural and domestic use.
So far Scotland has escaped the worst of the drought, with only small
and localised problems. In some areas, officials say the problem is not
a shortage of supplies but sheer pressure of demand, with people wanting
to use water faster than supplies can be treated.
Meanwhile, Mr Gummer came under fire over controversial new plans for
saving water. Opposition parties, consumer groups and water companies
all attacked the Environment Department's Water Conservation: Government
Action report.
Mr Gummer is considering prescribing a maximum flow rate for showers
and pondering the wider use of toilets that use less water. He is also
urging water companies to press ahead with metering.
Labour said the Government was failing to make water companies tackle
the problem of leaking pipes, the Liberal Democrats said the report was
a ''mind-boggling example of ministerial buck-passing'' and the
Consumers' Association said the public was being burdened with an unfair
share of responsibility.
The water companies said the report lacked any long-term conservation
plan and put too much emphasis on metering.
Mr Gummer defended the report, which has taken three years to produce,
insisting ''sustainable use of water required action by everyone''.
Shadow Environment Secretary Frank Dobson said 80% of wasted water
leaked from company-owned pipes.
''This 71-paragraph document devotes 56 paragraphs to talking about
customers saving water and it devotes just nine paragraphs to talking
about leakages from company pipes,'' he said.
''And at the end of those nine paragraphs it says the Government won't
intervene, won't set the company's targets, it will leave everything to
their judgment.''
Mr Dobson said he was opposed to compulsory metering, adding: ''I
think it's quite unnecessary and it's vastly expensive.''
Liberal Democrat MP Paul Tyler, secretary of the Commons' all-party
water group, said attempts to pin the blame on consumers were adding
insult to injury given the problems people were facing during the
current drought.
''The statement from the Department of the Environment this morning is
a mind-boggling example of ministerial buck-passing,'' he said.
''For 25 years some of us have been urging that priority should be
given to supply leakage rather than hoping that domestic meters would
solve the problem. Clearly, that is where the biggest savings can be
made.
''Is John Selwyn Gummer really as complacent about this as he sounds?
He sounds as if he is trying to wash his hands of the whole debacle.''
The director of the National Consumer Council, Ms Ruth Evans, said:
''Leakage control is a sensible way to spend consumers' money to save
water. Introducing widespread metering is expensive to instal and
maintain. Metering brings with it hardship, especially for large
families and those with particular medical conditions requiring large
quantities of water.''
However, industry regulator the Office of Water Services (Ofwat)
welcomed the report, saying it contained a ''useful framework''.
Ofwat was pleased by the report's endorsement for metering, saying it
would ensure that people who used garden sprinkers paid for the
privilege.
Mr Douglas said of the water-saving measures proposed for England and
Wales: ''We are a long way from considering such things in Scotland
because the Lord has blessed us with plentiful water and our forefathers
have blessed us by being sagacious in what they did.''
He added: ''If any such proposals came from the authorities in
Scotland, I would want to take a long, lingering look at anything like
that. My responsibility is to protect the consumers.
''The ethos of the water industry in Scotland has a different thrust.
Water is still in the public domain here. South of the Border, it has
been privatised: that would happen in Scotland over my dead body.''
</TEXT>
