<HEADLINE>Council warned of budget overruns</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACCALMAN, MUNICIPAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765124</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MEMBERS of the new City of Glasgow Council were told yesterday that
the #79m shortfall in its finances could result in some departments
exceeding Government guidelines by between 20% and 33%.
The #79m shortfall between the Government's estimate of grant-aided
expenditure and the city council's notional budget could in theory send
council tax bills soaring by up to 70% unless the Government provides
more resources.
Every department of the new authority would exceed the Government's
estimate if current levels of service were to be maintained, but some
would find their budgets going right through the roof.
Worst affected would be leisure and recreation, whose notional budget
of #46m would be 32.76% above illustrative grant-aided expenditure --
the amount the Government considers a local authority should spend on
relevant services.
Libraries, museums and art galleries (#22m) would be over by 31.92%,
cleansing (#30m) by 25.67%, while the strategically vital roads and
transportation budget (#49m) would be 20.12% over.
The biggest spending departments -- education (#284m) and social work
(#175m) would be over by 8.23% and 9.52% respectively, while the police
(#117m) and fire (#22m) budgets would exceed the guidelines by 4.85% and
9.9%.
Leader of the new authority that assumes power next spring, Councillor
Robert Gould, said the Government had to be reminded of its promises
that the reorganisation of local government would be carried through
smoothly without detriment to services.
He said: ''We're not arguing for someone else's money. We're arguing
for Glasgow's money. We're asking for fairness. We're arguing in terms
of needs to provide the services that's required.''
Deputy leader, Councillor Des McNulty, explained: ''We're running an
#80m gap between the services presently provided in Glasgow and the
notional allocation, which is a formula that the Government has
produced.
''All we're saying to the Government is that this formula doesn't
reflect the actual cost of services as they stand in Glasgow. It's not
something the Government should have any problem in altering if they
follow their own logic.''
</TEXT>
