<HEADLINE>Blaze tragedy mother marries</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976765125</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE mother who lost five of her children in a house fire earlier this
month was married yesterday in an emotional ceremony.
Ms Mandy Davies, 34, who broke both legs escaping the fire, sat
weeping quietly in a wheelchair decked with satin bows as she married Mr
Dennis Deverey, 63, at Wrexham Registry Office.
Although she cried during the eight-minute civil ceremony, Ms Davies
smiled afterwards and said: ''I am happier now. We had planned to marry
next month but, because of the horrible things that have happened, we
needed to be closer together.''
Mr Deverey said: ''After this tragedy, we decided to get married here
and now. We shall benefit from being bonded closer together.''
Ms Davies was injured when she jumped from a bedroom window as fire
engulfed her home in Hightown, Wrexham, on August 10.
The blaze claimed the lives of Philip Foulkes, seven, and his
eight-year-old brother Matthew, both from her first marriage, and her
three-year-old twins, Stephen and Robert Davies, by Dennis.
Sarah Foulkes, 12, suffered severe burns in the blaze and died in
hospital last Thursday. Sarah's best friend, 12-year-old Louise Jones
from Hightown, Wrexham, also died in the blaze.
The other victim, 18-month-old Heather Davies, remains critically ill
in hospital after a five-hour skin graft operation. Arrangements are
being made for the couple to stay at the hospital where Heather's
treatment could last six months. Mr Deverey said: ''Our thoughts are
with her now.''
After a small family reception in Wrexham Miners Institute, Mrs
Deverey returned to hospital at Wrexham.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
