<HEADLINE>Meek is dropped by group on constitution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765126</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LEADING Scots Tory Brian Meek, a part-time adviser to Scottish
Secretary Michael Forsyth, has been dropped from a think-tank set up to
study constitutional change.
Mr Meek, who has never made a secret of his pro-devolution views,
received a letter from the Scotland Consultative Group of the
Constitution Unit telling him his services were no longer required.
He was invited to join three months ago but had yet to attend a
meeting.
It is believed the unit decided to drop him because it was worried
that his appointment would have given the discussion group a political
flavour.
Mr Meek, a Herald columnist, described the decision to remove him from
the London-based group set up with the financial backing of the
charitable Nuffield Foundation as ''a little cowardly and slightly
insulting''.
However, he said he would not be losing any sleep over the decision.
Mr Meek was one of several public figures invited to join the group.
Among the others approached were Gavin McCrone, of Glasgow University,
and Sir William Kerr Fraser, a former Permanent Secretary at the
Scottish Office.
Last night, Mr Meek said: ''The decision is a little cowardly. Also I
find it slightly insulting that one day I am acceptable to be part of
the group and the next day I am not.
''I have been political all my life and they knew that when they
appointed me.
''I didn't think there was anything particularly secret about the
discussions and I believe they could have benefitted from an alternative
voice.
''In the letter they sent me telling me I wasn't needed, they asked me
to recommend somebody else. Suffice to say, I will not be recommending
anybody, not even my worst enemy.''
No-one from the unit, set up to work on details of constitutional
change in the expectation of a change of government, was available for
comment last night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
