<HEADLINE>Boy Scout leader hurt in 150ft fall</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976765127</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOUT leader was badly injured yesterday when he fell more than
150ft down a steep mountain in the west Highlands.
Mr David Holt, 47, of Hastings, Sussex, was leading a troop of 11 Boy
Scouts, including two of his sons, up the side of Beinn Alligin, Wester
Ross, when he slipped and fell.
Torridon Mountain Rescue Team rescued the leader and a Sea King
helicopter from RAF Lossiemouth, on a training detachment at Kyle of
Lochalsh, was diverted to the scene and winched the man to safety.
He was flown to Raigmore Hospital, Inverness, where he was treated and
detained suffering from serious head and back injuries.
The Scout leader fell on a well-known route up the mountain to the
Horns of Alligin.
His Scout group are camping half a mile from Torridon Youth Hostel.
Beinn Alligin, the mountain of beauty, has three summits, all above
2800ft, the largest peak being Sgurr Mhor which is at 3232ft.
The Scout group last night stayed in Glen Torridon with two other
Scout leaders. They are due to return home on Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
